<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Reax 4thLd-writethru a0805 02-10 0878</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Reax, 4th Ld-writethru, a0805,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats React Warily to Bush Budget Message</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Edits throughout to raise higher some GOP comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats reacted warily Thursday
as President Bush began to spell out a budget based on his campaign
promises, criticizing him for vagueness and vowing to reject any tax
changes that favor the wealthy. But predictably, Republican praised
Bush's speech.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, invited Bush's budget
officials to Capitol Hill for consultations next week, and said ``we
are ready to meet with President Bush any time he wishes and seek
common solutions.''
   But Wright signaled that certain things would be off the table,
such as cuts in Medicare and tax changes favoring upper-income
taxpayers. And he put the onus on Bush to address homelessness, the
trade deficit, the war on drugs and poor math and science scores
among U.S. students, all of which he portrayed as legacies of the
Reagan administration. ``America can do better than that,'' Wright
said.
   Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said Bush had extended a
cooperative hand to Capitol Hill. ``Congress can swat it away, or it
can grasp the President's hand in the true spirit of cooperation,''
he said. He called Bush's plan was ``not the final answer, it's a
starting point.''
   Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, the senior Republican on the
House Budget Committee, said Bush's budget was ``faithful to the
campaign pledges'' he made last year, although Frenzel predicted
that advocates of education, the environment, day care and aid to
the homeless would complain that they got less than was needed.
   ``The Bush budget is a tough one giving first priority to deficit
reduction,'' Frenzel said in a statement. ``It will be subject to
lots of negotiation, but it is an important step toward a deficit
solution.''
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., welcomed
Bush's emphasis on what he termed neglected social programs, but
added: ``Unfortunately, President Bush gave us a minimum down
payment on his `kinder, gentler America,' with no clear indication
of how he intends to make the necessary annual payments.''
   Bush continued the Reagan administration's practice of using
unrealistic economic assumptions to pretend that the deficit is
smaller, Sasser charged. And the president painted an optimistic
picture, but ``shunned the responsibility for telling us what the
sacrifices will be and who will make them,'' he said.
   ``Overall, the Bush budget outline does not meet the rigorous
economic demands of this moment in America's history,'' said Sasser.
``It gives the illusion of deficit reduction without decisively
addressing the deficit problem.''
   Wright, too, hinted that he would look to the administration for
more than small symbolic steps to fulfill promises to protect the
environment, aid education and fight drugs.
   ``We know, and you know that these goals cannot be achieved by
words alone, or by symbolic gestures,'' Wright said in a Democratic
counterpoint to Bush's nationally televised budget speech. ``They
require money.''
   In his remarks, Wright pointed to some Democratic priorities for
the year, including an increase in the minimum wage, employer-paid
health insurance for all workers, boosting the share of cleanup
costs paid by polluters and reining in the wave of leveraged
corporate buyouts.
   Earlier, in a speech at the National Press Club, House Ways and
Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., promised to fight
Bush's call for a cut in the tax rate on capital gains to 15
percent, reflecting the views of many Democrats that such a break
unfairly favors the rich.
   ``I'm not about to tell the wage earners in Chicago that they
should pay a higher tax than stockbrokers,'' Rostenkowski said.
   Wright, for his part, said, ``We would have to reject any kind of
`flexible freeze' that would bend with flexibility for the rich and
powerful but freeze out the middle income families of America.''
   But both Wright and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who shared the
stage for the Democrats' televised response, avoided any sharp
disagreements with Bush on specific programs. ``We want to give him
a chance to be heard,'' Wright said.
   But some Republicans were almost as wary as the Democrats. ``It's
not immediately apparent how all those initiatives are going to be
paid for, even with the defense freeze,'' said Sen. Gordon J.
Humphrey, R-N.H.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said
while Bush's call for cooperation was welcome, he left many
questions unanswered.
   ``Many of the tough choices on deficit reduction were put off for
another day,'' he said, adding that he and Sasser would meet with
Bush Budget Director Richard Darman next week to quiz him about
budget specifics.
   In his response, Bentsen echoed the theme of his losing 1988
campaign for vice president, saying Democrats ``will be guided by a
set of enduring values. At the top of that list is good jobs at good
pay.''
   And he picked up Bush's competitiveness theme, noting that
American workers are no longer the best paid in the world and that
the nation is suffering from technological competition from its
allies.
   ``It's all very well to say, `read my lips,''' Bentsen said in a
reference to Bush's oft-quoted anti-tax pledge. ``Japanese computer
companies tell customers: `Read my chips.' It's effective. Even the
Pentagon buys Japanese microchips.''
</TEXT>
