<FIRST>r a PM-East57th     02-10 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East 57th,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>On East 57th Street, An Upturned Nose For The Ginza</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailers on the second-costliest shopping street
in the world carried on with their accustomed snobbery, hoisting a
nose at news they've been supplanted for the top spot.
   ``We get the cream of the world coming to this street,'' said
Michael Bishop, manager of Burberry's, a British clothier at 9 E.
57th in midtown Manhattan. ``The Ginza may have a higher price, but
there's no comparison in clientele.''
   The Ginza, in Tokyo, demolished East 57th Street in the latest
survey of retail rents, scoring an astronomical average of $650 per
square foot per year. East 57th, the leader last year, was second at
$435 per square foot.
   ``They are taking over,'' said a horrified saleswoman at Guy
Laroche, a dress shop on East 57th between Park and Madison.
   But others interviewed on Thursday took the news in stride.
   At Giorgio Beverly Hills, a boutique at No. 47, manager Randall
Hemming purred his standard customer greeting _ ``Would you like a
martini?'' _ and extolled his store's location.
   ``The whole reason for being here is prestige,'' he said. ``If
you look at the shops on 57th from Fifth to Park, you're looking at
the entire world.''
   At least, a select slice of it. Store windows, starting with a
glittering bang at Tiffany's on the corner of Fifth Avenue, boast a
mind-boggling array of jewel encrustments, haute couture, master
artworks and fine antiques.
   Inside any door, the ambience is genteel in the extreme. Floors
are thickly carpeted, rooms tastefully furnished. Salespeople hover
discreetly, often far outnumbering the shoppers. Cash registers
operate soundlessly.
   You can drop $65 for a tie at Chanel, $120 for a wool scarf at
Burberry's, $900 for a cashmere running suit at Giorgio. At
Ackermann Galleries, packed with 18th-century English furniture,
things are a bit more dear.
   ``A single piece here may go for 24 or 25. While not a lot of
people come in off the street, one designer can spend 100 pretty
easily,'' said salesman John Vlachos. He was talking thousands.
   The serene Ackermann's, though, is a relic of bygone days on 57th
Street, where antique shops and fine art galleries reigned for
decades. ``There are so few of us left,'' sighed Vlachos. ``The
rents have killed people.''
   Bishop, at Burberry's, didn't want to discuss his rent. He did
want to discuss his space _ four floors, 1,500 square feet each; his
staff _ 25 salespeople and a stable of Italian-trained tailors; and
his merchandise.
   ``The Japanese customer shops more in here than he does in the
Ginza. They have a love affair with our quality goods,'' he said. In
the Ginza, he didn't mind adding, the shops are small and the
street's in a perpetual traffic jam.
   ``In the Ginza, it's unbelievable. There's no room,'' Bishop
said. ``If Japan was a bigger island, then it would be a different
story.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Mofford     02-10 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mofford,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mofford Reaches First Anniversary As Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after she took over Arizona's top job from
Evan Mecham, Gov. Rose Mofford says she has brought ``stability'' to
the state and plans to run for a full term, but some critics suggest
she's in over her head.
   The 66-year-old Democrat, who often refers to herself as
Arizona's mother and is instantly recognized by her beehive hairdo,
has found it tough adjusting from the popularity that went with her
largely ceremonial position of secretary of state to the controversy
that goes with being chief executive.
   She has tried to quiet those voices with such bold proposals as
$255 million in new taxes to balance a $3.35 billion budget, on top
of the $180 million tax increase she approved last summer. She also
has stood up to controversy by vetoing measures approved by
lawmakers.
   Mrs. Mofford became acting governor when Mecham, the first-term
Republican elected to the post in 1986, was impeached a year ago
this week. He was convicted and removed from office in April, and
she became governor.
   Mrs. Mofford's supporters attribute what they acknowledge as her
slow start to that turmoil.
   ``They sort of hit the ground without any time to get
organized,'' said Bill Jamieson, a former Cabinet chief to
Democratic Gov. Bruce Babbitt, Mecham's predecessor. ``It's like
changing the tires of a truck while it's still going down the
highway.''
   But others see deeper problems, saying Mrs. Mofford lacks
self-confidence and is hurting herself by her reluctance to explain
herself to lawmakers, the news media and the public.
   ``I don't have a theory on what is bedeviling this
administration, but clearly, at this point, it cannot be labeled a
smashing success,'' said Jack LaSota, a former state attorney
general and Babbitt chief of staff.
   ``She's in way over her head,'' said Republican Senate President
Robert Usdane.
   ``Rose's problem is that she is so unsure of herself,'' said Rep.
Peter Goudinoff, a Tucson Democrat and professor of political
science at the University of Arizona.
   Still, Goudinoff said he sees government moving forward after
years of inertia in during the lame-duck period of the Babbitt
adminstration and Mecham's crippled, shortened term.
   Mrs. Mofford and top aides declined to be interviewed about the
first year and what comes next, but she said Monday that her major
accomplishments have been ``the staff I was able to assemble and the
appointments I have made.''
   ``I think stability has been brought back to the state,'' she
added. She plans to run for a full term next year.
   She remains popular with voters, though the level of satisfaction
has ebbed a bit. A Behavior Research Center survey of 713 state
residents in early January found 40 percent rated her good or
excellent, compared with 45 percent in a similar survey in July.
Thirty-one percent rated her fair, the same as in July, but 14
percent saw her as poor or very poor, up slightly from 11 percent in
July. The pollsters said their margin of error was plus or minus 3.4
percent.
   Politicians say journalists have treated Mrs. Mofford more gently
than they did Mecham. But there have been some embarrassments during
her first year.
   Reporters found that while secretary of state and in charge of
financial disclosure regulations, she had failed to list property,
loans and income on the same disclosure forms that got Mecham in
trouble.
   They also found that over five years as secretary of state she
had spent at least $50,000 in state funds on gifts to visiting
dignitaries and office decorations while telling the public she paid
for such things herself.
   Even ribbon-cutting and making speeches, a favorite Mofford
pastime, turned sour when she fell from a platform at a speech and
suffered a concussion. She worked a limited schedule for weeks
afterward.
   Ken Smith, Mecham's last press secretary, says Mofford aides are
smart to keep her away from most media contact because ``she does
not cope well with those kinds of stressful situations.''
   Mrs. Mofford's few news conferences have been short.
   Reporters _ and the public _ have had difficulty getting answers
to such questions as how she feels about restricting abortion or
reinstating Arizona's death penalty in the wake of a court decision
invalidating it. Some newspapers have dubbed her the ``stealth
governor.''
   Yet in addition to showing courage by proposing new taxes, Mrs.
Mofford won praise for vetoing a bill giving the state's largest
telephone company a tax break. More controversial were her vetoes of
a measure that would have allowed communities to set their own
obscenity standards instead of relying on a statewide standard and
one that would have made it a felony for people who know they have
AIDS to have sex without telling the partner.
   ``She's not a caretaker at all,'' said state health director Ted
Williams, who has served five governors in a variety of posts. ``Any
time I have any questions, any time I want any policy clarified, she
has been there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
