<FIRST>r a PM-Cheese-Hair     02-10 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheese-Hair,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Marshals Find Hair-Adulterated Cheese in Kraft Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ULM, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials seized 830 cases of Kraft
cheese slices from a manufacturing plant here after a routine
inspection uncovered animal hair in one sample.
   The confiscation of the Kraft Deluxe American Slices was ordered
by the U.S. attorney's office in Minneapolis after the FDA found
three hairs in a sample, said Jay Allen, acting director of the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration's compliance branch in Minneapolis.
   ``Once we find a violation, we seize the entire lot,'' he said
Thursday.
   Laboratory analysis determined one of the hairs was that of a
dog, Allen said. Test results were not conclusive on the other two
hairs, but they did not belong to humans.
   Allen said that finding hair in cheese produced in the United
States ``doesn't happen a lot.''
   ``It's really hard to say how it (the hair) got in there,'' said
Tom Nelson, consumer affairs officer at the FDA in Minneapolis.
   Kathy Knuth, a spokeswoman for Kraft Inc. in Glenview, Ill., said
marshals tagged the cheese and left it at the plant. None of the
cheese in the lot had reached the market, she said.
   ``We've never had a consumer complaint'' of hair in cheese, Knuth
said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mary Jo Madigan said Kraft can appeal the
confiscation order. If the company does not challenge the order, the
cheese will be destroyed, she said.
   Knuth said Kraft has not decided whether to challenge the order.
She said the FDA inspection occurred in mid-December but the company
never received a written explanation of the inspection findings.
   ``Despite our request for test results, we've received no
documentation,'' she said. ``We don't know what the situation is
right now.''
   Madigan said the FDA will not seek any damages, fines or other
penalties against Kraft.
</TEXT>
