<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WrightText 3Takes   02-10 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Text, 3 Takes,0396</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of remarks by House
Speaker Jim Wright Thursday night.
   For 200 years this nation has given every new president its hand
and its help and a chance to lead.
   Senator Lloyd Bentsen and I are here tonight to tell you that the
Democratic Congress wants to work with this president in every way
that we can. We'll give him our sincere cooperation. That does not
mean obedience. It does mean our honest help and our very best
advice.
   In world affairs, Democrats in Congress are committed to seeking
true bipartisanship in all areas of America's foreign policy. As we
deal with other nations of the world, friend or foe, Americans
should stand as one.
   America struggles today to overcome three enormous deficits _ the
budget deficit, the trade deficit, and the social deficit which
results from our prolonged underinvestment in such things as public
education and industrial modernization.
   These deficits have been feeding on one another in a vicious way.
In just the short time it took us to hear Mr. Bush make his speech
tonight, the public debt was increasing by about $15 million. That
much is added to our children's bill every 50 minutes.
   As the debt skyrocketed during the past decade, the trade deficit
grew, and our standard of living began to fall for the first time in
modern recollection.
   Instead of employing Americans making goods to sell abroad _ and
lending money to those who buy our goods _ we've been buying things
that others make _ and borrowing from them to pay for it. And to pay
for our borrowing, we've been selling off little pieces of America.
Foreign interests own a bigger and bigger slice of this country. And
that's not good enough.
   We have seen the gap grow wider between the rich and the poor in
our own country, and average American families today are finding it
harder, not easier, to pay for such necessary things as housing and
health care and higher education for our children.
   As we sit in our warm homes right now, gazing at our television
sets, some things are easy to forget. I ask you to remember when you
go to bed this evening that 3 million of our fellow countrymen are
homeless tonight.
</TEXT>
