<FIRST>r i PM-PoorHealth     02-10 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poor Health,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Less Than One In Three Czechs Is Considered Healthy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said less
than a third of Czechs surveyed can be considered healthy, and an
official newspaper blamed poor nutrition and ``bad living.''
   The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo in its Thursday article
quoted Josef Podstata, a deputy minister of health care and social
affairs of the Czech Socialist Republic, as citing a ``selective
investigation in 1986'' that disclosed 669 chronic diseases per
1,000 inhabitants.
   The article did not say how many people were surveyed and no
figures were given on the health situation in Slovakia, the other
major region of Czechoslovakia.
   ``One citizen out of four dies of cardiovascular diseases and one
out of four due to malignant tumors,'' the paper said on the most
frequent causes of death in the Czech Republic.
   ``There is no doubt a role is played here by the bad living and
working environment and nutrition, i.e. lack of foodstuffs that
would correspond to requirments of good nutrition,'' Podstata was
quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
