<FIRST>r w PM-WrightText-2ndAdd     02-10 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Text - 2nd Add,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: we will.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Working together Congress will pass a clean air bill this year to
protect that precious commodity upon which all human life depends.
   A kinder, gentler America? That's old time Democratic religion.
We embrace it enthusiastically!
   We know, and you know, that these goals cannot be achieved by
words alone, or by symbolic gestures. They require money _ the
commitment of resources sufficient to win the battle against these
common enemies.
   On the question of how these vital initiatives will be paid for,
the Democrats in Congress will insist on fairness.
   We would have to reject any kind of ``flexible freeze'' that
would bend with flexibility for the rich and powerful but freeze out
the middle income families of America.
   We will oppose attempts to cut Medicare.
   We are ready to meet with President Bush any time he wishes and
seek common solutions. Our House Budget Committee will begin its
formal hearings in just a few days. The president's representatives
are invited. We are determined to complete our work on time, and
pass our appropriations bills on time, again this year _ just as we
did last year.
   We do have limited resources and urgent challenges. But you know
there are some things we can do without spending public money.
   We must raise the minimum wage, held down for eight long years _
because those who work honestly for wages in America must never
receive less than they would on welfare.
   We can ask that polluters pay more of the cost of cleaning up the
poisons which they create and from which they profit.
   We must encourage American corporations to reinvest in America _
in plants and factories and jobs and strength, not in leveraged
buyouts and paper profits.
   We should require that corporations insure the health of their
employees _ so that the hard-earned family savings of a decade or
more cannot be just wiped out by the single illness of a child.
   When it comes to shaping a kinder, gentler, fairer nation the
real test is not whether we have the words but whether we have the
will. For ultimately we will be judged by what we have done.
   In the years ahead, long after this night is forgotten and the
phrases have faded and our page of history has turned, let it be
said of us that we have refreshed America's sense of common concern;
that we renewed America's basic strength; that together we reached
out for America's future and put our faith and our investment in the
American people.
   In our earnest efforts to help the new president build this
future, the House and Senate will work together. The Senate
Democratic majority is represented tonight by the chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee _ our recent nominee for vice president of
the United States _ Senator Lloyd Bentsen.
</TEXT>
