<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BentsenText 2Takes   02-10 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bentsen Text, 2 Takes,0655</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of remarks by Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen Thursday night.
   My friends, George Bush and I have had our battles but we've been
on the same side too _ as far back as 45 years ago. We were both
young men, bomber pilots, defending the cause of freedom. There's
nothing like the first puffs of anti-aircraft fire to teach a flight
crew about the need to work together.
   Tonight, we're together again. Democrats and Republicans may
disagree on tactics. But we have the same destination in mind _ a
strong, free, prosperous America.
   There's a lot we can do together. Because we have worked as a
team, America is stronger militarily. President Reagan achieved a
major nuclear arms reduction treaty. That's good.
   My old colleague, the late Scoop Jackson, once said that in
foreign policy ``the best politics is no politics.'' I agree.
Democrats won't play politics with matters of war and peace.
Remember: that military build-up was enacted with lots of Democratic
votes. Democrats know how to work as a team. We've done it.
   That doesn't mean we won't disagree. There'll be sharp,
principled disagreements among Democrats and Republicans over one of
the greatest challenges America has ever faced.
   Because today our great industrial heartland is under attack. Not
from foreign military forces. From new technology. From foreign
competition _ often from our allies.
   You see the evidence everywhere. You see it in ships pulling up
to American docks loaded not with immigrants but with Volkswagens.
You see it in the living rooms of America _ in those VCRs so many of
you tonight have sitting beside the TV set. None of those VCRs are
made in America _ not one! It's all very well to say: read my lips.
Japanese computer companies tell customers: read my chips. It's
effective; even the Pentagon buys Japanese microchips.
   The result? We're losing good jobs. And that hurts the very
fabric of America. A few months ago, in Dawson, Ga., after two
plants closed wiping out 2,000 jobs, a high school class was asked
where they would settle after graduation. Only two out of 20 wanted
to stay in Dawson. At the beginning of this decade our workers had
the highest average income in the world. Today that distinction
belongs to the West Germans and the Japanese.
   Is it inevitable that we lose to Japan _ or the other Pacific rim
countries? Or Europe united by 1992? Should kids growing up in
Dawson, Ga., settle for a second-class economy dependent on the
goods of others?
   I don't buy that. America is a country of great strength. We can
take charge of our economic future.
   But to do that we're going to have to be more productive. You
can't have a vacuum tube outlook for the age of microchips. We'll
have to get tough with those countries whose trade practices are
unfair _ we deserve a level playing field. And we'll have to face
some hard facts.
   Example: Under the last administration we became the largest
debtor nation in history. Last year our trade deficit was $150
billion. That's cost us 500,000 manufacturing jobs.
   Example: The last administration rolled up more debt than every
administration from George Washington to Jimmy Carter combined. This
year one out of every seven federal dollars _ another $150 billion _
will go just to pay interest on that debt.
   We don't oppose foreign investment. But why should the money from
average taxpayers go to pay off bonds owned by rich bondholders,
whether from Tokyo _ or Palm Beach? How can we stay competitive _
how can we even preserve Social Security _ when we saddle ourselves
and our children with such a debt? It's like putting lead weights on
Michael Jordan's legs and asking him to slam dunk anyway.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MORE</HEAD>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BentsenText-1stAdd     02-10 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bentsen Text - 1st Add,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: dunk anyway.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Frankly, I don't think Republicans have faced up to these twin
towers of debt _ or some other problems.
   Education: Right now 25 percent of our youngsters won't finish
high school. Twenty-five million Americans can't read the warning
label on a bottle of poison. The Army uses comic books for
instruction manuals: there's a five-page comic to explain how to
release the hood of a jeep.
   How are we going to stay competitive that way? We have to cure
adult illiteracy. We must train Americans for the sophisticated jobs
of the 1990s.
   The environment: We have to send a message to polluters, whether
they dump PCBs into our river beds, or fluorocarbons into the
atmosphere. We have to tell them the free ride is over; that we want
air we can breathe and water safe to drink.
   And let's send a message to those who think they can fly light
planes loaded with cocaine across our southern borders _ or sell
crack in the schoolyards of New York and Chicago. The message to
drug dealers and criminals is this: you can't hide behind smart
lawyers. We won't plea bargain away our rights. We'll find you.
We'll catch you. And we'll put you away.
   A few years ago, Yelena Bonner, the Soviet dissident, visited
America. ``Americans don't want war,'' she wrote. ``They want a
house.''
   She's right. But it's becoming harder and harder to find housing
_ not just for the homeless but for those who grew up in homes and
want to buy one for their families. For the first time in four
decades the homeownership rate is declining in America. I meet lots
of young couples who've simply had to move in with mom and dad.
They'd like to be on their own.
   And mom and dad think that's a good idea, too.
   Finally, ethics: Do we really want Korean companies getting
favors from influence peddling ex-administration officials? Or
racketeers in New York getting contracts from cronies of an attorney
general? It's one thing to have a government that's a friend to
business. It's quite another to have one that just wants business
for its friends.
   George Bush is right, there is a new breeze blowing through
Washington. But don't expect us to stand with our fingers in the air
to see which way that breeze is blowing. We Democrats will work with
President Bush, but we will be guided by a set of enduring values.
At the top of the list is good jobs at good pay. We want American
workers to be the best paid in the world _ just as they were eight
years ago.
   You know, I've been around a long time. But in the last few weeks
my thoughts have often turned to a man who was around even longer _
in fact for almost half the history of our country.
   He was born dirt-poor. His parents were homesteaders on the
plains of South Dakota in a sod house. When that first blizzard blew
in, the family took turns staying awake during one 36-hour stretch,
burning bundles of straw so they wouldn't freeze to death.
   They made it through the storm. They lived. My father worked
hard. He prospered. And last fall, shortly before his death, he had
the privilege of seeing his son campaign for vice president of the
United States.
   I wish we'd done a little better for him.
   Still, my friends, in the story of Lloyd Bentsen Sr., lies the
promise of America. It's a reminder that this country allows those
who believe in hard work _ and teamwork _ to succeed, whether
sodbusting during a South Dakota winter . . . or as president.
   At this moment, when President Bush has announced his flight plan
for the years ahead, we Democrats in the co-pilot's seat say: let's
work hard _ together _ to keep America strong _ not just in planes
and tanks, but in the factory, in the farmhouse, and in the
schoolhouse. We'll make sure that when our children look back on the
last years of the 20th century, they'll say we did the job: we kept
the American dream alive.
   Thank you, and God bless you.
</TEXT>
