<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     02-10 0916</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public-Private Scenic Byways Program Wins Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has officially given
the green light to a ``scenic byways'' promotion by the Plymouth
division of Chrysler Motors but is shying away from endorsing the
company's products.
   A three-way partnership was worked out with the California-based
Forest Education Foundation, Plymouth and USDA to help upgrade
designated scenic stretches of highways into major tourist
attractions.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said Thursday the
191 million acres of national forests _ if gathered in one place, an
area larger than Texas _ offer ``some of America's most spectacular
scenery.''
   ``This partnership will allow us to showcase the beauty of these
areas for the American public, nearly half of whom spend part of
their leisure time driving for enjoyment,'' he said.
   Robertson told a news conference the venture is the first major
national effort undertaken by his agency with a private corporation.
The agreement is for three years and could be renewed.
   He said the Forest Service's involvement with Plymouth and the
foundation is strictly on behalf of the byways program and that the
company ``will not be using our logo'' on any of its products or
receive any endorsement by the agency.
   But Robertson and Pat Smorra, general marketing manager for
Plymouth, dodged reporters' questions about details of the financial
arrangement between the agency and the company.
   Smorra said that he was ``not announcing the exact dollars we're
putting into (the program), but it is extensive in terms of
communication efforts, as well as promotional efforts.''
   Robertson said the budget proposed for the Forest Service in the
1990 fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, calls for $1.5 million for
``challenge cost-share projects'' including the byways program.
   ``So we would anticipate at least that amount in 1990 _ and
perhaps some more of our budget _ going into it,'' he said.
   The funds call for matching dollars, at least, from approved
participants to carry out the cost-share projects.
   ``There is some up-front cash from Plymouth, but I'm not free to
say (how much) right now,'' Robertson said.
   The scenic byways program began last year with the designation of
a 26-mile stretch of U.S. Highway 64 in southeastern Tennessee. So
far, 30 have been designated, covering 1,676 miles, and others are
being identified for addition to the system.
   One goal is to upgrade the highway areas to make them more useful
and entertaining for motorists. Projects can include interpretive
signs, improved road maintenance, pullouts at scenic overlooks,
parking areas, some rest area facilities and short-loop walking
trails.
   According to an information folder by the non-profit foundation,
Plymouth will publicize the byways through ``an ambitious
promotional program which includes 20 exhibitions at heavily
attended regional consumer shows, discreet signage in 3,500 Plymouth
dealerships, and in 700 high-traffic retail locations and ski
areas.''
   The promotion also includes a national sweepstakes with a
Plymouth as grand prize.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
600,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat under an Agriculture Department
export subsidy program.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said Thursday the wheat
was part of an authorization of more than 2 million tons under the
Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Goldthwait said the wheat is for shipment in March. Counting some
left over from a previous EEP arrangement and 2 million tons
authorized Jan. 25, the Soviets have more than 1.4 million tons
still available under the program.
   With the latest sale, the Soviet Union has bought about 2.6
million tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a long-term
supply agreement, which was extended last fall to run through Dec.
31, 1990.
   A metric tons is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 600,000 tons are equal to about 22 million bushels
worth around $90 million at recent U.S. farm prices.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also
included about 10.2 million tons of corn, along with 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 508,900 tons of
grain sorghum.
   Goldthwait said the 600,000 tons of wheat were sold by Ferruzzi,
USA Inc., 100,000 tons; Continental Grain Co., 250,000; Louis
Dreyfus Corp., 200,000; and Central States Enterprises Inc., 50,000.
   The companies will get subsidy of $23.01 per ton, or about 63
cents per bushel, under the EEP arrangement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's orange harvest for the 1988-89
season is estimated by the Agriculture Department at about 215
million boxes, virtually unchanged from the previous forecast a
month ago but 7 percent more than last season.
   The Florida crop, based on Feb. 1 indications, was estimated
Thursday at 150 million boxes, unchanged from last month but 9
percent more than in 1987-88.
   California production was forecast at 61 million boxes, the same
as in January but 4 percent more than a year ago. The Arizona crop
was forecast at 2 million boxes, unchanged from January and up 10
percent from last season. The Texas harvest, at 1.85 million boxes,
was indicated at 6 percent more than the January forecast and up 29
percent from 1987-88.
</TEXT>
