<SECOND>PM-BRF--Video Targets,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Practice Shooting At Video Images</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgian state police will soon be taking
target practice at moving video images.
   Officials said Thursday the police corps will buy computerized
video equipment that will allow officers to practice shooting live
ammunition at moving pictures projected on a large screen of paper
or light cloth.
   Once hit, the images will freeze to show the accuracy of the aim.
   ``We are very progressive in this,'' said a police official.
   The official said the first of eight video machines to be used by
the state police should be installed by March.
   He said he did not know the cost of the equipment, which was
developed by the Browning Co., part of the Belgian arms producer
Fabrique Nationale Herstal SA.
