<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Education     02-10 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Education,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Leaders Say Bush Budget Better But Still Room to Improve</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's education budget makes good on
his campaign promises but falls short of matching inflation and
fails to restore cuts made under his predecessor.
   Bush, the would-be ``education president,'' is seeking $441
million more in Education Department spending authority than former
President Reagan had recommended. Most of the money would be used to
reward good schools and set up magnet schools, two ideas Bush pushed
on the campaign trail.
   But education officials, while welcoming Bush's initiatives and
his proposed $250 million increase in Head Start funding, also noted
the new president's budget would not save 24 programs Reagan asked
Congress to kill.
   And they said that even with the extra money Bush has proposed,
the increase is about $360 million short of what would be needed to
keep pace with inflation of about 4.2 percent.
   ``Funds have been moved around and a few dollars have been added,
but we're still dealing with the status quo, a maintenance level
budget,'' said Mary Futrell, president of the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teacher union.
   The federal education budget would go from $21.9 billion this
year to $22.5 billion in fiscal 1990 under the Bush plan, according
to unofficial department estimates. Of the $441 million sought by
Bush, less than $100 million would actually be spent in fiscal 1990.
   The major Bush education initiative is $250 million for a merit
schools program designed to reward schools with safe environments,
high-achieving students and low dropout rates. Grants would average
about $100,000 per school. Special emphasis would be given to
schools serving disadvantaged children. If Congress approved the
program, about $30 million would actually be spent in fiscal 1990.
Outlays would rise to $593 million by 1993.
   Bush is also asking Congress to authorize $100 million for magnet
schools offering specialized curriculum with an emphasis on math and
science and on recognizing the potential of children from
disadvantaged families. Outlays in fiscal 1990 would come to $12
million. The Education Department already runs a $115 million magnet
school program, but the money is available only for desegregation
purposes.
   Bush also called for a $250 million increase for Head Start, the
preschool enrichment program operated by the Department of Health
and Human Services. The program, now receiving slightly over $1.2
billion, currently serves about 20 percent of eligible low-income
children.
   Other education proposals include emergency grants to
drug-infested urban schools; endowment grants to historically black
colleges and universities; science scholarships and teacher awards;
grants to help homeless students and illiterate homeless adults;
money to make it easier for scientists, engineers and other
professionals become teachers and principals, and grants to schools
that experiment in a broad range of areas including curriculum,
management and teaching methods.
   Congress would have to approve all but the homeless programs, the
drug-free school grants and the endowment grants to black colleges.
   Under the Reagan and Bush plans, more than half of the $750
million saved by eliminating 24 programs would go to the Pell grant
program for needy college students and the Chapter 1 program for
disadvantaged schoolchildren.
   Congress has refused in the past to kill the programs Reagan and
Bush have targeted for extinction, which include Perkins or
campus-based direct loans; state student incentive grants that to
spur states to set up need-based scholarship programs, and some
impact aid, which goes to school districts with high enrollments or
low tax revenues due to federal activities.
   The combination of new ideas and old cuts left education
officials with a kinder view of the Bush administration but still
nursing the wounds of past budget battles.
   ``Certainly this is a different administration than the one we
had before. They show a positive inclination to try and do something
for education. There are some promising things,'' said Gerald
Morris, a lobbyist for the American Federation of Teachers and
president of a coalition called Committee for Education Funding.
   ``But the additional investment in Chapter 1 will come at the
expense of other programs,'' Morris added. ``That's the other side
of the coin.''
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House Education
and Labor Committee, said Bush's budget does not stem ``the serious
erosion of education spending that has occurred over the past eight
years.'' He called the plan ``a framework for future discussion and
I look forward to helping the president do a better job of making
good on his campaign pledges.''
</TEXT>
