<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Farm     02-10 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Farm,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>$2 Billion Farm Cut `Unreasonable,' House Chairman Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan to cut $2 billion in farm
payments next year as a way of mopping up red budget ink makes
``unreasonable demands on agriculture,'' says the top farm lawmaker
in the House.
   ``We in agriculture are prepared to make a fair contribution,''
Agriculture Committee Chairman E. (Kika) de la Garza, D-Texas, said
Thursday night. ``But this administration is asking us to take cuts
which represent considerably more than our share of the
budget-balancing burden.''
   His comments came as Bush delivered to Congress a speech about
his fiscal 1990 budget which called for something similar to the
sweeping farm cuts proposed a month ago by an outgoing President
Reagan.
   Reagan called for a 19 percent cut in overall Agriculture
Department spending, ranging from payments for crop producers to a
subsidy for school lunches for youngsters of families earning more
than $39,500 annually.
   Total USDA spending would have dropped from $52.1 billion
currently to $42.4 billion in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
Reagan proposed to cut farm payments by $2 billion in next year's
budget, but actually would only have reduced payments by $1.1
billion, paying $900 million to the farmers in the current fiscal
year.
   Bush's blueprint said current programs were put in place to
counter the farm crisis five years ago and noted that the farm
economy is now flourishing.
   ``It is now time to reform our farm programs and not wait until
the current farm bill expires two years hence,'' said Bush's budget
book. It said Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter would ``work
with the Congress to develop a specific set of initiatives designed
to reduce federal farm expenditures by $2 billion in 1990.''
   De la Garza said in a statement, however, that the Bush proposal
``still makes unreasonable demands on agriculture, which already has
given $30 billion in cuts from proposed budgets over the last eight
years.''
   The $30 billion figure did not represent rollbacks in actual
spending but included estimates of outlays under programs altered to
head off soaring costs.
   ``I would remind everyone that if we cut out the entire amount
proposed for agricultural spending, it would still make only an
almost infinitesimal impact on the total budget situation,'' de la
Garza said.
   Most lawmakers were waiting until the nitty-gritty of the Bush
blueprint became clearer before saying much about it.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, a power on
agriculture issues, met with reporters and pronounced himself
pleased that Bush ``touched on the farmers'' in his speech.
   Rep. Virginia Smith, R-Neb., a member of the House Appropriations
Committee, said she did scan some of the details and found to her
dismay that Bush's assumptions about current spending were at sharp
variance with those of his predecessor. She said that could force
down next year's levels.
   Tough negotiations are expected between the administration and
farm lawmakers wary over the reaction of farmers hammered by drought
last summer and fearing more of the same this year, she said.
   ``Ultimately, Mother Nature and the U.S. Congress will have the
last word,'' she added.
   Bush cuts actually would be double the automatic reductions that
would kick in under the Gramm-Rudman law if Congress failed to
reduce the deficit, according to Senate Agriculture Committee
Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
   ``An agricultural budget cutting twice as deep as the
Gramm-Rudman sequester is not a kinder and gentler budget,'' Leahy
said.
   He also said reducing farm payments would do nothing to pressure
America's trading partners to reduce their own agricultural
subsidies. Some lawmakers say the way to force down payments that
spur European Community farm exports is for America to retaliate
with huge subsidies of its own.
   Actually, U.S. subsidies are running at a level of about $13
billion annually, down from twice that amount only three years ago
when the government pulled out all the stops to get agricultural
exports moving and pump life into a farm economy that was wallowing
in the doldrums.
   Leahy said that when ``the 1990 Reagan budget was released, I
expressed my hope that it was designed to make Bush budget kinder
and gentler.''
   ``I also expressed my fear that the Reagan farm cuts would
undermine a tough U.S. negotiating position in the GATT talks,'' he
said, referring to efforts to reduce subsidies through changes in
the 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. ``I am very
disappointed that the Bush budget is neither kinder to the farmer
nor tougher on our competitors in the GATT negotiations.''
</TEXT>
