<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-NationalSecurity     02-10 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-National Security,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Reagan's Pentagon Budget Must Be Cut, But Specifics Few</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says former President Reagan's
Pentagon budget has to be cut, but he's leaving it up to his defense
secretary to figure out where the reductions will be made.
   That means it may be several weeks before there are any specifics
because the nomination of John Tower, Bush's choice as defense
secretary, is bogged down in questions about Tower's personal life
and financial dealings.
   Bush called on Thursday for Pentagon spending of $308.8 billion
in fiscal 1990, which would maintain defense spending at about the
current pace, allowing for inflation. The Pentagon is operating on a
$299.5 billion budget.
   The Bush plan is a 2 percent cut from the proposal sent to
Capitol Hill a month ago by Reagan. And Bush says he prefers the
Reagan version.
   ``The president would like to embrace, even for the short term,
the defense budget projections which are in the Reagan budget,''
Bush said in his budget message. ``Unfortunately, the current
economic situation requires defense budget savings.''
   The Bush plan is on target with the predictions of leaders of the
Democratic-controlled Congress, who said a month ago that the best
the Pentagon could hope for would be a budget which keeps pace with
inflation.
   There were few details in the Bush plan, outside his promise that
the National Security Council will review U.S. policy and defense
commitments over the next 90 days.
   Bush also promised to reform the weapons procurement system, but
offered no specifics. The system has been plagued for years by
inefficiency and cost overruns and now is the target of a Justice
Department criminal investigation of fraud.
   One reason for the lack of details in Bush's speech is Tower's
stalled nomination. Without Tower or any of the new top-level
defense team in place, the Pentagon has essentially been rudderless,
according to defense sources.
   Routine decisions are being made by hold-over officials from the
Reagan administration, but major decisions have been delayed until
there is a new defense secretary.
   Tower's nomination won't be voted upon by the Senate Armed
Services Committee for at least two weeks. That means that even if
he were confirmed by the full Senate, he couldn't take office until
late in February.
   But Tower has been advising Bush on defense issues and sat next
to the president Thursday in a Cabinet review of the defense budget.
He entered the House of Representatives with the rest of the Cabinet
to listen to Bush's nationally televised address.
   One decision that will have to be made quickly is whether to
build the single-warhead Midgetman nuclear-tipped missile or a
railroad-based version of the 10-warhead MX missile.
   Congressional Democrats favor Midgetman while Reagan backed the
rail-based MX. In a compromise last year, the current Pentagon
budget includes $350 million which can be used for research and
development of one missile or the other.
   But that budget includes a March 15 deadline for making the
decision. Unless Tower is confirmed soon, the decision may be made
by Brent Scowcroft, Bush's national security adviser and a supporter
of the Midgetman weapon. Scowcroft chaired a 1983 presidential
commission which recommended construction of hundreds of Midgetman
weapons.
   If Tower is confirmed, he may also seek cuts in Star Wars. The
current budget is $4.1 billion, and Reagan last month proposed to
increase the figure to $5.9 billion for the program known formally
as the Strategic Defense Initiative.
   Bush's budget plan called for ``the active pursuit'' of SDI, but
included no figures. Last month, Tower told senators at his
confirmation hearing there are still a large number of unanswered
questions about Star Wars.
   The president's message also urged ``a new partnership with this
nation's allies,'' particularly in Japan and Western Europe.
   Although Bush's proposal offered no specifics, the United States
has been pushing both Japan and the European members of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization to increase their contributions to
allied defenses.
</TEXT>
