<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ComaBaby Bjt   02-10 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coma Baby, Bjt,0681</SECOND>
<BYLINE>New Mother Celebrates Recovery From `Cerebral Death'</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto YAK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Blodgett kissed her newborn son as
she happily recalled that just two months ago, suffering from
``cerebral death,'' she became one of the few comatose women in
medical history to give birth.
   Since that time Mrs. Blodgett has made a recovery that has
confounded her doctors.
   On Thursday, she gazed at little Simon Alan Blodgett, stroked the
hair of her other son and nodded her head emphatically when asked if
she hoped for full recovery. She pointed to letters on a piece of
paper to spell out words.
   ``I felt wonderful,'' the 24-year-old woman spelled, when asked
her first response to seeing the newborn.
   Sitting in a wheelchair with her dark hair in a ponytail, she
watched her husband, David, feed the baby from a bottle. Then she
kissed the infant.
   One expert on head injuries speculates that Simon's birth on Dec.
9 may also have triggered his mother's return to consciousness
following a June 1988 auto accident.
   ``One of the things that occurs during birth is massive changes
in hormones,'' said Dr. Bill Blackerby, a specialist in head
injuries in suburban Nashville, Tenn. ``There could be some
relationship between hormonal changes taking place and in some way
maybe that triggered some sort of metabolic process to increase the
level of alertness.''
   Dr. Thomas Benedetti, who delivered the baby, said at the time of
birth that it was only the fourth such case in the world that he
could locate in medical records.
   Such a birth is so rare because any injury sufficient to cause a
coma likely will cause a miscarriage too, said Blackerby, a
physician at Rebound Corp., a private rehablition center for people
with head injuries.
   Coma-causing injuries are also commonly followed by respiratory
problems, which can kill a fetus, he said.
   Dr. Loren Winterscheid, medical director of Seattle's University
Hospital, said he doubts there is a connection between the birth and
return to consciousness.
   ``There is no way of knowing when or how much a patient in a coma
is going to recover,'' he said in a telephone interview from Seattle.
   Although Mrs. Blodgett was never diagnosed as brain dead,
hospital spokesman L.G. Blanchard described her condition as
``cerebral death.'' And her doctors did not hold much hope for her
recovery, Winterscheid said.
   But within a week after the birth, Mrs. Blodgett began to show
signs of coming out of the coma, doctors said. Since then, her
recovery has been steady.
   By mid-January, after returning home, she had regained limited
use of her left hand, and the ability to answer questions by shaking
her head. By late January, she was able to mouth words, could take
wheelchair rides and hold a bottle to Simon's lips.
   It seems like a miracle to family members who had been warned to
hold out little hope for recovery.
   Family members are now watching with interest a New York case in
which a man is seeking to abort a 17-week-old fetus that doctors say
is threatening the life of his comatose wife.
   David Blodgett Sr., Mrs. Blodgett's father-in-law, said he
questions the advice of medical experts who recommend the abortion,
suggesting they cannot really know if that will save the mother.
   ``Any baby that is conceived should have a chance to live,'' he
said.
   Mrs. Blodgett was thrown from a Jeep during an auto accident in
Yakima on June 30, 1988. A cousin was killed, but her husband and
young son escaped serious injury.
   Mrs. Blodgett, who was three months pregnant at the time of the
accident, went into a coma with damage to the cord that connects her
brain to her spine.
   She was transferred on Aug. 18 to University Hospital, where
Benedetti and other doctors monitored the pregnancy.
   On Dec. 9, doctors used drugs to induce labor and delivered
8-pound Simon by Caesarean section.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Reax     02-10 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Reax,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Likes Tone of Bush Speech, Questions Substance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Congress used to being Ronald Reagan's
whipping boy ambled out of the House chamber Thursday night trying
hard to accustom itself to President Bush's offer of partnership in
shaping the next federal budget.
   While the president's debut of his $1.16 trillion spending plan
for fiscal 1990 left many of them suspicious about its details, the
Bush tone of conciliation seemed to make the biggest impression on
them.
   In a town that values comity as the best way to make progress,
many of the lawmakers agreed the mood Bush strove to create was an
auspicious way to start the legislative year.
   ``This is a man I can work with,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y., the liberal chairman of the House narcotics committee.
``With Reagan I just never had the opportunity.''
   Being a member of Congress for the last eight years meant
listening to speech after speech in which then-President Reagan
vilified the lawmakers as profligates whose unbridled pleasure at
spending was a key cause of deficits hitting $200 billion annually.
   But the president who spoke to the joint session of Congress for
50 minutes Thursday was a different man with a different message.
   ``His speech could have been delivered by any Democrat,'' said
Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark. ``His problem will be getting it through
his party. Ours will go along with 70 or 80 percent of it.''
   ``We know what we have to do now,'' said Sen. Alan Simpson of
Wyoming, the Republican Senate whip. ``We have to go hump.''
   Everyone realizes that once the tough work of actually shaping a
budget begins, there will be conflict as usual. Many of the
battlefields on which Bush will clash with the Democrats who control
both houses of Congress became clear after the speech.
   One was the president's proposal to lump hundreds of programs _
mainly domestic _ into a single category that, in total, he would
restrict to the same amount of spending as this year. Because of
inflation, population growth and the lurking possibility of
unanticipated problems, such restraint can be tougher than it sounds.
   For Bush, this was a manifestation of his ``flexible freeze''
approach he mentioned vaguely during the presidential campaign. For
many Democrats, this was a crafty way of claiming deficit savings
while leaving the hard choices for later.
   ``It's a black box that frankly we haven't seen before,''
complained Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee.
   ``There's a black hole over at OMB into which all these programs
have sunk,'' said Senate Budget Committee Chairman Jim Sasser,
D-Tenn., referring to the president's Office of Management and
Budget, which wrote the spending plan.
   ``I suspect his strategy is to not make specific proposals for
cuts, and to try to bring Congress into negotiations so Congress can
share the blame for the cuts and the pain,'' Sasser said.
   Many Democrats also grumbled that the president had simply not
provided enough specific information on how the government would
save raise revenues and reduce spending.
   ``The only thing that troubles me is the arithmetic,'' said Rep.
Norman Mineta, D-Calif. ``He has a lot of additional programs, but
the arithmetic doesn't add up.''
   Another fight looms over Bush's proposal to slash the capital
gains tax on productive assets held more than two years to 15
percent, less than half the current top rate. Many Democrats find
his claim that the reduction would increase revenues by $4.8 billion
next year to be implausible.
   Nonetheless, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said the
Democratic reaction ``doesn't mean there won't be some compromise.''
And Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee, wouldn't rule out the idea. ``I think he's going to have
to sell that to the American people,'' he said.
   Bush won Democratic praise for his proposal to limit the increase
in defense spending to the inflation rate and spreading some of the
savings around to domestic programs.
   ``Nobody can come in and say he's controlling growth in domestic
programs to fund defense,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   Overall, it was a budget message that left Congress feeling like
it had been offered a hand, not a fist.
   ``Tonight,'' said Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., ``this was a
president who didn't want to pick a fight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
