<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Health     02-10 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Health,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praised for Restoring Some Funds, Criticized for Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social services groups welcomed President
Bush's budget plan restoring funds that former President Reagan had
proposed cutting from Medicaid, but they said he should have done
the same with Medicare.
   Bush's proposal incorporating Reagan's $5 billion in Medicare
savings ``extinguishes forever some of the president's vaunted
`thousand points of light,''' said Michael D. Bromberg, executive
director of the Federation of American Health Systems, which
represents 1,400 for-profit hospitals.
   The savings would be achieved mainly by limiting increases in
payments to hospitals, doctors and other health care providers _
which, Bromberg said, will result in more hospital closings and loss
of health-related jobs.
   Medicare serves about 31 million elderly and 3 million disabled
Americans.
   Bush's spending plan would hold Medicare growth to $8 billion,
about $5 billion less than it would be if the program were extended
in its current form. Bush would fund the program at $92.5 billion in
fiscal 1990, about 9.5 percent above the current level.
   To meet his pledge for a ``kinder, gentler nation,'' Bush
proposed to maintain the current level of Medicaid services for 26
million poor Americans in fiscal 1990 and extend coverage for
pregnant women and children. He also wants to increase spending for
AIDS research and outreach, the homeless and adoption services.
   For Medicaid, the federal-state health insurance program for the
poor, Bush restored $1.7 billion Reagan had proposed cutting back
and added $3.3 billion, or 9.7 percent, to bring the program up to
$37.6 billion _ the amount needed to maintain the current level of
services under the program.
   Bush withdrew Reagan's proposal to cut $1.1 billion in matching
Medicaid payments to the states, an action that drew praise from the
American Association of Retired Persons.
   ``Restoring Medicaid to full funding ... is good news,'' said
Horace Deets, AARP executive director. ``But we're certainly
disappointed we're not hearing a similar statement on Medicare.''
   Costs of the Medicaid and Medicare programs are among the fastest
growing segments of the federal budget because health care costs
have been increasing far faster than the general inflation rate.
   The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a nonprofit group
that researches policy issues affecting low-income people, said Bush
took ``a step in the right direction'' by requiring Medicaid
coverage for pregnant women and infants at 30 percent higher than
the poverty level, up from the poverty level, and expanding
immunization coverage for children.
   But Ellen Nissenbaum, legislative director of the center, said
Bush would be placing a heavier burden on states, which besides
paying for half the costs of the expansion would also have to pick
up a larger share of the administrative costs of the program.
   ``States, which administer Medicaid, would end up having to make
other cuts in Medicaid protection for poor children and their
families in order to finance Bush's Medicaid expansions, unless
states were willing to pump significantly more money of their own
into the program,'' she said.
   Spending on AIDS research and educational programs would rise 13
percent to $1.4 billion next year, not enough to satisfy AIDS
activists, who noted that the Department of Health and Human
Services last year proposed $1.9 billion for AIDS research and
education.
   The Reagan administration said reported cases of the fatal
disease in this country are expected to reach 365,000 by the end of
1992 _ with 80,000 new cases and 65,000 deaths projected for that
year alone.
</TEXT>
