<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-10 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Sharply, Stocks Set New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed sharply lower today against
the Japanese yen, while stock prices rebounded after early losses to
set a record high for the sixth consecutive day of trading.
   The dollar closed at 127.65 yen, down 1.74 yen from Thursday's
close of 129.39 yen. The U.S. currency opened at 127.80 yen and
traded at 127.30-128.10 yen.
   Traders ascribed the dollar's slide to its overnight drop on
foreign markets.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told reporters today he
considered the new dollar level stable, indicating monetary
authorities are pleased with the currency's retreat.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said there was no fresh incentive
from President Bush's budget address, which was delivered late this
morning Tokyo time.
   Bush, making his first appearance before the Congress, proposed a
$1.16 trillion budget for fiscal 1990 that he said would hold down
the nation's budget deficit to $91.1 billion.
   The budget was also designed to increase money for social
programs while freezing defense spending for a year, said Bush,
pledging to work hard with Congress to put America's fiscal house in
order.
   ``The president will have to carry (his pledges) through a
difficult period ... with the U.S. economy predicted to slow down in
1990 and a growing concern over inflation likely during the first
half of this year stemming from high (U.S.) interest rates,'' said
Nobuyuki Ueda, a senior economist at the Japan Long-Term Credit Bank.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 53.56 points, or 0.16 percent, to finish the
week at 32,131.99, a new high. The Nikkei index shed 46.36 points
during the morning session but gained toward the end of trading. It
closed at a 32,078.43-point record high Thursday.
   ``Following an overnight fall on Wall Street, investors had some
concern over the index's continued rise during the morning session
but they came back with a strong buying drive toward the end of the
day,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese brokerage, who requested
anonymity.
   Analysts say low interest rates in Japan, steady expansion of
domestic demand and relative stability in exchange rates are pushing
stock prices higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
