<DOCNO> AP890210-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BudgetDetails     02-10 0887</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget Details,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Budget a Down Payment, With Interest Due</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's $1.16 trillion spending plan
makes a down payment on his campaign promises but leaves unanswered
many important questions about how to pay for a cleaner and
better-educated America.
   Unlike President Reagan, Bush didn't face a requirement to submit
a full budget to Congress spelling out precisely how every dollar
would be spent and what programs would be cut to reach the deficit
targets.
   Instead, he offered a 193-page outline of his priorities which
went into some detail on his spending increases for education, the
homeless, the fight against drugs and cleaning up the environment.
   However, the budget was a good deal less specific about where he
would make cuts to finance the increases. In the case of the
Pentagon, Bush called for a reduction of $2.6 billion in spending,
but provided few specifics about what military programs would come
under the knife. Instead, he proposed a 90-day study by his National
Security Council.
   In other areas, Bush tacitly embraced many of the program
eliminations Reagan has repeatedly sought over the years, although
Bush said he was willing to consider other ways to save the money
which might be suggested in negotiations with Congress.
   In broad outlines, the Bush budget envisions collecting $1.069
trillion in the fiscal year which begins next Oct. 1 and spending
$1.160 trillion, leaving a deficit of $91.1 billion.
   Bush upped the deficit estimate for the current year to $163.3
billion, $1.8 billion higher than Reagan's budget estimated just a
month ago, in part because of the worsening savings and loan crisis.
   Bush's deficit projection for next year would be well within the
Gramm-Rudman law's target of $100 billion. However, most of the
cushion comes from sales of government assets, which can't be
counted toward meeting the deficit targets, and a highly
controversial cut in the tax on capital gains, which Bush claims
will make, not lose, money for the government.
   Bush's first budget projects that the deficit will be eliminated
by 1993, when he estimates the government will enjoy a $3.8 billion
budget surplus. But that forecast relies on optimistic assumptions
about the performance of the economy which many private analysts
believe are highly improbable.
   Bush did not propose any new general tax increase, but in what
some might consider a violation of his no-new-taxes pledge, he did
recommend continuing two taxes that are scheduled to expire or
decline _ the 3 percent federal tax on local and long distance
telephone calls and the 8 percent tax on airline tickets.
   Many of the promises Bush made during his long campaign for the
White House were reflected in his budget blueprint. To wit:
   _Increases in education spending to boost by one-third the number
of 4-year-olds enrolled in Head Start, to provide $30 million as a
down payment toward an eventual $500 million-a-year program of
grants to reward excellence in schools and to provide smaller
amounts for funding of new awards programs for teachers and
students. However, Bush's overall spending for education still would
not keep up with inflation.
   _A new tax credit of up to $1,000 per child under age 4 that
would go to working poor families with infants and toddlers and a
separate tax deduction of up to $3,000 for families who adopt
children.
   _Increased support for the war on drugs, pushing federal spending
to $5.5 billion in 1990. The increases would include a 24 percent
jump in spending for drug treatment.
   _Increased spending to fight acid rain, clean up ocean pollution
and purchase park lands, all in support of Bush's drive to protect
the environment.
   _Full funding of the McKinney Act to provide housing for the
homeless, increasing outlays from a projected $500 million this year
to $644 million in 1990.
   _Rejection of Reagan's proposed $1.7 billion cut in the Medicaid
health program for the poor. But Bush also accepted Reagan's plan to
cut $5 billion from Medicare, the insurance program for the elderly.
   _Also rejected was a Reagan proposal to save $828 million by
cutting the school lunch program and raising $394 million by
charging veterans higher fees when they took out VA mortgages.
   Bush kept Reagan's proposed reductions in farm subsidy programs,
and retained Reagan's proposals for a freeze in 1990 pension
payments to retired civil servants. For 1991 and beyond, the
president proposed limiting government retirees' cost-of-living
raises to 1 percentage point below inflation. Currently, they get
the full inflation increase.
   In reacting to Bush's proposals, Democrats in Congress voiced
strong opposition to the proposed cut in the capital gains tax,
which they branded as a giveaway to the wealthy. They also
complained about the lack of specifics in many parts of Bush's
budget.
   ``Unfortunately, President Bush gave us a minimum down payment on
his `kinder, gentler America,' with no clear indication of how he
intends to make the necessary annual payments,'' said Senate Budget
Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn.
   But Richard Darman, Bush's budget director, said the president is
willing to negotiate with Congress.
   ``We are not claiming to have solved all the problems,'' Darman
said. ``This is an extremely credible beginning. (Bush) is saying he
is ready to negotiate. He doesn't expect it to be found 100 percent
acceptable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
