<HEAD>With PM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is information about the jurors in Oliver
North's trial. They were chosen from a pool of 45 people, all of
whom said under questioning that they knew little or nothing of him.
   Caswell Gilbert Hartridge, 61, tow-truck driver who says that in
connection with North and the Iran-Contra affair, ``Whatever I heard
I didn't understand.''
   Lisa Krishawn Brooks, 20, a clerk typist at the U.S. Department
of Labor, who said that ``the front page is the last thing I look
at'' and that she changes channels when the news is on television.
At the time North was testifying on Capitol Hill in 1987, she said,
she was going to clerk-typist school by day and working in the
evening.
   Ernest W. Nelson, 29, an electronics technician who works for MCI
and installs and maintains long-distance communications lines.
Regarding the Iran-Contra affair and North's congressional
testimony, he said that between headlines and TV ``I can't help but
see it,'' but didn't follow it.
   Tara Leigh King, 34, Xerox operator who said ``I don't remember''
anything about North's nationally televised appearance in which he
gave immunized testimony to Congress.
   Justine Newell Parrish, 39, worked for the Navy 21 years and says
the only thing she heard about North is that he was ``selling
weapons to the overseas people.''
   Deborah Gray Bell, 37, a statistician for the U.S. Labor
Department, says that when she reads the paper, she focuses on the
comics or the horoscope and wasn't interested in North's
congressional testimony.
   Earl F. Williams, 64, unemployed, a veteran of Patton's 3rd Army
in World War II, his last job was as a security guard and he
formerly was a messenger for the State Department. He said ``I sure
would try'' to be fair to North if selected for the jury and said
his knowledge was limited to seeing North's picture on the front
page of the newspaper.
   Jean I. Johnson, 53, a cashier with a husband who is disabled,
has a son who is a deliveryman for The Washington Post. North lawyer
Barry Simon, who lodged objections to selection of almost all of the
prospective jurors, objected to her being included because she had
read headlines and was therefore exposed to North's testimony.
   Helen Gina Lynch, a pathology lab technician at George Washington
University, said she heard that North ``shredded some papers ...
that's all I know.''
   Denise Anderson, 34, a clerical worker at a hospital, lives with
her mother whom she refers to as ``news media'' because she likes to
watch the news. Ms. Anderson, on the other hand, says ``I don't like
the news'' and when her mother comes to her room to discuss current
events ``I always tell her to get out.''
   Beverly Turner, a typist in the Army chaplains' office at the
Pentagon who worked for the government 17{ years. She says she knows
only that North ``is the head of soldiers that went to Iran or
something like that.''
   Patricia Bennett, 39, laid-off office manager of an advertising
firm, said she thinks she heard that North was ``selling something
to Iran,'' recalled something about shredding, but didn't watch any
of the congressional testimony. North's attorneys objected to her
selection, saying she read the paper and ``could not miss
headlines.''
