<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Error Delays 450,000 Tax Refunds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An error at the Internal Revenue Service has
delayed 450,000 federal tax refunds by a week, but the government
says the problem was corrected in time to get checks out after only
the brief delay.
   Ellen Murphy, IRS director of public affairs said checks for
those who filed in the second or third week of January will be
mailed Feb. 17, rather than Feb. 10 as had been planned.
   ``People are going to get their refund checks in the
four-to-six-week time frame that is typical at this time of the
year,'' she said Thursday.
   The problem, the result of a human error in running a computer,
was fixed before it grew to the proportions of 1985, when millions
of tax refunds were delayed for several weeks because of problems
with a new $103 million computer system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>U.S. to Open Doors to 20,000 Additional Immigrants</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will issue 10,000 extra visas
in both 1990 and 1991 to immigrants from 162 countries on a random
basis.
   The State Department said Thursday that citizens of the Soviet
Union, Poland and several other countries whose refugee quotas are
filled will be eligible for the lottery. The application period is
March 1 through March 31. Unlike the last such lottery in 1986, the
visas will not be issued on a first-come, first-serve basis.
   Instead, the applications will be fed to computers and the
selections made on a random basis. Immigrants from all the eligible
countries will have an equal chance.
