<NOTE>Hospitals Very Short of Supplies, Nurse Says</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially-strapped Veterans' Administration
hospitals have had to raid supply accounts to pay salaries and avoid
layoffs, according to testimony before a congressional panel.
   Claudette Morissey, a nurse at the Brooklyn, N.Y., veterans
hospital and president of the Nurses Organization of the Veterans
Administration, said in testimony Thursday that at one hospital
nurses ``brought in souvenir hotel soaps and shampoos for the
patients, and in another, brought and cut large bars of soap in
small pieces for patients to use.''
   The testimony was submitted to the House Veterans Affairs
Committee, which held a hearing Thursday on the budget problems at
VA hospitals.
   Donald R. Smith, VA spokesman, while not addressing the
allegations of problems at specific facilities, said VA
director-designate Edward Derwinski told the committee earlier this
week that he would seek more money as a supplemental budget for 1989
and in the 1990 budget.
