<FIRST>r a PM-BrothersBuried     02-10 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brothers Buried,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Inseparable' Brothers Buried Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISONVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vicky and Bill Bates buried their young
sons side by side in twin white caskets, taking scant comfort in
knowing that the boys, inseparable in life, had died together when
they drowned in an icy pond.
   ``I know those little guys are arm in arm somewhere,'' Mrs. Bates
said. ``Everything Chad did, Adam did ... They always were
together.''
   The boys were buried Thursday, three days after drowning in the
pond on their parents' farm near Madisonville.
   ``It is not how long the blossom lasts,'' the Rev. John Meredith
said during the service. ``It's whether we loved it before it's
gone. And we certainly can say we did love these boys.''
   Family, friends and classmates from the Roman Catholic elementary
school which the boys attended wept quietly as Bates leaned over the
caskets to kiss his boys goodbye.
   Chad, 9, and Adam, 7, went out to play on the farm Monday after
being forced to stay home from school because of icy roads in
western Kentucky. They drowned after being in the pond about 35
minutes, authorities said.
   Mrs. Bates described her sons as excellent swimmers, but she
believes Adam, whose orange cap was found near a small hole on the
pond, fell into the pond while trying to skate on the surface and
that Chad tried to save him.
   Chad died late Monday afternoon at Madisonville's Regional
Medical Center, where his mother is a nurse. Adam, who would have
turned 8 today, died about 11 hours later.
   On Wednesday, she and her husband sat in their living room
looking at photograph albums filled with the boys' pictures.
   There were pictures of Adam and Chad on the soccer team that
their father coached, and photographs of the two in Halloween
costumes. One picture showed Adam watching as a proud Chad posed
with his first pulled tooth.
   ``Adam wanted to lose a tooth after Chad lost one,'' Bates said.
``I remember Adam pulled and pushed, trying to lose a tooth so he
would be like Chad.''
   Mrs. Bates dressed them alike until this past year, when each
began asserting his own individuality.
   ``They were about as close as brothers could get,'' Bates said.
``If Chad had a hamburger, he would give Adam half of it.''
   Bates went looking for his sons Monday after they failed to
answer their mother's call. He said that 15 minutes earlier they had
been playing near the barn where he was working.
   He jumped into the pond after realizing the cap on the ice was
Adam's. Mrs. Bates rushed to the pond to find her husband up to his
chin in the cold water, frantically searching for their boys.
   ``He was breaking the ice with his elbows,'' she said.
   Emergency rescue workers eventually pulled the boys from the pond.
</TEXT>
