<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     02-10 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jail Release Considered for Molestation Defendant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) Raymond Buckey, one of only two defendants left
in the 5-year-old McMartin preschool molestation case, was a step
closer to gaining his freedom today after spending five years in
jail without being convicted.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders, who has heard personal
assurances from some 20 people who posted their property to insure
Buckey's $1.5 million bail, said he likely would decide today
whether to release Buckey after hearing the results of the Los
Angeles County Counsel's investigation of bail security.
   The judge expressed concern that Buckey's five years in jail
already has exceeded the average sentence for a person convicted of
a felony _ and Buckey has not been convicted on the charges he faces.
   The 30-year-old defendant is on trial with his 61-year-old
mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, on charges of molesting children at
their now-defunct preschool in Manhattan Beach.
   Mrs. Buckey has been freed on $295,000 bail.
   Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin, who has opposed Buckey's
release on bail, told reporters she still considers him a danger to
the community.
   ``There are a lot of people, parents of children involved, who
are concerned about his release,'' she said
   Buckey's attorney, Danny Davis, told reporters: ``Ray wanted to
say he'd not been in the company of so many friends in five years
and it has restored his faith in not only people, but the system.''
   Davis said a total of $3 million in property was posted _ twice
the bail amount required by the court.
   Pounders said Buckey already has served the equivalent of a
10-year sentence with time off for good behavior.
   Buckey and his mother are the last of the seven original
defendants in the case, which burst into the national media
spotlight in 1983 with lurid tales of mass sexual abuse, devilish
rituals, death threats and animal mutilations.
   Buckey is charged with 52 counts of molestation and his mother is
charged with 12 counts. Both face a combined charge of conspiracy in
the case, which stems from alleged abuse of 11 children at the
school.
   The case against the Buckeys has run more than a year and a half
in Superior Court.
   Five teachers originally charged later were cleared as defendants
when the district attorney declared the evidence failed to support
the charges.
</TEXT>
