<FIRST>r i PM-PuertoRico-Statehood     02-10 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico-Statehood,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Comments Favoring Statehood For Puerto Rico Praised</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of a Puerto Rican
party that favors statehood for the U.S. Commonwealth praised
President Bush for calling for a referendum on Puerto Rico's future
in his address to Congress.
   ``It is the type of direct message we were expecting from
President Bush,'' said Pedro Rosello, vice president of the New
Progressive Party.
   ``When the president says he is in favor of the process and asks
for congressional cooperation, it gives a seriousness to the issue
which never before existed,'' Rosello said.
   In his speech Thursday evening before a joint session of the
House and the Senate, Bush said he favored statehood for Puerto Rico
but believed the Puerto Rican people should decide their own future.
   ``I have long believed that the people of Puerto Rico should have
the right to determine their own political future,'' Bush said.
``Personally, I favor statehood. But I ask the Congress to take the
necessary steps to let the people decide in a referendum.''
   Puerto Rico, an island of 3.3 million mostly Spanish-speaking
people, has been a U.S. territory since 1898 and a commonwealth
since 1952. Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens, but they pay no U.S.
taxes and cannot vote for president. They are eligible for military
service.
   The island's three main parties are divided on its future,
supporting either statehood, commonwealth or independence. But they
united in January to ask Congress and the president to support the
results of a plebiscite.
   In the last referendum in 1967, 60 percent of Puerto Ricans
favored commonwealth status, 39 percent favored statehood and 1
percent voted for independence. The referendum had no significance,
however, because the results were not recognized by Congress.
   Puerto Rican leaders want congressional legislation to guarantee
the results will be carried out.
</TEXT>
