<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Color     02-10 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>^PM-Budget-Color,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Returns `Home' To Take Center Stage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Returning to the chamber where he began his
political career as a House member 22 years ago, George Bush drew
his first cheer of his first address to Congress when he said, ``I
feel as if I am returning home to friends.''
   Eight times as vice president Bush had occupied the chair next to
the Speaker of the House, listening in silence as President Reagan
assessed the State of the Union and drew the cheers.
   On Thursday night there was another vice president _ Dan Quayle _
to do the respectful listening, to provide the dutiful applause.
   George Bush could, at last, look out over Congress assembled, the
Supreme Court, his own Cabinet, the diplomatic corps, and address
the nation and the world in his own right.
   It was his turn to set the national agenda.
   The new president's debut before Congress was interrupted by
applause at least 62 times, although there were times when lines
that appeared to beg for applause failed to attract any at all.
   The first cheers, the first standing ovation went not to the
president but to First Lady Barbara Bush as she entered the family
gallery of the House of Representatives.
   When his wife's moment was over, Bush took center stage and
promoted his programs, not attempting to match Ronald Reagan's
fabled charismatic style.
   Bush's delivered the address with a measured pace, his voice low
pitched and under control.
   He was applauded when he was tough _ when he pledged a billion
new dollars for the war on drugs, when he hailed the nation's police
officers, when he warned drug dealers: ``If you are caught and
convicted you will do time.''
   He was applauded for his initiatives on education and on the
environment.
   He was applauded when he denounced complacency, when he pledged,
yet again, that he plans ``no new taxes.''
   But when he asked for reductions in the capital gains tax, the
roar of approval from the Republican side of the aisle produced a
counterpoint in the distinct groan from the Democrats seated to his
right.
   While Bush's speech lacked much of the ideological pungency of
many of Reagan's addresses to Congress, there were other times when
the applause stopped abruptly on the Republican edge of the aisle,
leaving Democrats in frozen silence.
   That happened when Bush repeated Reagan's fervent wish that
Congress pass a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced
federal budget.
   And it happened with a vengeance when Bush, telling his audience
``don't take this wrong,'' called for an end to ``congressional
micro-management of our nation's military policy.''
   All cheers and clapping hands from the GOP. All silence and
folded arms from the Democrats.
   ``It seems there is a slight division on that question,'' the
president ad libbed, drawing a bipartisan laugh.
   One Bush line drew only a single pair of clapping hands.
   ``We must make use of clean coal,'' Bush said, to the applause of
coal-state Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.
   During the 49-minute speech Bush quoted Benjamin Franklin, a
distressed Pennsylvania mother whose son had become ``addicted to
cocaine,'' Abraham Lincoln, Sir Winston Churchill, Henry Wadsworth
Longfellow and a Chinese poet who, Bush said, once advised his
readers not to fear ``the simple words like goodness and kindness
and mercy.''
   The 41st president did not Reagan, at least not by name. He did
praise his predecessor for reversing the nation's course and said:
``I don't propose to reverse direction.''
   And he drew a low rumble from Democrats when he adopted, without
attribution, Democrat Jesse Jackson's 1988 campaign slogan, ``Keep
hope alive.''
   Still, although Bush carried on the spirit of conciliation he
called for in his inaugural address, there was a hint at the onset
that the administration and Congress may not be on the same path.
   The White House took pains to portray the speech as just a
speech, a look at the new president's budget priorities and not a
formal State of the Union address.
   But the House and Senate resolution authorizing Thursday night's
joint session said its purpose was to: ``receive a message from the
president on the State of the Union.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
