<FIRST>r i PM-China-Cambodia     02-10 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Cambodia,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Pol Pot Will Never Return To Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk said today that Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot would never
return to power in Cambodia.
   The announcement came a day after resistance leaders called for
``national reconciliation'' between the warring factions of Cambodia
and issued a peace plan that they said would keep the Khmer Rouge
from returning to power.
   ``I solemnly declare that there is no question of letting Mr. Pol
Pot return to power,'' Sihanouk said in a statement.
   ``If one day there are elections held in Cambodia under the
United Nations, Mr. Pol Pot will not take part,'' Sihanouk's
statement continued. ``And after the elections, there will be no
question of giving Mr. Pol Pot a place in the government of free
Cambodia.''
   Pol Pot led the pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge during their bloody reign
of Cambodia from 1975 to early 1979, when they were ousted from
power by a Vietnamese invasion.
   During Pol Pot's rule, an estimated 2 million of Cambodia's 8
million people died from Khmer Rouge executions, famine and civil
unrest.
   Since the Vietnamese invasion, the Khmer Rouge have joined forces
with those of Sihanouk, Cambodia's former ruler, and Son Sann, a
Western-leaning politician, to fight the occupation.
   In a news conference Thursday, Khieu Samphan, who now leads the
Khmer Rouge, declined to disclose the whereabouts of Pol Pot. He
also refused to confirm or deny reports that China offered to let
Pol Pot live in Beijing as part of a settlement of the Cambodian
conflict.
   Under the resistance leaders' proposal, 2,000 U.N. personnel
would supervise the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops.
   A U.N. peacekeeping force would also be stationed in Cambodia
after the Vietnamese left to keep the Khmer Rouge from monopolizing
power, prevent a civil war and protect Cambodia from the possibility
of another Vietnamese invasion.
   The proposal also calls for the establishment of a provisional
government during the withdrawal that would include the three
resistance factions and the Vietnamese-backed government. General
elections would follow.
   The plan will be discussed during talks with Vietnam in Jakarta,
Indonesia, beginning Feb. 19.
   Also taking part will be Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
   Faced with a worsening economy, the Soviet-backed Vietnamese
government has said it will withdraw its troops from Cambodia by
September provided the four warring parties arrive at a political
settlement. Hanoi says 50,000 troops remain in Cambodia. U.S.
officials put the toll much higher.
   China also has agreed to cut its aid to the guerrilla factions as
Vietnamese forces returned home.
</TEXT>
