<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Glance     02-10 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Glance,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights of the President's Budget Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of President Bush's fiscal
1990 budget proposal, a revision of an earlier budget proposal
submitted by former President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUSH BUDGET-REAGAN BUDGET:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the $1.16 trillion budget remains as Reagan had proposed
it. That includes the unpopular proposal to terminate dozens of
domestic programs. However, the Bush plan calls for no increase in
the military budget beyond keeping up with inflation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SAVINGS AND LOANS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush budget revisions would include the $1.9 billion cost to
taxpayers next year of his program to bail out the ailing savings
and loan industry.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHILD CARE AND EDUCATION:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A renewed and expanded $3,000 tax deduction for adoption
expenses; a child care tax credit of $1,000 for low-income families;
increased spending on the Head Start preschool education program by
$149 million; a new merit award program for schools and increased
subsidies for black colleges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HEALTH:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush rejects Reagan's proposed $1.7 billion cut in the Medicaid
health program for the poor, but embraces Reagan's call for limiting
spending on Medicare resulting in a $5 billion cut in what otherwise
would be spent. Increased spending for the battle against drug abuse
and for AIDS research.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FLEXIBLE FREEZE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Most budget items left over from Reagan would be lumped together
in Bush's ``flexible freeze'' as he invites Congress to join him in
setting national priorities for increasing or decreasing specific
areas. He nonetheless uses the sum of those Reagan cuts in
contending that he, too, would meet deficit-reduction goals.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DEFICIT:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush budget document says the federal deficit would be
reduced to less than $91.1 billion next year, just slightly lower
than the $92.5 billion in Reagan's proposal. The Gramm-Rudman law
sets a $100 billion deficit limit in 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CAPITAL GAINS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reduce the tax rate on capital gains to as low as 15 percent for
productive assets held more than two years. That's less than half
the current maximum.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOCIAL SECURITY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security is untouched by the budget plan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DRUG WAR:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush proposes increasing spending by almost $1 billion over this
year for a total of $5.5 billion, $236 million more than Reagan
proposed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENERGY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   More than $300 million in new tax breaks for the oil and gas
industry; allowing new drilling in selected offshore areas and in
the Alaska wildlife refuge.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENVIRONMENT:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   More spending on the Superfund program for toxic waste cleanup,
clean coal technology, clean water and wetlands programs, and a
greater emphasis on global environmental problems such as the
greenhouse effect. Adds $350 million to the $1.4 billion Reagan
sought for cleanups needed at the government's nuclear plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
