<FIRST>r a PM-HoffaSuit     02-10 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hoffa Suit,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jimmy Hoffa's Daughter Asks for FBI Files</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of James R. Hoffa, the former
Teamsters union leader presumed to be dead, has asked a federal
court to force the FBI to give her its files on his disappearance
13{ years ago.
   ``I think it's time the family knows what the FBI knows,'' said
Barbara Ann Crancer of St. Louis County. ``I think it would benefit
the public to know what kind of investigation was done.''
   Crancer, a lawyer, said in a complaint filed in U.S. District
Court that the FBI has twice denied her request for records under
the Freedom of Information Act. She asks the court to require the
agency to respond with her request under the act.
   Hoffa disappeared July 30, 1975, outside a restaurant in
Southfield, Mich., a suburb of Detroit.
   Crancer's complaint says she is seeking documents to help her in
her search for those responsible for her father's disappearance.
   Despite the 13{ years that have passed since Hoffa disappeared,
the complaint says, ``there have been no indictments, no trials, no
convictions as a result of the Department of Justice's investigation.
   ``Instead, the family of James R. Hoffa must glean information
from official and unofficial leaks made to the media.''
   In rejecting Crancer's previous requests for information, the
Justice Department has said the release of the records ``could
reasonably be expected to interfere with enforcement proceedings.''
   Crancer, 50, said she wanted to learn what information the FBI
had about the account of a nurse who saw Hoffa forced into a car
outside the restaurant.
</TEXT>
