<FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Guild     02-10 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Guild,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Presidents: SAG Strike Would Be `Devastating'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A likely strike this summer by the Screen Actors
Guild would be ``devastating'' to the networks, still struggling
with the effects of last summer's writers' walkout, the president of
CBS Entertainment said.
   The other two network entertainment presidents, Brandon Tartikoff
of NBC and Brandon Stoddard of ABC, agreed with CBS' Kim LeMasters
at Thursday's meeting of the International Radio and Television
Society.
   The guild contract is up June 30th, and a strike is considered
likely. Contract issues are similar to those that prompted the
24-week strike by the Writers Guild of America, among them the
amount of royalties received from network programs sold into
syndication. Movie production would also be halted if the actors'
guild called a strike.
   ``We think it would be tremendously damaging to the network
business if there was an SAG strike,'' said LeMasters. ``All three
networks are still reeling from the WGA strike. It is a business
where we are trying to increase and hold our shares, not have them
go down. ... I fervently hope that there isn't (a strike).''
   The writers' strike caused delays in the start of the networks'
1988-89 television season and is blamed for further defections in
network audiences to cable options and videocassettes. The three
networks' aggregate share of the viewing audience has averaged 68
percent so far this season, compared to 90 percent a decade ago.
   The three-network share rose into the 80s during this week's run
of CBS' blockbuster miniseries ``Lonesome Dove,'' which finished
14th on the list of all-time highest-rated network miniseries.
   The critically acclaimed miniseries was considered proof that
quality programming will still draw viewers to network television,
but the level of acting, writing and productions values is not
likely to be often repeated on network television.
   NBC's Tartikoff said studios and networks should start working
now to deal with the strike threat.
   ``I think the attitude on the part of the studios, and certainly
on the part of the networks is, we've got to get out there much
earlier than we did ... with the WGA, that we can't wait for certain
periods of negotiation and deadlines to be hit before we start to
take it seriously,'' he said.
   ``And I think the attitude is to start wrestling with the
situation now and not waiting until we get to June 30th, which is
the D-day date.''
</TEXT>
