<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-10 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chilly Weather In The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chilly weather prevailed in the East today as freeze warnings
went up in Florida and the mercury dipped below zero in New England.
Snow fell in Michigan and New York, and tapered off in Southern
California.
   Temperatures dropped into the teens throughout the mid-Atlantic
Coast and the Carolinas, the 20s in Mississippi, Alabama and
Georgia; and below zero in northern New England.
   The thermometer read 12 degrees this morning in Asheville, N.C.;
16 degrees in Richmond, Va.; 18 degrees in Birmingham, Ala.; and 28
degrees in Tallahassee, Fla.
   A hard-freeze warning was posted for extreme northeast Florida
and a freeze warning was in effect elsewhere in the extreme northern
section of the state.
   By contrast, it was 82 degrees Thursday in North Miami, Fla., the
nation's highest temperature.
   The weather remained cold in the Plains today, but was moderating
after days of below-zero readings. Temperatures ranged from near
zero in the far North to the teens in the central Plains and the 30s
and 40s in much of Texas.
   Snow showers continued in Michigan and New York along the Great
Lakes. In six hours overnight, 4 inches of snow fell at Grand Rapids
and Traverse City, Mich., and in Watertown, N.Y.
   Snow diminished over Southern California, but a snow advisory
remained in effect for the Owens Valley.
   Today's forecast called for scattered rain across the California
coast and valleys, snow showers from California's Sierra Nevada to
central Utah, much of Utah, parts of Arizona and western Colorado;
and snow showers lingering in northeast Minnesota and from New York
state to northern New England.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s and 40s across much
of the nation, the teens in northern Maine, the 20s in northwest
Colorado and from North Dakota to the Great Lakes, the upper Ohio
Valley and New England; the 50s and 60s from the California coast to
the southern Rockies, the central High Plains and the southern
Plains, the Gulf Coast and much of Florida; and the lower 70s across
Florida's southern tip.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees below zero at Houlton, Maine; St. Johnsbury, Vt.; and
Bozeman, Mont., to 68 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 22 fair; Boston 14 cloudy; Buffalo 14 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 27 fair; Cincinnati 20 cloudy; Cleveland 17 snow;
Detroit 16 snow; Miami 58 fair; New York 19 cloudy; Philadelphia 21
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 17 windy; Portland, Maine 8 cloudy;
Washington 21 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 4 fair; Chicago 10 windy; Dallas-Fort Worth 33
cloudy; Denver 16 hazy; Des Moines 11 fair; Indianapolis 21 snow;
Kansas City 21 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 5 fair; Nashville 21 fair;
New Orleans 38 fair; St. Louis 25 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 cloudy; Anchorage 27 foggy; Las Vegas 44
cloudy; Los Angeles 52 cloudy; Phoenix 58 cloudy; Salt Lake City 20
foggy; San Diego 57 drizzle; San Francisco 41 foggy; Seattle 31 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 12 snow; Toronto 10 windy.
</TEXT>
