<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 02-10 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Meets Today To Close Divisions In Ruling Elite</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with announcement that Grosz will
give speech. Pick up 3rd pvs, ``The special...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party members called on their
leaders to close the deep divisions in the ruling elite and use
today's Central Committee meeting as a springboard to social and
political reform.
   The official MTI news agency, in a brief dispatch, said officials
opened the Central Committee meeting and ``will discuss current home
political issues, to be presented by (Communist Party leader) Karoly
Grosz'' but gave no further details.
   The special session was called after a leading party reformer
touched off unprecedented debate with a startling reassessment of
the Hungarian revolt in 1956 against the Soviets.
   It also comes after a weekly party youth magazine revealed that
former Premier Janos Kadar repeatedly called the revolt a ``popular
uprising'' and urged Soviet troops to leave his country just three
days before they crushed the rebellion and elevated him to power.
   Kadar, who relinquished the party leadership last May, dropped
the offending term following the revolt, which began Oct. 23, 1956
with mass demonstrations for a new government and demands that
Soviet troops leave Hungary.
   The rebellion, however, quickly ended on Nov. 4 when 200,000
Soviet troops entered Budapest to quell the uprising.
   What happened in 1956 remains as important emotionally to
Hungarians as the Prague Spring reforms and Warsaw Pact invasion of
Czechoslovakia in 1968 is to most Czechoslovaks.
   The ideological debate over 1956 revived Jan. 28 when Politburo
member Imre Pozsgay in a radio interview termed the revolt a popular
uprising, contradicting what for years has officially been termed a
counterrevolution, or communist parlance for a concerted effort to
overthrow socialism.
   Party leader Grosz, who replaced Kadar, and other Politburo
members publicly disagreed with Pozsgay.
   But Pozsgay's statement has triggered a passionate debate that
has ranged beyond the uprising to include the pace and extent of
recent Hungarian reform and relations with Moscow.
   Last month, Hungary's Parliament passed laws legalizing
independent poltical movements and most demonstrations, and setting
an Aug. 1 deadline for a bill intended to legalize alternative
political parties.
   But party provincial members warned Thursday that such reforms as
a coalition government are in danger from party conservatives.
   The reform wing of the party's Csongrad County branch was quoted
as saying, ``The crisis of confidence among the party membership has
been reproduced, and the danger of a party rupture exists even
before attitudes are cleared up.''
   Similarly, the newspaper Magyar Nemzet quoted a party
organization of social science institutes in a Budapest district as
saying:
   ``What we see ... is that passions have been unleashed and in the
wake of this organizations have become stronger that endanger the
process of political reform and democratization.''
   Government spokesman Gyoergy Marosan warned Thursday evening that
the party must unite if the government is to improve the stagnating
economy and repay Hungary's $17 billion foreign debt.
   Marosan comments referred to increasing dissatisfaction over two
waves of price hikes last month and other austerity measures the
government says are necessary but which have slashed real wages and
prompted strikes by workers.
   This week's edition of Oetlet, a publication of the Communist
Youth Union, published the text of a stunning radio appeal made by
Kadar on Nov. 1, 1956.
   Kadar reportedly referred to the revolt five times as a popular
uprising, but an informed source said the speech was not published
afterward except in underground journals.
   Oetlet reported that in the same radio address, Kadar also said,
``Our people have proved that by shedding their blood they are
solidly behind the government's demand for the total withdrawal of
Soviet forces.
   ``We no longer want to be dependent. We don't want the country to
become a battle zone,'' Kadar reportedly said.
</TEXT>
