<HEAD>Jury Finds Anthony Quinn's Son Innocent of Assault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Anthony Quinn's son has been
found innocent of charges that he beat his girlfriend, whom defense
attorneys depicted as a crazed woman like the villain in the movie
``Fatal Attraction.''
   Francesco Quinn, an actor whose credits include several
television roles and an appearance in the movie ``Platoon,'' was
acquitted Thursday of beating and assaulting his live-in girlfriend,
Carolyn Greenberg.
   The criminal charges stemmed from an alleged fight on Oct. 31,
1987, between Quinn, 25, and Greenberg, 24, who shared a West
Hollywood condominium.
   In his closing argument Wednesday, defense attorney Godfrey Isaac
said no beating occurred. He portrayed Ms. Greenberg as an
emotionally unstable would-be model who, like the female villain in
the movie ``Fatal Attraction,'' could not let go of a romantic
involvement.
   Ms. Greenberg alleged Quinn beat her on the arms, struck her in
the stomach and kicked her in the side as she cowered on the
bathroom floor of their condo.
   The injuries resulted in a ruptured spleen, which doctors removed
several weeks after the fight, according to testimony during the
trial.
   Isaac maintained that Ms. Greenberg was injured while riding a
dirt bike and, desperate over the failure of the relationship, she
lied about the cause of her injuries.
  
