<DOCNO> AP890210-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-ManleyProfile     02-10 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manley Profile,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamaica's Election Winner Projects New, Moderate Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Name Beverley cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jamaica Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Manley shed his bush jacket for
a business suit and replaced anti-imperialistic rhetoric with talk
of free enterprise in his successful bid to return to power.
   Before his party's victory in parliamentary elections Thursday,
Manley tried to show he had changed from the radical who nearly
bankrupted his country and was soundly defeated in 1980 after eight
years as prime minister.
   ``I think there are two types of people: those who won't learn
and those who try to,'' Manley told reporters this week. ``I try to
learn.''
   As prime minister in the 1970s, Manley catapulted Jamaica to the
forefront of the developing world's non-aligned movement. He forged
close ties with neighboring Cuba and railed against CIA plots and
capitalist domination.
   His policies and defiant words alienated the United States and
foreign investors, plunging Jamaica into economic chaos.
   Today, the 64-year-old Manley encourages foreign investment and
says he has ``abandoned all thoughts of nationalization'' and wants
private business to flourish. He says he would restrict relations
with Cuba to normal diplomacy and gives far greater emphasis to the
United States and Western lending agencies.
   As vice president of Socialist International, Manley says his
true philosophy is what he calls ``social democracy.''
   ``What I really am,'' he said in an interview recently, ``is a
hard-line democrat. But not Democrat vs. Republican. Democrat in the
sense that ... my abiding commitment is to the democratic process.''
   If less defiant now, Manley is still a powerful orator who can
stir a throng to near frenzy. They call him Joshua, after the Old
Testament prophet. Away from the crowds, he is a man of refined
tastes, wit and quiet pleasures. He spends much of his time on his
40-acre coffee farm in the mountains and jogs daily.
   The former prime minister is the author of seven books, his
latest a 575-page history of West Indies cricket. He watches
American football on television, reads spy thrillers and is ``an
enthusiastic but utterly indifferent bridge player.''
   But his ``real sort of secret passion,'' is classical music.
``For a long time, I've loved people like Shostakovich and
Prokofiev,'' he said of the Russian composers _ ``but not because of
where they come from, please.''
   He has been married four times and is separated from his wife,
Beverley. He has two sons and three daughters.
   Michael Norman Manley was born Dec. 10, 1924, the son of Norman
Manley, founder of his People's National Party, and his wife Edna, a
sculptor and artist. He was graduated from Jamaica College in 1943
and served in the Royal Canadian Air Force until the end of World
War II.
   He then took an economics degree at the London School of
Economics and spent a year working as a free-lance journalist for
the British Broadcasting Corp.
   On his return to Jamaica in the early 1950s, Manley got involved
in the trade union movement and was elected president of the
Caribbean Bauxite and Mineworkers Union in 1962.
   He was first elected to Parliament in 1962 and became leader of
his party in 1969, upon his father's retirement.
   Picking up the mantle of radical socialism, Manley led his party
to victory in 1972. He developed a warm relationship with Cuban
leader Fidel Castro and brought in scores of Cuban doctors and
technicians to build schools and train young Jamaicans.
   Soon, the firebrand Jamaican with the trademark bush jacket and
camouflaged ascot was a familiar figure around the world and a thorn
in Washington's side. Foreign investors fled and grocery shelves
emptied.
   In 1980, with the country at the edge of bankruptcy, Manley was
turned out of the prime minister's office by conservative Edward
Seaga in a landslide.
   Now, after eight years out of government, Manley considers
himself a wiser man whose top priority is ``a new beginning'' with
the United States and Western financial institutions upon which his
developing nation depends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
