<FIRST>r a PM-Vatican-Reaction     02-10 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Reaction,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Document Seen As Widening Battle Against Racism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vatican-Racism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic officials in the United States
hailed a new Vatican denunciation of racism, saying it marks a
milestone in the church's assault on racial hatred.
   ``This is the first time for a statement of this magnitude,''
said John Carr, social development specialist for the U.S. Catholic
Conference.
   Carr said the document, released today, shows the connection
between different types of ``social racism,'' whether based on skin
color, religion, ethnicity or economic condition.
   ``Racism is a part of prejudice against foreigners, Jews or the
poor as well as against people of different color,'' he said. ``All
are linked in some way.''
   He said the document sees them all as ``assaults on human
dignity'' and to eliminate them calls for a ``change of hearts'' as
well as a ``change of structures.''
   The Vatican report, ``The Church and Racism: Towards a More
Fraternal Society,'' examines the history and causes of racism and
singles out specific countries for criticism. It said ``much still
needs to be done'' to combat racism in the United States.
   Several church authorities hailed the educational value of the
document and its potential impact on society, including its sharp
condemnation of South Africa's apartheid system of racial separation.
   ``This is particularly important at this time,'' Carr said.
   Eugene Fisher, director of the Catholic bishops' office for
Catholic-Jewish relations, said the document was ``the first
official church statement to link anti-Zionism with anti-Semitism,''
which it firmly condemns.
   ``This is very helpful,'' Fisher said. ``Anti-Zionism often is
used as a cover.''
   Regarding the document generally, Fisher said it ``seems to be
striving for a fundamental theory of racism in all its
manifestations and distinction'' as ``one of the fundamental evils
of our times.''
   ``It's the first document that attempts this kind of depth
analysis, putting racism into its larger context,'' he said. ``The
phenomenon of prejudice and animosities in the world have the same
dynamics.''
   ``Hatred is hatred,'' he added, whether directed at the poor,
blacks, immigrants, foreigners or other groups treated as inferiors
or outsiders.
   He said the new document should ``help expand the horizons of
Americans by its dynamics. I would like to see it become a
centerpiece of educational efforts in communities across the
country.''
   Auxiliary Bishop John Ricard of Baltimore, chairman of the
bishops' committee for black Catholics, called the document ``a
milestone.''
   ``It is the first time in my memory that the Holy See has
explicity singled out the issue of racism as a primary factor in
causing divisions in the human family, as a source of suffering and
threat to peace,'' Ricard said.
   Ricard, who is black, termed the document ``very comprehensive in
its breadth and depth,'' adding, ``I think it will be extremely
helpful to us and to our brothers and sisters in South Africa who
are under institutional racism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
