<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Angola     02-10 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Angola,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Denies Angolan Claim Of South African Incursion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military headquarters has denied a
claim that South African troops invaded Angola this week in
violation of a regional peace agreement.
   Angola's Defense Ministry, in a statement reported Thursday by
the Angolan news agency ANGOP, said South African troops penetrated
25 miles into southern Angola a day earlier in support of the UNITA
rebel movement.
   ANGOP said there was a clash in which the South Africans used
long-range artillery, but it made no mention of any casualties.
   South African military headquarters said in response that its
forces were strictly observing the peace agreement signed in
December.
   The agreement bars South African military support for UNITA and
calls for withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola, where they have
been supporting the Marxist government in the civil war. The treaty
also calls for implementation of a U.N. plan to bring independence
to Namibia, which South Africa has ruled since World War I.
   ``Allegations like this could have a detrimental effect on
agreements already signed,'' the South African statement said.
   ``Conflicts between FAPLA (the Angolan armed forces) and UNITA
should not be laid at South Africa's door,'' it said. ``The joint
military monitoring commission was established (under the peace
agreement) precisely to investigate such allegations.''
   UNITA was not party to the peace agreement and says it plans to
continue fighting.
