<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland     02-10 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks On Political Reform Begin With Government Foes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today began talks with two
longtime foes, tackling political reforms as part of a series of
negotiations aimed at legalizing Solidarity and signing a new social
accord.
   In southern Poland, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa urged 2,000
people in a rally to support efforts to reach agreement with
authorities.
   In Warsaw, Adam Michnik and Jacek Kuron, opposition philosophers
and essayists who have been active in anti-government organizing
since 1968, were prominent among the group taking seats at the
Council of Ministers Palace.
   Last year, the government opposed permitting the pair into the
proposed talks, but dropped the objections following last month's
Communist Party decision to seek an agreement with the opposition.
   In 1976, Michnik and Kuron were founding members of the Committee
for Defense of Workers, and Michnik's collected essays, ``Letters
from Prison,'' have provided much of the philosophical underpinning
for the Polish opposition movement.
   The broad talks began Monday, and working groups have been
meeting through the week on specific topics. The full negotiations
are expected to last four to six weeks.
   The group on political reform, holding its first meeting today
with 36 participants, will face some of the most delicate problems.
   The government has insisted that in exchange for legalizing
Solidarity again, the union agree on a package of political and
economic reforms, help draft a new law on elections and participate
in parliament and other official forums.
   It would put the opposition in the position of endorsing a
political system that guarantees communist domination, and some
opposition members are wary of being co-opted.
   In Krakow, Walesa tried to sell his vision of seeking a
compromise to the crowd at the 600-year-old Jagiellonian University.
   Walesa invoked a slogan that rhymes in Polish: ``Agreement
builds, disagreement ruins.''
   ``If you take the path of peaceful evolution, it will be a
revolution,'' he told the crowd, including many students, that
overflowed from a cramped auditorium. ``Let us give the (talks) a
chance. Let us not provoke, because then we will all have to pay.''
   Walesa spoke for 10 minutes, and spent another hour answering
questions from the audience. Earlier in the day, he met privately
with Krakow Roman Catholic Cardinal Franciszek Macharski.
   Later he was to travel to the industrial city of Bielsko-Biala,
site of Poland's small-car factory.
   Walesa met Thursday night with workers from the strike-prone Nowa
Huta steel mill, asking them to set aside the local grievances for
now in order to help regain Solidarity's right to function legally.
   A mediator sent by Walesa helped settle a strike Thursday by
thousands of workers at the Belchatow power plant in central Poland.
   But new signs of labor unrest appeared this morning when a strike
over wages declared by the increasingly militant official union OPZZ
crippled bus service in Piotrkow Trybunalski, a central Poland
provincial capital of 80,000 people.
</TEXT>
