<HEAD>Mother Says Ex-Husband Made Threat Before Killing Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FANNIN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who killed his two children, doused
them with gasoline and died in the resulting inferno had dropped a
veiled threat in a conversation less than an hour before, his widow
says.
   ``I asked him why he was calling me at lunchtime because I was
busy,'' said Connie Bilbrew, 24. ``He asked me did I want him
anymore. I told him, `No.' He told me I wasn't going to see the kids
anymore. He then just hung up.''
   Within an hour after the conversation Wednesday, Bennie Bilbrew
had killed Benny Jr., 6, and Fecia, 5, doused their bodies with
gasoline and burned them and himself in a pickup truck outside the
hospital where Mrs. Bilbrew worked, authorities say. Police believe
the children were already dead when they were set afire.
   ``I was thinking he was talking about leaving with them. I didn't
think he was talking about that,'' Mrs. Bilbrew said.
   Police had said earlier that there was nothing out of the
ordinary in the conversation, and no suggestion that Bilbrew planned
to take his children's lives.
   Before the fire, Bilbrew had been keeping the children
temporarily for his ex-wife, whose electricity at her Jackson
apartment was out because of an ice storm.
