<FIRST>r i PM-China-ArtExhibit     02-10 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Art Exhibit,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avant-Garde Show Reopens, Artist Says `No Regrets'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest exhibition of avant-garde art in
China's history reopened today, five days after police shut it down
when artists defied a ban on performance art and a sculptor shot her
own work with a BB gun.
   The sculptor said she didn't regret shooting her work and that
finally the piece had been completed.
   ``It was something I had to do, but I didn't realize it would
cause such a stir,'' Xiao Lu, the 26-year-old artist, said in an
interview at the China Art Gallery. ``The piece needed to be
destroyed slightly to be perfected.''
   Ms. Xiao and her boyfriend, Tang Song, were arrested and spent
three days in jail after the incident. They were released Wednesday,
two days early, and the case has been closed.
   ``My speedy release is a good sign,'' Ms. Xiao said. ``The police
were very reasonable. They tried very hard to understand my
motives.''
   None of the 300 works of art were removed during the three-day
closure, although such a move was discussed, said Fei Dawei, an
exhibition organizer.
   Museum officials, however, ordered the organizers to hire about
20 security guards to prevent any more performance art.
   Fei said that if artists continued to defy the ban on performance
art the show could be closed again. He said museum officials banned
the art form because they said it might ``cause chaos in society.''
   ``Because this is the first nationwide show of avant-garde art,
they said it was too early to do performance art,'' Fei said. ``But
we will be doing it in the future.''
   Police closed the show Sunday after a series of performance art
pieces rocked the exhibition.
   One artist sold shrimp to protest ``the commercialization of
art.''
   Three others, wrapped from head to toe in white cloth, walked
around the gallery, bumping into viewers.
   Another took off some of his clothes and squatted over several
eggs.
   One strolled around the gallery tossing handfuls of change and
condoms on the floor.
   Museum officials ordered these artists to stop their performances
but none was arrested.
   Shortly before noon, Ms. Xiao and Tang entered the museum.
   Tang handed her a BB gun and she fired twice into her work,
``Dialogue,'' a glass-and-metal sculpture of a man and a woman
talking to each other from two phone booths.
   Ms. Xiao fled the museum but Tang was arrested by police. She
later turned herself in after spending most of the day watching the
museum from across the street.
   Ms. Xiao said it was significant that Tang helped her shoot her
creation.
   ``It was an artwork about communication, between men and women,''
she said. ``So I needed him to help me add a destructive element.''
   Even without performance art, the show is an impressive one,
covering three floors of the gallery. A variety of styles, from
abstract to expressionist to video art, are represented.
   In one corner, viewers surrounded a waterbed filled with dead
fish. In another, a crowd swarmed around three huge balloons, shaped
like breasts.
</TEXT>
