<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>8 People Killed In Green Line Sniper Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people have been killed by sniper
fire across Beirut's dividing Green Line since last week, police
said today.
   A police spokesman also said unidentified gunmen fired rifle
grenades Thursday night at two checkpoints manned by Syrian soldiers
in Moslem west Beirut, but no casualties were reported.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations, said the sniper victims were ``civilians.''
   He said six of them were killed in Moslem districts on the
western side of the Green Line which has divided Beirut into
sectarian districts since the outbreak of civil war in 1975. The two
other victims were killed in Christian east Beirut, the spokesman
said.
   He said it could not be determined who was provoking increased
exchanges of sniper fire across the Green Line in the past two
weeks. The line is a traditional civil war front in Beirut but had
been calm for more than a year.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the grenade
attacks in west Beirut which apparently were intended to discredit
the Syrians' peacekeeping role.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces as well as in west and south
Beirut under a 1976 Arab League mandate to end the civil war.
