<FIRST>r a PM-Thursday'sChild     02-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thursday's Child,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pace Slows for Sailing Vessel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gale-force winds that turned to breezes
dramatically slowed the progress of the yacht Thursday's Child,
delaying its record-breaking arrival at the Golden Gate by as much
as a day.
   The racing sloop made such poor progress Thursday that
spokeswoman Nancy Lush said it would be ``miraculous'' if Thursday's
Child sailed into San Francisco Bay today.
   She said it would likely arrive on Saturday, still smashing the
world's oldest existing speed record by nine days. The ship left New
York on Nov. 23 in an assault on a 135-year-old record for sailing
around Cape Horn to San Francisco.
   The record for the 14,500-mile trip had been held by the
2,376-ton clipper ship Flying Cloud, which sailed in 1854 and made
the voyage in 89 days, 8 hours.
   At midday Thursday, the 10-ton Thursday's Child was 300 miles
south of the Golden Gate, making only 6 knots in unfavorable winds.
The position was about 60 miles west of Santa Barbara, west of San
Miguel Island.
   After hitting reported gale-force winds up to 40 knots earlier in
the day, Thursday's Child apparently hit shifting winds to the
north, forcing it to tack east and west in order to progress to the
north.
   Northerly winds for northbound boats on the West Coast always
signal a frustrating, time-consuming tacking drill, also tough on
the crew.
   The merchantman Flying Cloud, with its 17-story masts that could
carry 35 sails, was the marvel of its day. It was reputed the
fastest of thousands of sailing vessels that raced each other across
the Atlantic and Pacific, often with perishable cargo.
</TEXT>
