<DOCNO> AP890210-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Iran     02-10 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Asks U.N. To Demand Iraqi Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-UN-Gulf War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's chief justice today urged U.N.
officials to pressure Iraq into removing its troops from Iranian
territory.
   In a speech during Friday prayers at Tehran University, justice
Musavi Ardebili said Iraq is blocking peace negotiations by delaying
the withdrawal.
   Groups of Iranian servicemen in uniform were among thousands of
worshippers gathered for the prayer session. On Saturday, a rally
will be held on the 10th days of celebrations marking the Islamic
Revolution's 10th anniversary.
   Ardebili said that U.N. officials handling gulf war peace efforts
appeared to have ``caught a cold,'' and he urged them to ``show a
bit of firmness.''
   ``Can't they see who is the obstructor now? Who is the one who is
still refusing to retreat from the lands of others?'' the chief
justice asked.
   Iraq still occupies 260 square miles of Iranian territory seized
just before a cease-fire in the eight-year war took effect Aug. 20,
1988.
   U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Geneva that started five days later
have been deadlocked over the issue of troop pull-outs.
   However, Iran and Iraq's foreign ministers were to hold direct
talks today at the United Nations in New York with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar acting as mediator, officials at the world
body said.
   Iran insists the Iraqi troops must be withdrawn as the next stage
in implementing U.N. Security Council Resolution 598, which both
sides accept as the basis for a lasting peace agreement.
   But Iraq says Iran must first give up its right to search ships
in the international waters of the Persian Gulf for war material
bound for Iraq.
</TEXT>
