<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-US     02-10 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-US,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Remains Opposed to Sweeping Sanctions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vatican-Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said today it is committed to
ending apartheid in South Africa but remains opposed to imposing
further economic sanctions to achieve that goal.
   U.S. delegate William H. Marsh told the United Nations Human
Rights Commission that American laws ``imposed some of the world's
most severe restrictions on trade with South Africa,'' but without
significant results.
   ``Because of our experience, the United States believes the idea
of comprehensive and mandatory sanctions can contribute very little
toward achieving the abolition of apartheid, the fundamental goal we
all share,'' he said.
   Marsh spoke as the 40-nation commission discussed a U.N. report
that says South Africa's black majority overwhelmingly favors
sweeping economic, diplomatic and other sanctions as the most
effective way to pressure the white government to end racial
discrimination.
   Earlier this week, the U.S. State Department said in its annual
report on human rights worldwide that conditions in South Africa
continued to deteriorate last year because of greater government
repression of opponents of apartheid.
