<FIRST>u i PM-ChernobylFallout     02-10 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chernobyl Fallout,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say One-fifth Of Byelorussia Contaminated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials are monitoring the health of more
than 300,000 people in Byelorussia because of radioactive
contamination from the Chernobyl nuclear plant disaster, according
to Tass.
   Fallout has contaminated nearly one-fifth of the region, just
north of the power plant, Tass reported Thursday. Cancer and other
disease rates in the area are rising but remain below the national
average, it said.
   The official news agency asked why residents whose health may be
in danger were learning of the threat nearly three years after the
explosion and fire at the Chernobyl plant. ``Is this not too late to
tell the public the complete picture of the radiation situation?''
the agency asked.
   Vladimir Yevtukh, chairman of the area disaster relief
commission, responded by implying that residents still might not
know if it weren't for President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, or more openness.
   ``Glasnost and the democratization of public life played no small
role in the making public the data on the radiation situation in the
republic,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Yevtukh, a member of the Byelorussian Council of Ministers, said
some time was needed to collect 40,000 soil samples after the
accident in April 1986.
   Last week, the government newspaper Izvestia said 20 Byelorussian
villages were being abandoned. The number of people affected was not
given, but the newspaper said 1,200 apartments would be built for
them.
   The contaminated area is twice the size of Massachusetts.
Chernobyl is just south in the Ukraine, which was not addressed in
the article.
   Soviet officials did not report the Chernobyl accident until
three days later, when Sweden complained of unusually high radiation
levels. Reports on the cleanup have been sketchy.
   Tass said on Thursday the radiation absorbed by the residents of
the Byelorussian zone was nearly three times that found elsewhere,
but still less than 60 percent of the permissible level, according
to Yevtukh. It added, however, that ``no one precisely knows'' how
much radiation is dangerous.
   The contaminated area is divided into four zones, starting with
that immediately adjacent to the power plant. Tass said 4,400 people
were evacuated from the closest zone immediately after the accident.
   About 19,000 people were moved in the next four months from what
now is called the second zone, the report said.
   In the third zone, which covers 400 communities in the Gomel and
Mogilev regions of Byelorussia, authorities were giving medical
checkups to more than 100,000 residents and taking decontamination
measures, Tass said.
   In the fourth, the health of the 200,000 residents and the purity
of their food were being monitored.
   Towns in the contaminated area were washed to remove fallout from
roofs, fences and walls. Also, asphalt was replaced and hundreds of
thousands of tons of topsoil were removed and buried, Tass reported,
but did not say where the contaminated soil was taken.
</TEXT>
