<FIRST>r a PM-ActressAttacked     02-10 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Actress Attacked,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Refuses To Testify Against Man Accused of Attacking Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have dropped charges against a
man accused of attacking actress Tracy Scoggins in a hotel elevator
because she has refused to testify against him, authorities said.
   Ms. Scoggins told a prosecutor she would not travel here to
testify against Pedro Concepcion Padilla because he was to be tried
only on a misdemeanor assault charge. The maximum penalty on the
charge is $200.
   ``She told me that she is unwilling to come here to prosecute him
when all he's facing is a $200 fine,'' Assistant County Attorney
Timothy Byrne said at a court hearing Thursday.
   The charge was then dropped against Padilla, 36, of El Paso.
   Ms. Scoggins, who played the role of Monica Colby on ``The
Colbys'' television show, said Padilla pulled down her dress in a
hotel elevator while she was in El Paso to be cohost of the Miss USA
pageant in February 1988.
   A grand jury declined to indict Padilla on felony assault
charges, choosing to issue an indictment alleging a Class C
misdemeanor.
   Padilla's lawyer, Jose Montes, said Ms. Scoggins' decision proves
his contention that she was only seeking publicity from the alleged
attack.
   ``She's gotten what she wanted out of the case, millions of
dollars in publicity, while my client has sat in jail,'' Montes
said. But Padilla has spent only a few hours in jail since his
arrest.
   Padilla's arrest drew attention when he was released by a
municipal magistrate on just $100 bond when arraigned on a felony
charge of attempted sexual assault.
   After it was revealed that Padilla had given a false name at the
arraignment, another judge raised the bond to $100,000 and ordered
Padilla rearrested. Padilla quickly posted the higher bond.
</TEXT>
