<HEAD>Texas Lawmakers Want to Trim Governor's Salary _ By $84,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pay-cut fever has apparently spread from Washington
to Texas, where several lawmakers have threatened to slash Gov. Bill
Clement's salary by $84,000 to bring it in line with their own
incomes.
   State Rep. Keith Oakley has drafted a bill to cut Clements'
$91,000 salary to $7,200, and the measure has won support from other
Texas House members who were upset by an exchange between the
governor and House Speaker Gib Lewis.
   During a luncheon Wednesday attended by both Clements and Lewis,
the governor said he would not support a raise for state
legislators, who are paid $7,200.
   When Lewis reminded Clements of the gap between his salary and
legislators', the governor said, ``And I hope that gap gets wider.''
   Lewis, a Democrat from Fort Worth, is co-sponsor of a
constitutional amendment to raise legislators' pay. However, he said
he wasn't angered by the Republican governor's remark.
   ``I think it was an attempt to be cute and funny and we all get
in trouble when we do that,'' he said.
   But state Rep. David Hudson said many lawmakers were ``appalled
and disgusted'' by the governor's remark. ``I am not amused. And
members of the Legislature are not amused,'' Hudson said.
   A spokesman for Clements, Reggie Bashur, said the governor
opposes legislation to raise lawmakers' pay, but not a
constitutional amendment that would be submitted to voters.
   In the face of a popular outcry, Congress voted overwhelmingly
Tuesday to reject a proposed pay increase for its members from
$89,500 to $135,000.
