<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     02-10 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Jet Carrying Relief Supplies Arrives in Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet chartered by the United Nations
arrived in Kabul today with 30 tons of wheat and dried milk to help
feed the most needy people in the embattled capital.
   The Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 707, emblazoned with ``UN'' on one
side, was loaded with 238 bags of supplies to be handed out to
30,000 people targeted as the most vulnerable to the bitter winter
and food shortages plaguing Kabul.
   The food will be distributed from 30 centers around Kabul
beginning Sunday, said Steffan de Mistura, a spokesman for the U.N.
Office of Economic and Humanitarian Assistance to Afghanistan.
   ``This is a small step, a small shipment which we hope will be
able to make a real difference to the lives of some of the
vulnerable groups in Kabul that have been suffering from a hard
winter and being caught in the middle of war,'' said Ross Mountain,
deputy drector of the country's U.N. Development Program.
   An estimated 350,000 people in Kabul have been suffering from a
lack of food and fuel during one of the city's harshest winters in
years.
   U.N. officials say that if the conditions deteriorate, those who
will be most affected will be children between the ages of 1 and 5,
pregnant women and nursing mothers.
   Another 360 tons of food, medicine and blankets will be airlifted
into Kabul within the next 10 days, weather permitting, de Mistura
said.
   Kabul has been hit by severe shortages since early January
because of bad weather and attacks by Moslem rebels that have
disrupted convoys coming from the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union last month began airlifting supplies into the
city, delivering flour, canned meat and other items. Dozens of
Soviet military transport planes land daily in Kabul.
   Soviet officials have delivered more than 6,000 tons of flour
this month, about half the amount they said they wanted to airlift
in before the Feb. 15 deadline for their army's withdrawal from the
country.
   The goods are distributed on a coupon-rationing system, but only
government employees and supporters of the ruling party have access
to the supplies.
   The United Nations originally chartered an Egyptian Airlines
plane to fly in shipments to Kabul, but on Wednesday, officials said
the crew backed out because of concern for their safety.
   A six-member Ethiopian crew, headed by Capt. Sisay Tadisse,
agreed to do the job.
   ``I find it rather beautiful that after many years when the
United Nations has been airlifting goods into Ethiopia, it is the
Ethiopian airline that helps out the U.N.,'' de Mistura said.
   Michael Keating of the World Food Program said the crew had no
problems on the flight. Asked if he was concerned about safety
during the flight, Tadisse said, ``A little bit.''
   In neighboring Pakistan, Afghan rebels met today to debate a
future Islamic government in Afghanistan, but Iranian-based
guerrillas boycotted the gathering because of a feud with the
Pakistani-based faction.
   The meeting, or ``shura,'' coming five days before the scheduled
departure of all Soviet troops from Afghanistan, has been seen by
Western advisers as a last-ditch effort to avert a civil war between
the factions and consolidate power against the Kabul government.
   A spokesman for Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, chairman of the alliance
of Pakistani-based rebels, said after the opening session the
meeting would adjourn ``indefinitely'' until leaders agree on a
compromise for including the Iran-based contingent.
   Mohammad Karim Khalili, chairman of the Iran-based coalition,
said the dispute was over representation to the shura and a separate
supreme council of guerrilla leaders and their appointees.
</TEXT>
