<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan-Council 1stLd-Writethru   02-10 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Council, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Meet, but Iranian-based Faction Boycotts Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with rebel meeting, CORRECT
spelling of Khalili in 10th graf. Pickup 11th pvs, `A spokesman...' TRIMS
last graf. ^By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan insurgents today met to debate
a future Islamic government in Afghanistan, but Iranian-based
guerrillas boycotted the gathering because of a feud with the
Pakistani-based faction.
   Journalists were allowed access to the site, a religious complex
at the outskirts of Islamabad, for only 10 minutes.
   A spokesman for Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, chairman of the alliance
of Pakistani-based insurgents, said after the opening session the
meeting would adjourn ``indefinitely'' until leaders agree on a
compromise for including the Iran-based contingent.
   ``It will not be complete without representation from Afghans
living in Iran,'' the spokesman said earlier, after the chairman of
the Iran-based guerrillas announced his group would not participate.
   The meeting, or ``shura,'' coming five days before the scheduled
departure of Soviet troops from Afghanistan, has been seen by
Western advisers as a last-ditch effort to avert a civil war between
the factions and consolidate power against the weakened
Soviet-backed government in Kabul.
   Several hundred Pakistan-based insurgents, officials of previous
Afghan governments, scholars and exiles attended today's session.
   Mohammad Karim Khalili, chairman of the Iran-based coalition,
said the dispute was over representation to the shura and a separate
supreme council composed of guerrilla leaders and their appointees.
The supreme council would make many day-to-day decisions of a rebel
government.
   He said his Iran-based guerrillas were promised seven Cabinet
positions and six seats on this supreme council, as well as 100
delegates to the shura, during a meeting several days ago in Tehran
with Mojaddidi.
   On Thursday, the Pakistani-based guerrilla spokesman, Qaribur
Rehman Saeed, said the insurgents living in Iran were offered 80
delegate seats. There were no offers of Cabinet positions or supreme
council seats.
   ``We have problems, big problems,'' Saeed told reporters.
   Khalili said he agreed on the higher figures with Mojaddidi, but
reports circulated today in Pakistan's official Pakistan Times that
Mojaddidi had been replaced as leader of the guerrillas based in
Pakistan.
   A spokesman for Mojaddidi's Afghan National Liberation Front,
Ghulam Waziri, denied the reports.
   Waziri said the Iran-based Afghans broke off talks after four of
the seven guerrilla groups in the Pakistani alliance refused to
accept their representation figures.
   The majority of Afghan fighters based in Iran belong to
Afghanistan's minority Shiite sect of Islam. The Pakistan-based
guerrillas are Sunni Moslems, which represent about 80 percent of
Afghans.
   The guerrilla leaders had been touting today's meeting as a
political solution to 10 years of fighting between U.S.- and
Pakistani-based guerrillas and Soviet-backed communists.
   The guerrilla's political maneuvering over a future government
assumes the fall of Afghanistan's ruling communists after the Soviet
troop withdrawal.
   The Soviets had 115,000 troops in Afghanistan before the
withdrawal began in May under a U.N.-mediated agreement. Most of the
several thousand remaining troops are believed headed home along the
Salang Highway.
   Soviet forces intervened in Afghanistan in 1979 to support the
Afghan communists against the guerrillas. The communists seized
power in a 1978 coup.
</TEXT>
