<FIRST>r a PM-People-Fox     02-10 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Fox,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Accused of Sending Michael J. Fox Threatening Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of sending more than 5,000
threatening letters to actor Michael J. Fox apparently became upset
when she learned that he planned to marry actress Tracy Pollan,
authorities said.
   ``She wanted him to go back to an old girlfriend,'' said Al
Albergate, spokesman for the Los Angeles County district attorney's
office.
   Tina Marie Ledbetter, 26, was arrested in Westlake Village Feb. 3
for investigation of making terrorist threats, district attorney
investigator Gary Schram said Thursday. She was released after
posting $100,000 bail.
   Fox and Miss Pollan, who once played the actor's girlfriend in
the hit NBC television series ``Family Ties,'' were married last
July.
   The letters, sent to studios where Fox worked and to public
relations firms that represented him, were first sent in February
1988 and kept arriving after the couple were married.
   ``They were spread out pretty evenly over a year's time,''
Albergate said. ``I haven't read all 5,000. Basically, they have the
same theme. She threatened to kill him and his wife and their unborn
baby.''
   Fox, 27, who won two Emmys for his portrayal of the insufferable
conservative son of liberal parents on ``Family Ties'' has also
starred in such movies as ``Back to the Future'' and ``Bright
Lights, Big City.''
