<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sakharov     02-10 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sakharov,0390</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Sakharov Receives Honorary Citizenship, Calls for Tolerance ^By
MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov, the human rights
campaigner from the Soviet Union, became an honorary citizen of this
Renaissance city today.
   The scientist thanked the citizens of Florence and all others who
supported him during his struggles with five Soviet regimes.
   ``It's been said here that liberty and fraternity unite people,''
the Nobel Peace Prize winner said. ``Certainly that's true but there
is another thing that unites us, the knowledge of the danger that
threatens mankind.
   ``I think a city like Florence, with its grand humanistic
tradition, can contribute strongly to mankind's following the road
of understanding, tolerance and wisdom, the only road by which we
can avoid this danger.''
   During his five-day visit to Italy, Sakharov has cited pollution
and the threat of nuclear war as dangers.
   He told 200 people in a city government hall that his trip to
Florence was an emotional one.
   His wife, Yelena Bonner, also a human rights activist, stayed in
Florence several times in the 1970s and early 1980s when seeking
treatment for an eye problem. ``She always told me how she felt
protected and surrounded by warmth in this city,'' Sakharov said.
   The Florence city government voted in February 1980 to make
Sakharov an honorary citizen. A month earlier, he had been banished
to the closed Soviet city of Gorky for what Moscow called
anti-Soviet behavior.
   During his nearly seven years in Gorky, Sakharov went on several
hunger strikes so that his wife, also sent into exile, could travel
to Italy for operations.
   In conferring the certificate of honorary citizenship, Florence
Mayor Massimo Bogianckino hailed Sakharov for his human rights work.
   Sakharov accepted the document to the blare of horns played by
musicians dressed as Renaissance courtiers in red-and-white velvet
tunics. A huge banner with a red fleur-de-lis, the symbol of
Florence, dominated the gilt-trimmed room where the government has
met for nearly eight centuries.
   During Sakharov's seven-year detention, the Soviet government
said he would never be allowed to leave the country because of his
knowledge of state secrets. The nuclear physicist helped develop the
Soviet hydrogen bomb.
   But in December 1986, Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev released
the couple from internal exile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
