<FIRST>r a PM-JudgeProtest     02-10 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge Protest,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Going Slow In Protest Over Pay Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge with a reputation for resolving
lawsuits quickly has decided to slow down to protest the
congressional vote to scuttle 51 percent pay raises for federal
lawmakers and judges.
   Chief Judge Carl Rubin of the Southern District of Ohio said he
will limit himself to two civil trials a month, starting with his
oldest cases.
   ``I'm not willing to take this lying down,'' Rubin told The
Cincinnati Enquirer in an interview published today. ``I believe I
have been dealt with unjustly. This is the only way I have to
protest.''
   Rubin, 69, said he intended to work for $100 an hour. Since his
pay is $89,500 a year, he calculated that he would have to work 900
hours a year or about 20 hours a week.
   Congress voted Tuesday to block a proposal which would have
automatically raised pay for its members and federal judges to
$135,000.
   Under his slowdown, Rubin said, a lawsuit will take about 20
months to come to trial in his court, instead of a year. He said 20
months is the national average.
   ``I'm not required to be a particularly speedy judge,'' he said.
``I'm going to be an average judge. If I'm being paid in that
fashion, I'll work in that fashion.''
</TEXT>
