<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyShower     02-10 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Shower,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exploding Packets Of Dye Foil Robber; Passers-By Return Most of the
Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A would-be bank robber foiled by an
exploding packet of dye and tear gas concealed with the money
apparently went to a second bank branch minutes later and was foiled
the same way again, authorities said.
   In one case, the exploding packet spewed money on a downtown
street, setting off a lunchtime scramble for cash, witnesses said.
But a bank spokesman said most of the money was returned.
   ``Cars were stopping and people were jumping out and grabbing
money,'' Brenda L. Johnson, a witness, said after the robbery turned
into a free-for-all Wednesday. Cash was ``flying around,'' she said.
   Two branches of the Colonial National Bank, about 1{ miles apart,
were robbed between noon and 1 p.m. Wednesday, police said. In both
crimes, a man wearing a blue jacket and a red scarf across his face
demanded cash from a teller.
   Authorities said they suspect the same man was involved in both
robberies, but planned to compare pictures taken by bank cameras to
be sure.
   After the first bank was hit, the robber dropped the money bag he
was handed when a packet of red dye and tear gas in it exploded.
   The second time, the robber asked the money not be put in a bag,
police said. The teller handed over wads of cash with the explosive
pack concealed inside.
   After the robber left the bank, the device exploded in a flash of
red smoke, sending the money flying on the street. The man fled, a
witness said.
   The sight of $50, $20, $10 and $1 bills prompted shouts of
``hallelujah'' from one pedestrian.
   Ms. Johnson said she gave police several hundred dollars that she
retrieved after the explosion occurred within five feet of her.
   Bank spokesman Al Jacobson said all but an ``insignificant''
amount of money was recovered. He declined to say how much was
stolen.
</TEXT>
