<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-HungerStrike     02-10 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Hunger Strike,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Hunger Strikers In Hospital, One Near Kidney Failure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more detainees involved
in a widespread hunger strike were hospitalized today, and another
striker was reported on the verge of kidney failure, a human rights
group said.
   Two anti-apartheid church leaders, Archbishop Desmond Tutu and
the Rev. Allan Boesak, said they were considering joining the
19-day-old hunger strike. About 300 of the estimated 1,000 people
detained without charge are participating in the strike, demanding
they be freed or put on trial.
   The hunger strike represents one of the strongest challenges to
the policy of detention without trial since President P.W. Botha
declared a national state of emergency in June 1986.
   The three hunger strikers taken to Hillbrow Hospital in
Johannesburg brought to 11 the number that have been hospitalized
this week, according to the Detainees Aid Center.
   Mark Modiba, who was sent to the hospital on Wednesday, was
suffering from pre-renal failure, a serious kidney disorder, the
group said.
   The strike began Jan. 23 at Diepkloof Prison outside Johannesburg
and has spread to at least three other cities.
   The detainees, some held for 32 months, have demanded the
government charge them with an offense or release them.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying lengths of time under the state of emergency.
   ``The emergency regulations have paralyzed the legal system
because detainees cannot challenge their detention in court,''
Boesak said. ``They have had to use this extreme method to draw
attention to their plight.''
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said in Parliament, ``It is
clear the strike is being orchestrated from outside.''
   ``It is not spontaneous, but carefully planned worldwide by these
organizations,'' Vlok said without referring to any groups by name.
``Most of the detainees taking part do not share the enthusiasm of
these organizations.''
   He claimed some detainees were intimidated into joinging the
strike.
   Vlok has said the detainees are being held for ``good reason''
and that the government chose not to charge them because it would be
difficult to obtain convictions in many of the cases.
   On Thursday, more than 40 civil rights lawyers pledged to fast
for 48 hours in support of the strikers' demands.
   The Star newspaper of Johannesburg, the country's largest-selling
daily, carried a feature article today about Bobby Sands, the Irish
Republican Army leader who died at a prison in Northern Ireland in
1981 after a 66-day hunger strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
