<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Neo-Nazi 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 02-10 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Neo-Nazi, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neo-Nazi Says He Has Formed New Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Kuehnen saying new group formed.
Deletes outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A neo-Nazi whose political
organization was outlawed by the government said today he has formed
a new group.
   ``Right after the banning of the Nationale Sammlung (National
Rallying), I formed a new organization with the name Initiative
Volkswille (Popular Will Initiative),'' Michael Kuehnen said. ``I
want to keep being politically active.''
   Kuehnen, who has spent more than seven years in prison for his
neo-Nazi activities, spoke to reporters outside a Munich court,
where he was fined $490 for staging an illegal rally in May.
   In Bonn, an Interior Ministry spokesman, Michael-Andreas Butz,
called Thursday's outlawing of Kuehnen's Nationale Sammlung a
success.
   Butz also emphasized during a news conference that the ban came
in time to prevent the group from running in next month's municipal
elections in Frankfurt and suburban Langen.
   Police confiscated guns, knives, ammunition and Nazi propaganda
in a series of coordinated raids against homes of the organization's
members Thursday. The group, which was founded during the summer,
had about 170 members.
   Guenther Scheicher, head of the Hesse state Office for the
Protection of the Constitution, said in a telephone interview today
that slayings and robberies have been linked to ``the neo-Nazi
scene,'' but he did not name any groups or individuals.
   Scheicher said the raids have been completed, and no further
actions were planned. He said state officials had no plans to issue
any arrest warrants as a result of the raids.
   A newspaper today reported that more than 30 neo-Nazis at a time
had gathered at Kuehnen's home, and neighbors summoned police when
loudspeakers blared ``the tape-recorded speeches of Hitler and (Nazi
propaganda chief Joseph) Goebbels at full volume one Sunday last
summer.''
   The Frankfurter Rundschau newspaper said police ordered the
volume turned down but did not stop the speeches from being played.
   The Nationale Sammlung had fielded candidates for next month's
elections in Frankfurt and suburban Langen and said it hoped to run
in other locations as well. Its platform included renaming a railway
station after Adolf Hitler.
   The ban forbids Nationale Sammlung members from carrying out
activities as a group, including running candidates in an election,
and bans them from using the name publicly.
   The Interior Ministry may ban any organization it determines is
spreading Nazi propaganda. Violations of the ban carry penalties of
up to five years in prison.
   The ministry's action coincided with a growing concern in West
Germany of a possible resurgence of ultrarightist tendencies.
   A poll published Sunday by Welt am Sonntag newspaper said another
extreme right-wing group, the Republican Party, would win 11.5
percent of the vote nationwide if federal elections were held now.
   The Republicans, headed by a former Nazi Waffen SS soldier,
captured 7.5 percent of the vote in last month's elections in West
Berlin. That sends 11 party members to the local legislature and
gives the Republicans two seats in Parliament next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
