<FIRST>u i PM-UN-GulfWar 1stLd-Writethru   02-10 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Gulf War, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0483,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Iraq and Iran Will Hold Direct Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to ADD comments from Perez de Cuellar, Velayati
meeting U.N. chief. Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``Both parties...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-War-Mistakes, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said the foreign ministers of
Iran and Iraq would hold direct talks today with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar as mediator, the first time the two
ministers have agreed to face-to-face talks.
   ``The only thing I want is to agree on what to do next, and to
obtain from the two parties (assurances) that they will resume the
direct talks,'' Perez de Cuellar told The Associated Press as he
left his home this morning.
   The U.N. chief said he hoped to persuade the foreign ministers to
resume more extended direct talks ``perhaps in the end of March,
early April.''
   Top U.N. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Perez de Cuellar would ask the two to begin talks with him today.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati met Perez de Cuellar
this morning to receive the request.
   His Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz, said Thursday he is ready for
talks with Velayati in an effort to break the deadlock in the
negotiations, which began in August.
   The two have met for peace talks in Geneva and New York but have
not held face-to-face talks. After initial appearances at a
conference table for photographers, they and their aides went to
separate rooms.
   Velayati said on Thursday that he expected to take part in
three-way talks with Aziz and the secretary-general. He was at the
U.N. headquarters for a reception sponsored by his country's U.N.
Mission.
   The Persian Gulf neighbors went to war in September 1980. They
agreed to a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire that went into effect in
August and was followed by peace talks.
   ``Unfortunately, those meetings, which were called `direct
talks,' were fruitless to a great extent,'' Aziz told reporters
Thursday.
   
   Both parties have expressed optimism and a willingness to talk
but have given no sign they are ready to budge from their positions.
   Iran believes that the cease-fire is complete and that Baghdad
and Tehran should move on to the next points in Security Council
Resolution 598, the 1987 U.N. peace plan that calls for withdrawal
of armies to the border, exchange of prisoners of war, and holding
peace talks leading to a negotiated settlement.
   Iraq still occupies about 260 square miles of Iranian territory.
   Baghdad says the cease-fire is not yet legally in place because
Iran has not yet yielded its right to search ships in international
waters of the Persian Gulf for war material bound for Iraq.
   Iraq says it will withdraw from the land it holds when Iran gives
up its right to search ships.
   Baghdad also wants Iran to cooperate with an Iraqi plan to have
the United Nations dredge and open the Shatt-al-Arab waterway for
use by both nations.
   The waterway, which forms part of their southern border, is
clogged with silt, sunken ships and unexploded ordnance. It is
Iraq's main outlet to the gulf, along which Iran has a long
coastline.
   Iran has been unwilling to discuss the Shatt al-Arab unless it
retains sovereignty over the eastern half of the waterway under a
1975 treaty. Iraq believes the treaty should be renegotiated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
