<DOCNO> AP890210-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0475 02-10 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Outlines Drug Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `The budget document,' with 2 grafs
to CLARIFY that figures given for specific programs are authorization requests,
not requests for actual outlays of money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told Congress he needs $5.5
billion to wage the war on drugs, with the lion's share going to law
enforcement efforts including border interdiction.
   The request is 21 percent more _ $974 million _ than the $4.6
billion to be spent this year. And it is $236 million more than
former President Reagan sought in his first-draft 1990 plan
submitted last month, according to Richard Darman, director of the
Office of Management and Budget.
   Bush's proposal Thursday calls for almost $970 million ``to
educate our young people to say no to drugs'' including programs
from kindergarten through college, $661 million to expand drug abuse
treatment, ``particularly for the indigent, disadvantaged, youth and
expectant mothers,'' and $3.9 billion for law enforcement efforts,
according to the budget documents.
   Although not included in the drug war proposals, Bush also called
for $929 million in spending on corrections.
   ``I want to make sure that when a drug dealer is convicted, there
is a cell waiting for him,'' Bush said Thursday night in his
nationally televised speech to Congress. ``He should not go free
because prisons are too full.''
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden, D-Del., chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, praised Bush for adding $1 billion to the anti-drug
effort, but said, ``He's still got a way to go.''
   ``Illegal drugs is a $100 billion-a-year business, but we spend
only one-twentieth of that amount trying to stop them,'' he said.
``At the very least, we should fully fund the drug bill, which will
require another $500 million.''
   While the budget document listed actual outlay requests for broad
goals, it provided only multi-year authorization requests _ which
generally are higher _ for more specific programs.
   The authorization requests include $150 million for the Justice
Department's program of drug grants to state and local governments.
Reagan had eliminated all funding for such grants in his 1990 budget
proposal.
   The Drug Enforcement Administration would get more than 300 new
positions and would be called upon to increase its overseas
operations.
   Funding for the State Department's Bureau of International
Narcotics Matters would increase by $14 million to $115 million to
allow for ``enhanced crop eradication and lab destruction in foreign
drug-producing countries,'' especially in the cocaine-producing
countries of South America.
   The U.S. Customs Service would add about 550 people to its drug
interdiction program, authorized at a total of $442 million, and the
Coast Guard's drug-interdiction authorization would increase by 9
percent to $690 million.
   The Defense Department, which Congress authorized to get $300
million in 1989 for its expanded role in the drug war, would receive
the same amount under Bush's 1990 budget authorization request.
   Bush also requested $215 million for new Organized Crime Drug
Enforcement task forces.
   The budget request also calls for funding two new programs for
anti-drug education. About $25 million would be spent on Urban
Emergency Grants to ``city school systems with the worst drug
problems,'' and $35 million would go for community partnership
grants.
   Bush also is seeking $367 million for the Drug-Free Schools and
Communities program, which provide grants for states, higher
education institutions and teacher training, among others.
   In addition, Bush proposed $25 million to reduce admission delays
to drug treatment programs, $30 million for a new grant program ``to
support expansion of treatment capacity for the indigent,
disadvantaged, youth or expectant mothers in selected states which
are seriously committed to expansion,'' and a tripling of funding,
to $7 million, for HHS research into effective treatment programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
