<FIRST>r a PM-StrandedDancers     02-10 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stranded Dancers,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stranded Soviet Dancers Get Temporary Aid; Fate Of Tour Undecided</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York arts foundation has extended its
temporary financial assistance to a stranded Soviet ballet troupe
and a way may be found to allow the dancers to continue their tour,
a spokeswoman said.
   The Donetsk Ballet, still hoping to complete a 15-city U.S. tour,
has been in limbo for a week in Baltimore. The troupe ran out of
money when backers withdrew their commitment of $200,000 because
dancers from better-known Soviet ballet companies could not join the
tour.
   The Donetsk is a troupe of 59 Ukrainian ballet dancers, mostly
under the age of 25.
   Natalie Moody, spokeswoman for the Howard Gilman Foundation in
New York, said Thursday that the foundation is supporting the
dancers' stay at least through Sunday while a way to salvage their
itinerary is sought.
   ``The foundation has extended their stay, as solutions seem to be
closer to keeping the troupe here,'' Ms. Moody said. She said an
announcement might be made as early as today.
   As news of the troupe's plight has spread, arts patrons have sent
money and telegrams and have made other gestures of support. A free
performance by the dancers Wednesday at the Lyric Opera House
brought donations of about $4,200 from people in the audience.
   The dancers originally were scheduled to remain in the United
States through April and had performances booked in Detroit;
Chicago; Columbus, Ohio; and other cities.
   The Soviet Embassy reportedly was seeking financial backers to
take over the tour. Embassy press secretary Igor Bulay referred all
calls Thursday to the consular attache, but there was no answer at
that office.
   David Hermon, one of three stockholders in Heart of Art Inc., a
Santa Rosa, Calif.-based artistic management company that organized
the tour, said he hoped the financial problems would be resolved.
   Hermon said a condition imposed by Gilman was that Heart of Art
forfeit control of the tour.
   The dancers' plight also has drawn some attention from Mikhail
Baryshnikov, the Soviet emigre dancer who now is artistic director
for the American Ballet Theatre in New York. The New York Times
reported that Baryshnikov offered to lend costumes and scenery to
the troupe if the U.S. tour continues.
</TEXT>
