<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TradingPlaces     02-10 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trading Places,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Tech President Swaps Roles With Student for Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After trading places with a student for a day,
Georgia Tech President John Patrick Crecine got into big trouble. He
was late for his calculus class.
   Meanwhile, junior David Ritchie was having a grand time as the
university's chief executive officer, abolishing parking fees and
giving pleasant contemplation to the idea of canceling classes.
   Crecine and junior Ritchie exchanged car keys and identities
Thursday morning in a parking lot outside Junior's Grill.
   Crecine inherited a 1981 Cutlass Supreme and no special
privileges, while Ritchie got the president's new Chrysler New
Yorker and all the perks and power of office.
   Each drove off with some last-minute advice from the other.
   ``If the Legislature calls, they're friends,'' Crecine told his
alter ego. ``Take that call.''
   Ritchie offered the president some tips on whre he might find a
parking space _ an issue of great concern for Tech students.
   Even with the inside scoop, Crecine had trouble parking and was
15 minutes late for his 8 a.m. calculus class.
   ``This is embarrassing,'' he said, interrupting class. ``About
the best I can hope for is that there will be no pop quizzes.''
   Trading places was the idea of Tech's Student Foundation, a group
that financially assists student organizations. To raise money,
members of the foundation approached Crecine about raffling off his
job for a day and the president readily accepted.
   Ritchie said he bought 20 raffle tickets at $1 each. About 260
tickets were sold.
   ``I wanted to get to see the administration from a different
point of view -or bring a different point of view to the
administration,'' the student said.
   One of Ritchie's first actions, although short-lived, was to
abolish fees at the new parking deck on campus. He contemplated
canceling classes, but realized the move would let Crecine off the
hook.
   But along with the power came responsibility. After giving a
speech to officials of the Ford Motor Co., Ritchie was briefed on
the university's plans for restructuring its academic departments.
He also met with Tech's library director about the need for more
funding.
   ``I've found myself wanting to talk to people more, but I have
other appointments,'' Ritchie said. ``The president only has so much
time in a day.''
   Although Crecine's schedule intentionally was designed by
students to have built-in hassles (getting a student identification
card, for instance), the break from the daily meetings was a welcome
relief.
   ``This is a great luxury,'' Crecine said. ``The notion of having
some time where you get to concentrate on something longer than five
minutes is refreshing. It's like being in an isolation tank.''
   Ritchie and Crecine both agreed they'd like to continue the swap,
but a deal's a deal. At the stroke of 5 p.m., they reluctantly
resumed their former identities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
