<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages     02-10 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Hostage's Sister Prays for His Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAALOULA, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of American hostage Terry
Anderson today prayed for his release from Lebanon and for peace in
that war-battered country.
   But Lebanon's main Shiite Moslem spiritual leader ruled out an
early release of foreign hostages. In an interview published today,
he cited unspecified ``new complications.''
   Peggy Say hung a bracelet engraved with her brother's name on a
cross on the altar of the Greek Catholic church of St. Sergius,
built 300 years after the death of Christ. It is one of the oldest
churches in the world.
   With the local priest, Rev. Michael Zarura, Mrs. Say also prayed
for better U.S.-Syrian relations, urging ``the healing of
relationships between our countries and the hearts of the people in
Lebanon so they may live in peace.''
   Syria is believed to have played a role in the release of French
and German hostages last year, acting as mediator between countries
seeking the release of hostages and the pro-Iranian Moslem groups
holding them.
   Syria has close relations with Iran and was that country's only
major Arab ally in the Iran-Iraq war. Syria, with 40,000
peacekeeping troops in Lebanon, is the major power broker in that
country.
   Zarura prayed, ``here, in the oldest church in the world, that
your wishes come true and that Terry Anderson is in good health.''
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was seized by Shiite Moslem extremists March 16, 1985.
   Anderson, a native of Lorain, Ohio, is the longest-held of 15
foreign hostages in Lebanon. There are eight other Americans, three
Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian.
   Mrs. Say is in Syria for meetings with Syrian officials who have
been cooperating in attempts to free the hostages.
   She came to this ancient Christian site at the suggestion of
Jodeph Atiyeh, a Syrian-American of Baton Rouge, La. Atiyeh is
employed as an oil consultant in Syria and the United States.
   Mrs. Say and Atiyeh met in the lobby of a Damascus Hotel.
   ``We came to pray for a miracle,'' Mrs. Say said after hearing
that Maaloula is the site of several reported miracles in the early
history of the Christian church.
   Mrs. Say and Atiyeh also prayed at the chapel marking the hiding
place of St. Takla, described as the first female Christian martyr
who was converted to Christianity by St. Paul.
   Several miracles are attributed to St. Takla, including creation
of a holy spring near the chapel, carved out of a rock cliff.
   Sister Agatha Homsy, of the convent built around the chapel,
showed Mrs. Say and Atiyeh the spring where faithful may drink from
a metal cup.
   ``I'm a believer and I believe that water has some real bounce to
it,'' Atiyeh said after he and Mrs. Say drank.
   The Rev. Raymond Barnet, of Vancouver, Canada, who is
accompanying Mrs. Say, also prayed in the chapel of St. Takla and
asked that a miracle be performed again for the persecuted and that
Anderson and the other hostages be freed.
   Barnet, a Protestant minister, whose organization ``Friends in
the West'' is active in seeking the hostages' release, asked God for
``that special miracle you alone can grant, freedom for Terry
Anderson and all the hostages.''
   In Beireut, Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin, interviewed by
Lebanon's weekly magazine Ash-Shiraa, would not explain the ``new
complcations'' mentioned. When he was asked if he was hopeful of an
early settlement of the hostage issue, he was quoted as saying, ``In
fact, no.''
</TEXT>
