<FIRST>r a PM-People-Sadler     02-10 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Sadler,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Appoints Lawyer As Guardian For Sadler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has appointed a lawyer as
guardian for author-singer Barry Sadler, whose disabling injury in a
shooting last fall touched off a legal dispute among his relatives.
   Attorney David Brandon, appointed as guardian Thursday, said he
hopes to return Sadler from Brecksville Veterans Administration
Hospital in Ohio to a VA hospital in Nashville or nearby
Murfreesboro.
   Sadler, 48, who had the 1960s hit record ``Ballad of the Green
Berets'' and has also written a series of adventure novels, has been
the object of a legal tug-of-war since he was brain-damaged in a
shooting in Guatemala in September.
   ``I think it's necessary that we get Mr. Sadler back here as fast
as we can,'' Probate Judge Jim Everett said in making the
appointment.
   Brandon represents neither side of the family, Everett's office
said today.
   Everett ordered Sadler's relatives Thursday not to ``comment
derogatorily about each other in the presence of Mr. Sadler or
anyone else.''
   Sadler's wife and children, who live near Nashville, and his
business agent, Rob Robison, filed a lawsuit in Probate Court on
Jan. 10. They said they were to surprised to learn on the previous
day that Sadler had been discharged from the Wade Park Veterans
Administration Hospital in Cleveland, where he was transferred in
November from Nashville's VA hospital.
   The lawsuit said the group had just learned that Sadler's mother,
Bebe Sadler of Denver, had filed a petition for guardianship in
Cleveland on Jan. 5.
   ``I think everybody probably has the right purpose in mind, but
they're not going about it in the right way,'' Everett said.
   A Cleveland judge who visited Sadler in a private hospital ruled
Jan. 31 that Sadler needs help in making medical and other
decisions. But after hearing from attorneys for both sides of
Sadler's family, that judge said he would let Everett name a neutral
guardian.
</TEXT>
