<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Soviet     02-10 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Soviet,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Says Soviet Criticism One-Sided</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel today rejected Soviet accusations that it
is violating the human rights of Palestinians in the occupied
territories, saying Moscow's remarks were unjust and one-sided.
   The Soviet Union on Thursday accused Israel of ``crudely
violating human rights and trampling underfoot generally recognized
international legal norms'' in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``The Israeli authorities are stiffening reprisals against the
innocent Palestinian population and extensively using firearms and
ammunition, which leads to suffering, injuries and the deaths of
many people,'' Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov said in a statement.
   Alon Liel, a spokesman for the Israeli Foreign Ministry, said the
statement was ```blatantly one-sided.'' He said, ``It is unjust and
therefore cannot be accepted with indifference.''
   The Soviet criticism was relayed through the Dutch Embassy in
Moscow, which represents Israeli interests in the Soviet capital.
   It came one day after the U.S. State Department released a report
outlining Israeli abuses in the occupied lands, where government
troops have been battling Palestinians in the 14-month uprising
against Israeli rule.
   The Soviets called on Israel to halt violent activity in the
territories, which Moscow said ``could not be justified under any
circumstances.''
   Gerasimov criticized Israel for relying on ``power methods''
instead of pursuing a Middle East peace settlement to end the
uprising.
   Liel said the Soviet Union could not help bring peace to the
region unless it restored relations with Israel, broken after the
1967 Middle East war.
   Only after the restoration of ties ``will the Soviet attitude be
based on an understanding of the complexity of the issues in
question,'' Liel said, quoting from a statement being relayed to
Moscow.
   Israel-Soviet relations have been improving slowly, and the harsh
exchange was not expected to threaten that progress, said Arye
Levine, who represents Israel's interests in Moscow.
   ``They have probably thought long and hard before taking a
position on this,'' he said on Israel radio. ``They have taken a
position, but that does not affect ... the process of normalization
of relations.''
</TEXT>
