<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-USMIAs     02-10 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-US MIAs,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Religious Figure: Cambodia Holding U.S. Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cambodian government is holding the
remains of about eight Americans killed during the Indochina war, a
U.S. religious figure today quoted the Cambodian prime minister as
saying.
   W. Stanley Mooneyham, a former president of the Christian aid
group World Vision, said the prime minister, Hun Sen, told him in an
interview Feb. 3 that about 10 percent of the 83 American servicemen
Washington lists as missing in action in Cambodia have been found.
   ``Let us talk and we can discuss an aircraft to take them out,''
Mooneyham quoted Hun Sen as saying.
   Mooneyham said Hun Sen told him no conditions would be attached
to talks or repatriation of the remains to the United States, which
does not recognize the Cambodian government and refuses to deal with
it.
   Hun Sen also told Mooneyham there were more than 83 American MIAs
in Cambodia. No figure was given. Eight other Americans also
disappeared in Cambodia during the war, which ended in 1975. They
included journalists, contractors, a missionary and a merchant
seaman. A total of 2,383 are listed as missing in action in Vietnam,
Cambodia, Laos and China.
   Hun Sen was quoted as saying his government continued to search
for MIAs but might abandon its efforts if the United States did not
respond.
   ``Our people are losing faith in the search because we are being
scolded by the United States instead of being encouraged,''
Mooneyham quoted Hun Sen as saying.
   Mooneyham first went to Cambodia in 1968 and has known Hun Sen
for 10 years. Mooneyham said he would relay information from his
talks with Hun Sen to U.S. Embassy officials in Bangkok and had
offered to act as a mediator.
   Some U.S. officials say the Cambodian government hopes to use the
MIA issue to gain some form of recognition from Washington. The
United States regards the Phnom Penh government as a puppet regime
set up by Vietnam after it invaded Cambodia in late 1978.
   Mooneyham served as president of World Vision from 1969 to 1982
and now is involved in consulting and Christian activities. In 1980
he persuaded Hun Sen to allow World Vision to reopen a pediatrics
hospital in Phnom Penh that the group built and staffed during the
war.
</TEXT>
