<FIRST>u i PM-Vatican-Racism 1stLd-Writethru   02-10 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Racism, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0536,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Blasts Racism, Urges Worldwide Fight to Eradicate It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with more details from document. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican today denounced racism as a sin
that has long tormented humanity and urged efforts to stamp out all
forms of prejudice. It said the Roman Catholic Church itself shares
the blame for racism.
   In a major document that took the unusual step of mentioning
countries by name, the Vatican reserved its harshest criticism for
South Africa's system of apartheid.
   It also said ``much still needs to be done'' to wipe out racial
prejudice in the United States, but it cited the country as one of
the most interracial societies in the world.
   Examining the history and causes of prejudice, the 45-page
document warned of possible new forms of racism, saying modern
science could be exploited by ``apprentice sorcerers'' seeking to
produce human beings selected by race.
   The document, titled ``The Church and Racism: Towards A More
Fraternal Society,'' was writted by the Vatican's Justice and Peace
Commission at the request of Pope John Paul II.
   It said the Roman Catholic Church ``wants first and foremost to
change racist attitudes, including those within her own
communities'' and noted that throughout history church leaders
themselves have not been blameless.
   The document said harboring racist thoughts and attitudes ``is a
sin against the specific message of Christ.''
   ``Racism still exists and continually reappears in different
forms. ... It is a wound in humanity's side that mysteriously
remains open.''
   The document called South African apartheid ``institutionalized
racism ... justified by an ideology of the superiority of persons
from European stock over those of African or Indian origin or
`colored' which is, by some, supported by an erroneous
interpretation of the Bible.''
   Under apartheid, that nation's black majority has no voice in
national affairs.
   ``Today apartheid is the most marked and systematic form'' of
racism, the document said. ``Change is absolutely necessary and
urgent.''
   There was no immediate comment from South Africa's government.
   The document added: ``It would be hypocritical to point a finger
at only one country: rejection based on race exists on every
continent.''
   It called anti-Semitism ``the most tragic form that racist
ideology has assumed in our century,'' referring to the Nazi
extermination of millions of Jews during World War II.
   ``As if some had nothing to learn from the crimes of the past,
certain organizations, with branches in many countries, keep alive
the anti-Semite racist myth, with the support of networks of
publications,'' it said.
   The document cited terrorist attacks against Jewish people and
symbols, and said anti-Zionism ``serves at times as a screen for
anti-Semitism, feeding on it and leading to it.''
   In an apparent reference to the Soviet Union, it noted some
countries ``impose undue harassments and restrictions'' on Jewish
emigration.
   The document said the world should not forget other mass
exterminations, such as that of Armenians after World War I and
Cambodians in the 1970s.
   The document expressed fear about ``new and yet unknown forms of
racism'' that might appear as a result of artificial procreation
techniques and the possibilities of genetic manipulation for racist
ends. It called for laws to prevent this.
   The document praised the role of the Catholic church in
contributing to the passage of civil rights legislation in the
United States, but added: ``Despite ongoing efforts, much still
remains to be done to eliminate completely racial prejudice and
behavior even in what can be considered one of the most interracial
nations of the world.''
   Among other things, the document:
   _Condemned legislation that discriminates against religious
minorities, singling out the imposition of the ``sharia,'' or
Islamic law, on non-Moslems in certain countries. It did not name
them.
   _Cited problems of people who ``although living in their own
land, are subjected to humiliating conditions.'' While not naming
any people, it said in a footnote the pope has often stated
Palestinians have the right to a homeland as well as Jews.
   _Called for revision of school history texts which ``falsify
history, pass over the historical misdeeds of racism in silence or
justify the principles behind it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Missiles     02-10 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Missiles,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Will Try to Delay Missile Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will try to persuade its
NATO allies to put off a decision on replacing some nuclear missiles
in Europe with longer-range rockets, a spokesman for Chancellor
Helmut Kohl said today.
   Some Western allies have viewed West Germany's position on the
plan as a test of its loyalty to the Western military alliance.
   The Kohl spokesman, Friedhelm Ost, told reporters today that West
Germany sees no need for the 16-member North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to decide the issue before 1991. The decision is now
expected to be made in June.
   The United States, Britain, and other members of the Western
alliance have already voiced support for the missile upgrading,
which is referred to as ``modernization.'' They have also suggested
the alliance lay out its position on the controversial subject
during a NATO summit expected in June.
   West German officials have been sending out conflicting signals
over the past few months on whether they will approve the
modernization plan.
   Kohl and his government have hinted they consider a decision this
year to be premature and potentially harmful to East-West
disarmament talks.
   Today, Kohl's spokesman made that position explicit.
   ``We want no decision during this dynamic disarmament process,''
Ost said.
   He refused to be pinned down, however, on whether West Germany
would go along with the rest of the alliance if allies press for the
plan at the summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Korea     02-10 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>South To Redefine North As Non-Hostile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has proposed a law that
would redefine North Korea as non-hostile in an effort to promote
trade and other exchanges, officials said today.
   The decision came despite a snag this week in talks aimed at
improving relations between the two Koreas.
   On Wednesday, the North postponed today's scheduled meeting of
parliament members in the border truce village of Panmunjom to
protest annual U.S.-South Korean joint miltitary exercises.
   However, South Korean officials said today that high-ranking
government officials and representatives of the governing Democratic
Justice Party made the decision to redefine North Korea as
non-hostile at a meeting Thursday.
   The participants also decided to set up a special committee to
coordinate exchanges with North Korea and other communist countries,
the officials said. They said the proposed panel will be chaired by
Prime Minister Kang Young-soon.
   Officials said a bill will be sent to the National Assembly
following an endorsement of the plan by the Cabinet next week.
   A special assembly session will convene Monday to take up several
bills, possibly the one redefining North Korea.
   The law would take precedence over security law that now defines
the North as a hostile country and bans private sector contacts with
North Koreans.
   The capitalist South is ideologically anti-communist and has
until now banned activities and publications that support or
sympathize with the North.
   South Korea and North Korea were created at the end of World War
II and fought the Korean war from 1950 to 1953. They are technically
still at war because no peace treaty was signed, and more than 1
million heavily armed soldiers face each other across the 150-mile
border.
   About 42,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South Korea under a
1954 mutual defense treaty.
   Under the proposed law described by the officials, South Korean
nationals will be allowed to visit the North. Trade with the North
would be treated as internal commerce and imports from the North
would be exempt from import tariffs.
   Under a policy of detente, the South recently held preliminary
contacts with North Korean lawmakers and government officials. South
Korean traders also began to purchase North Korean goods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
