<DOCNO> AP890210-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-JamaicaElection 1stLd-Writethru   02-10 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamaica Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manley Gets `Second Chance' To Lead Jamaica</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with today's incidents. Pickup
8th graf pvs, ``Across the...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Manley, a social democrat who
led Jamaica in the 1970s, returned to power today after trouncing
Prime Minister Edward Seaga in a tense but generally orderly
election.
   With 65 percent of the ballots counted, the government-run
Jamaica Broadcasting Corp. network declared Manley's party the
winner of at least 34 of Parliament's 60 seats. Seaga's party took
eight seats and 18 were undecided.
   The party winning a majority of parliamentary seats forms the
government for a five-year term. Seaga's party held all 60 seats
going into the vote.
   The latest returns showed Manley's left-leaning People's National
Party leading Seaga's right-of-center Jamaica Labor Party by a 57
percent to 43 percent margin, or 429,680 votes to 324,486.
   The balloting was Jamaica's first nationally contested election
since 1980, when an estimated 700 people were killed in political
violence over a nine-month campaign.
   The killing Thursday of a pregnant housewife, Glenna Williams,
raised to at least 12 the number of people killed in politically
related violence since the campaign opened Jan. 15.
   The island was generally quiet this morning, but police reported
isolated disturbances.
   Police chased off dozens of political activists who erected
barricades of burning debris and blocked a road for about an hour
today just outside Spanish Town, the old colonial section of
Kingston. Police would not say whether the demonstrators were Manley
or Seaga supporters.
   The campaign was shortened to just over three weeks because of
fears of violence at the height of the island's tourist season.
Tourism, the main industry, has bounced back after Hurricane Gilbert
raked the island Sept. 12, killed 45 people and left about $1
billion in damage.
   Across the Caribbean island, 10,000 police and soldiers were
deployed to maintain order at more than 6,000 polling stations, but
skirmishes broke out.
   Many polling stations closed early because of violence, and
soldiers fired shots and used tear gas in many instances to break up
arguments.
   Attacks were confined mainly to slums in Kingston, the capital.
   Manley, 64, told cheering supporters outside his headquarters,
``Let us set an example for all future generations of dignity and
cooperation in victory. ``(It is) not given to many people a second
chance to serve a nation.''
   Manley was prime minister from 1972 to 1980. His government then
embraced Cuba, alarming the United States and foreign investors. But
he has moderated his views and today seeks a ``new beginning'' with
the Bush administration.
   ``I am wiser, more experienced man,'' he said in a recent
interview.
   In his concession speech, Seaga indicated he would not challenge
the results despite his earlier allegations of fraud.
   ``The people have spoken and we abide by their decision,'' Seaga
told supporters at his party headquarters. ``We can hold our heads
high as a previous government and we'll hold our heads high as an
opposition.''
   Manley and the People's National Party boycotted the last
election in 1983 in a dispute over voter registration.
   First elected in 1980, Seaga, 58, was trying for a third
consecutive term, something no prime minister has done since
universal suffrage began in 1944.
   Seaga, Boston-born and Harvard-educated, was the closest U.S.
ally in the Caribbean. He was the first official visitor to the
Reagan White House in 1981, and supported the U.S. invasion of
Grenada in 1983.
   Seaga restructured the economy by emphasizing exports, raising
taxes and laying off thousands of government workers. Although the
economy grew it did not recover from the collapse of the vital
bauxite industry in 1983, and the standard of living of Jamaica's
2.4 million people fell.
   He is regarded as a skillful manager, but aloof and autocratic.
Manley, a powerful orator with an engaging personality, is seen by
supporters a champion of the little people.
   In the 1970s, Manley alienated the United States and foreign
investors, broke off with the International Monetary Fund and
plunged Jamaica into economic chaos.
   Manley has said he would re-establish diplomatic relations with
Cuba _ broken in 1980 by Seaga _ but that a greater priority would
be given to the U.S. ties and relations with international lending
agencies and business.
</TEXT>
