<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardDoctor     02-10 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard Doctor,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Who Plagiarized Reappointed at Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELMONT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who was forced to resign as the
director of a hospital and as a psychiatry professor at Harvard
Medical School because of plagiarism has a new appointment at the
hospital.
   McLean Hospital trustees said Thursday they named Dr. Shervert H.
Frazier as a staff psychiatrist with full admitting privileges.
   They also named him psychiatrist in chief emeritus, an honorary
position that ``recognizes Dr. Frazier's prominent place in
psychiatry and his former role as psychiatrist in chief'' of the
hospital, trustees said.
   Frazier, a 67-year-old former director of the National Institute
of Mental Health, has not been re-appointed to the Harvard faculty.
   Dr. Daniel Tosteson, dean of the Harvard Medical School, asked
Frazier to resign from the school and the hospital four months ago
after an investigation by medical school officials revealed he
plagiarized other people's work in four papers published between
1966 and 1975. A graduate student first noted the plagiarism.
   In a prepared statement, Tosteson said the new appointment to
McLean ``expresses appropriate respect and gratitude for Dr.
Frazier's many years of service as an administrator and physician
concerned for the care of the mentally ill.''
   McLean, a 328-bed psychiatric hospital, is affliated with Harvard.
   Telephone calls to Frazier's office today were not returned, and
McLean spokeswoman Sandra Judd said, ``He does not want to make a
public comment.''
</TEXT>
