<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Army Medical Building, 10 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 10 hurt. Pickup 4th, `There
have...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside
an army medical building in a Johannesburg business district,
injuring 10 people, police said.
   The building's entryway was damaged, and windows in adjoining
office buildings were shattered. Ten passers-by _ eight whites and
two blacks _ were slightly injured by flying glass and taken to a
hospital, said Col. Frans Malherbe, a police spokesman.
   They were treated and released from a hospital.
   The Soviet-made mine exploded at 1:21 p.m. on a window ledge of
army's regional medical headquarters, Malherbe said.
   There have been scores of bombings in Johannesburg and other
cities the past three years, virtually all of them blamed by police
on the African National Congress guerrilla movement. Limpet mines,
which can be attached to other objects, have been used in many of
the bombings.
   The ANC has declined to confirm or deny responsibility for most
recent bombings.
   On Thursday, a limpet mine planted in a police van exploded on a
highway in the port city of Durban, injuring two policemen and a
pedestrian.
