<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-YellowstoneFires-Impact     02-10 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Fires-Impact,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Fires Increased Tax Revenues In Surrounding Counties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Wyoming counties surrounding
Yellowstone National Park received an economic boost from the forest
fires that raged in and around the park last year, according to a
state report issued today.
   Although the park's tourist flow plummeted in August, September
and October as the infernos charred thousands of acres, sales tax
collections in Park, Teton, Sublette and Fremont counties showed an
increase from a year earlier, the report said.
   ``On the premise that visitors were held rather `captive' in
Jackson, Cody and the surrounding area (due to park closures), and
that thousands of firefighters were brought into the area, the
boosted sales tax figures are fairly understandable,'' it said.
   Prepared by the Department of Administration and Fiscal Control's
Research and Statistics Division, the report said the four counties'
sales tax collections jumped 4.94 percent in June, July, August and
October from the year before.
   Statewide, sales tax collections through the same period were up
6.78 percent, the report said.
   ``The areas most affected were the retail and service related
sectors,'' the report's authors said in analyzing the collections.
``In reviewing the following data for these particular sectors, it
appeared that the `impact' was generally of a positive nature
instead of negative, in terms of taxable sales.''
   The four counties realized a 4.94 percent increase in sales tax
collections, from $8.8 million during the period in 1987 to $9.2
million last year.
   With roughly half of the 2.2-million-acre park blackened by the
firestorms, visitation to Yellowstone in 1988 was off 17.2 percent
as a result of the fires, the report noted.
   The number of visitors was down 50,724 in July 1988 compared to
July 1987; down 187,695 in August 1988 compared to August 1987; and
off 186,129 in September 1988 compared to September 1987.
   In October, however, tourists flooded the park as the fires died
down. While 125,597 people visited Yellowstone in October 1987, the
total jumped 39.3 percent in October 1988 to 175,019.
</TEXT>
