<FIRST>r a PM-SafeWrestling     02-10 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Safe Wrestling,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey Says Wrestling May Look Nasty, But It's Really A Safe
Profession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce-looking professional wrestlers may
grunt, groan and pound bodies to the canvas amid the roars of
frenzied fans, but don't be fooled.
   These big guys aren't really hurting each other, says the New
Jersey State Senate. Senators on Thursday passed a bill to remove
professional wrestling from the strict safety regulations posed by
the state Athletic Control Board.
   ``Wrestling is an entertainment event which poses little serious
risk to the participants,'' said state Sen. Francis J. McManimon,
the bill's sponsor. ``The strict regulatory procedures needed to
protect the health of boxers are not needed for professional
wrestling.''
   McManimon said his bill would attract more wrestling events to
New Jersey because wrestlers would be free from the state's tight
safety regulations of boxers, including requirements that a doctor
and an ambulance be at the matches. The bill now heads to the state
Assembly.
   And those snarling behemoths who regularly tell tales of how they
will terrorize their opponents aren't objecting to reports that
their body slams pose no serious health dangers.
   Officials from the World Wrestling Federation are seeking wider
access to the potentially lucrative New Jersey market, which
includes the Atlantic City casinos.
   The officials recently admitted in a legislative hearing that
Hulk Hogan and other big-name wrestlers perform in a sport of
entertainment in which participants are trained to avoid serious
injury.
</TEXT>
