<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ElephantStroll     02-10 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Elephant Stroll,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elephants Force Residents Indoors, Bar Patrons Stay Put</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A herd of elephants forced residents of a
coastal town to remain indoors overnight and allowed nightclub
revelers to enjoy themselves long after legal closing hours, a news
agency reported.
   The residents of Kwale said residents fled indoors and locked
themselves inside when 20 elephants strolled into town about 8:30
p.m. Wednesday, the state-owned Kenya News Agency reported.
   Bar patrons, afraid of provoking the elephants into stampeding,
stayed put until Thursday morning.
   All these precautions proved unnecessary. The elephants finally
settled in the town's playground for the night, and leisurely
strolled to the nearby Shimba Hills at dawn.
   Elephants have been known to destroy crops by stampeding through
farms around Kwale, about 18 miles southwest of the Indian Ocean
port of Mombasa. The Ministry of Tourism and Wildlife is installing
an electrified fence to confine them inside nearby Tsavo West
National Park.
