<FIRST>r a PM-StudentsBoxed 1stLd-Writethru a0593 02-10 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Students Boxed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0593,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Investigating Use Of Boxes To Discipline Special Ed Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``I would ...' to restore dropped words in quoted
material to reflect that principal would prefer not to use boxes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three elementary schools disciplined
special-education students by locking them inside wooden
``time-out'' boxes for up to 30 minutes, a punishment one critic
said has not been seen ``since the Dark Ages.''
   The state began an investigation into use of the boxes after a
12-year-old boy escaped from one last month. The boxes have not been
used since at Washington Elementary School, principal Lyle Stine
said.
   The boxes, measuring about 3 feet by 3 feet and 7 feet tall, are
used ``in extreme cases as a very last resort,'' Stine said. They
are used for pupils who have ``behavior disorders'' and need
isolation.
   ``The only reason we do this is when we feel it's needed for the
safety of the kids or the teachers,'' he said.
   ``I would prefer not having to use it, but sometimes you have no
choice,'' Stine said today, adding that he would rather use a room
instead, but there is not one available.
   The State Board of Education is reviewing the practice and is
expected to issue a report by the end of next week, the the Peoria
Journal Star said in a story published today.
   ``We don't necessarily oppose time-out procedures when used
appropriately,'' said Rene Christensen, the board's consultant for
the severely and multiply handicapped. ``We do not condone the use
of boxes.''
   Time-out is a common disciplinary method in which a special
education child who misbehaves is separated from classmates.
   But use of a box for discipline has not been seen ``since the
Dark Ages,'' said Michelle Hall Bolden of the Champaign-based
Protection and Advocacy Inc., a watchdog group advocating the rights
of the mentally ill and disabled that is considering lawsuits to
fight the practice.
   ``The box I saw is in a vacant room. Why not use just the vacant
room?'' she said.
   Children are kept up to 30 minutes in a box, which is equipped
with a lock, Ms. Bolden said, adding that it seems cramped.
   Stine, however, said the box is not cramped.
   ``You can easily get three people in there,'' he said.
   Stine said use of the box is the culmination of a 10-step
``assertive discipline process,'' which includes a trip to the
principal's office.
   Three elementary schools at Pontiac, a central Illinois town of
11,000, use the boxes because they have special education students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
