<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Palestine     02-10 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Palestine,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Debates Israeli Response To Palestinian Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council met today to debate
Israel's methods of combating the Palestinian uprising in the
occupied lands. The meeting came after a U.S. report criticized the
Israeli crackdown.
   The PLO has tried since mid-January to draft a resolution
condemning the Israeli army's use of rubber and plastic bullets and
tear gas but has been unable to formulate language that the United
States will not veto.
   About a week ago the PLO gave up and withdrew its resolution
after U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters said he would veto any
language that did not also call on the Palestinians to restrain
their protests.
   More than 370 Palestinians have been killed in protests since the
uprising began in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in December
1987.
   Fifteen Jews also have died in clashes.
   Asked about the latest resolution, Riyad H. Mansour, the PLO's
deputy permanent U.N. observer, said the language was still being
drafted, but ``it condemns the Israeli policies and practices.''
   ``We expect a resolution to be adopted that will allow the
Security Council to really assume its responsibility to stop the
Israelis from the continuation of this onslaught against our
people,'' said Mansour.
   ``There will be reference to human rights violations, especially
as it is coming from the United States, the closest friend to
Israel.''
   The Palestinian Liberation Organization and the Arab League
renewed their efforts after the State Department criticized the
Israeli army in a human rights report for tactics that caused ``many
avoidable deaths and injuries.''
</TEXT>
