<FIRST>r a AM-BaryshnikovReviews     02-10 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baryshnikov Reviews,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baryshnikov A Good Bug in `Metamorphosis'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Baryshnikov earned bravos as a bug
from the North Carolina critics in the Broadway-bound stage version
of Franz Kafka's ``Metamorphosis,'' now playing at Duke University.
   Tony Brown of The Charlotte Observer, the state's largest
newspaper, called the dancer's stage acting debut ``powerful,''
adding, ``The surprise is that Baryshnikov _ in his first acting
role in which he does not play a dancer _ does so well in the
speaking parts.''
   As for the play, written and directed by Steven Berkoff, Brown
predicted it would be a success on Broadway, drawing ``dance fans,
Kafka nuts, Berkoff followers and the strictly curious. And the
show's sheer power will win over the critics.''
   In the Raleigh News and Observer, Harry Hargrave described
Baryshnikov as ``simply amazing,'' saying his performance was ``an
exhausting and very physical tour de force'' in the 95-minute play,
which is performed with no intermission.
   Jim Wise of the Durham Morning Herald said the 41-year-old dance
superstar ``does make an engaging bug. A sympathetic one, even. More
importantly, a metaphorical one, which engages a viewer's
fellow-feeling and renders `Metamorphosis,' surreal as it is, a
moving expression of human feeling.''
   But Wise thought the stage adaptation was ``not overwhelming
theater. Despite the show's frequent humor and rapid,
intermission-less pace, the tedium that is part of its theme
eventually catches up with the showmanship. Even so, however, the
story's essential humanity shines through.''
   Abe D. Jones Jr. of the Greensboro News &amp; Record said Baryshnikov
``seems perfect for the role'' of Gregor Samsa, a young man who
wakes up one day and finds he has started to turn into an insect.
   Not that the production needed favorable reviews to do good
business at the 640-seat Reynolds Industries Theater at Duke. The
run, which ends Feb. 25, has been sold out for weeks.
   ``Metamorphosis'' opens on Broadway on March 6 at the Ethel
Barrymore Theater.
</TEXT>
