<FIRST>u a PM-HotelFire     02-10 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hotel Fire,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Injures 11, At Least Three Unaccounted For</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIXVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire raced through a hotel today,
injuring 11 people and leaving at least three others unaccounted
for, as subfreezing temperatures forced firefighters to draw water
from a river a half-mile away.
   The fire at the Wall Block Inn was reported about 4 a.m., said
Mike Hatlin, a supervisor with the Chester County fire and rescue
dispatch service.
   Twenty-five to 30 people living at the hotel were evacuated to a
nearby building, where the American Red Cross aided victims, said
Sue Pinkham, a spokeswoman for the county Emergency Services
Department.
   ``There are between three and five unaccounted for,'' she said.
``To my knowledge, nobody's been allowed to go into the building to
do a search for anybody.''
   More than 200 firefighters responded to the fire, which was
declared under control at about 7:40 a.m., Mrs. Pinkham said. The
cause was under investigation.
   The weather slowed water flowing through mains and forced
firefighters to draw water from the Schuylkill River, Mrs. Pinkham
said. Phoenixville is about 25 miles northeast of Philadelphia.
   One man was critically burned and transferred to a Philadelphia
hospital. Two people were admitted to Phoenixville Hospital, six
others were treated for minor injuries and two rescue workers were
being examined, officials said.
</TEXT>
