<FIRST>r i AM-Elephant     02-10 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elephant,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Elephant for Buddhist Temple Arrives in Colombo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old elephant selected to
carry the sacred tooth of Buddha in an annual festival arrived in
Colombo on Friday en route to his new home at Sri Lanka's holiest
shrine.
   Indiraja, a 4,884-pound elephant named for former Indian Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi, will live at the Temple of the Tooth, the
Buddhist shrine in the central mountain town of Kandy, and will
participate in the temple's annual pageant.
   Indiraja was taken off a West German cargo vessel, the
Quibeluberg, after a 48-hour voyage from Madras in south India.
   He will be trained to replace Raja, the elephant who held pride
of place in the Kandy pageant.
   A golden casket containing a tooth believed to be from the Lord
Buddha is carried by the lead elephant during a ceremonial
procession, the high point of the festival.
   Raja died last year at the age of 82, and plunged the
predominantly Buddhist nation into grief. The elephant had been
declared a national treasure by former President Junius R.
Jayewardene.
   The search for a replacement was not easy, said Niranjan
Wijeratne, the temple's chief custodian. According to custom, the
elephant's tail and trunk should touch the ground in a perfect arc,
the sign of a pachyderm with poise.
   Indiraja was found in a south Indian zoo by Wijeratne after
months of searching. The elephant was then donated to the temple by
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, the son of Indira Gandhi.
   Indiraja will rest at the Colombo Zoo before he leaves for Kandy,
about 50 miles to the northeast, said zoo director Bradley Fernando.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
