<DOCNO> AP890210-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Arens     02-10 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Arens,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arens Supports Soviet Role in Talks, Opposes Land for Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens has expressed
support for a Soviet role in Middle East peace talks but said Israel
is not prepared to consider trading occupied territory for peace.
   Arens has opposed Soviet participation in negotiations along with
other permanent members of the United Nations Security Council.
   In an interview with the daily Jerusalem Post, however, he said
he now believes Moscow could play a useful role.
   ``I would say, in principle, any country might contribute to the
peace process if it has good will, if it's truly interested in the
stability of the area, and if in addition it has something to
contribute,'' he said in the interview, published in the newspaper's
Friday editions.
   ``I think the Soviet Union falls in that category. ... My
impression is that they want to contribute in that area, and since
they have influence with some countries in the area I would say in
principle, `yes' to Soviet participation,'' Arens said.
   Arens also said he would not support a peace initiative that
included relinquishing any of the occupied West Bank or Gaza Strip,
and that he opposed removing Jewish settlers from the lands.
   ``Just what part of the territories Israel would retreat from ...
and just where the secure boundaries for Israel are, that's a
subject for interpretation,'' Arens said. ``It bears directly on a
permanent settlement and is not something that is usefully discussed
at the present time.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has called for resolving
the Arab-Israel problem through an international peace conference
sponsored by the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council: the United States, the Soviet Union, Britain, France and
China.
   Although accepting some role for Moscow, Arens repeated his
opposition to an international conference.
   He also said he was encouraged by progress toward resuming
diplomatic ties with Moscow.
   The Soviets halted diplomatic relations after the 1967 Middle
East war, in which Israel seized the West Bank, Gaza Strip and Golan
Heights from the Soviet Union's Arab allies.
   Israel has made normalization of ties a condition for Soviet
participation in peace negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
