<FIRST>u a PM-MultipleKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0610 02-10 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0610,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Slugs Prosecutor Before Jury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with defendant punching prosecutor,
Picks up 3rd graf, `Monroe cited ...'; SUBS 10th graf, `Johnson County
...' to conform; DELETES last 4 grafs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing 14 members of
his family punched a prosecutor today in front of the jury and a
crowded courtroom hearing his murder trial.
   R. Gene Simmons, 48, and lawyers in the case were in conference
at the bench of Johnson County Circuit Court Judge John Patterson
when Simmons struck out with his right fist and hit Prosecutor John
Bynum on the chin.
   As Simmons struggled and Bynum regained his balance, law
enforcement officers swarmed Simmons, subdued him and hustled him
out of the courtroom.
   Some spectators shrieked and several relatives of the people
Simmons is accused of killing ducked to the floor and huddled over
each other.
   ``I'm all right,'' Bynum said. ``He just got me one time. I'm all
right.''
   Bynum said the conference was about how much more time would be
needed to complete the trial, which began Monday.
   The scuffle took place in full view of the jury.
   A few minutes later, Patterson had the jury brought back to the
court and announced that the trial would take a recess for lunch.
   ``I want you to set aside what happened in the courtroom just
now,'' Patterson said. ``This trial has gone on five days. We want
to finish it if we can. You need to disregard the incident that
happened here today.''
   Defense lawyers said they were shocked by the attack and said
they were considering seeking a mistrial.
   Earlier today, firearms expert Burwin Monroe of the state Crime
Lab in Little Rock testified that a gun handed to authorities by
Simmons was one that fired the bullets that killed several victims.
   Monroe cited tests that showed a .22-caliber revolver which
Simmons had when he surrendered after a 40-minute shooting rampage
in Russellville on Dec. 28, 1987, fired the shots that killed his
wife, eldest son, and others whose bodies were found that day in
Simmons' house or the next day in a nearby grave.
   On Thursday, defense and state attorneys blamed each other for
leaking a statement to the press in which Simmons said he would see
his eldest daughter in hell.
   Simmons made the remark about Sheila Marie McNulty, 24, in a
written statement found in his safe-deposit box in a bank in
Russellville.
   Simmons also apparently refers to Mrs. McNulty's husband, Dennis
McNulty, 33, in the note.
   ``You have destroyed me,'' Simmons wrote. ``I do not want D. to
set foot on my property. He turned you against me. You want me out
of your life. I will be out of your life. I will see you in hell.''
   A three-page transcript of Simmons' five-page handwritten
statement was published in Thursday editions of the Arkansas
Democrat, a Little Rock newspaper.
   The bodies of the McNultys and 12 other members of Simmons'
family were found at his home on Dec. 28 and Dec. 29, 1987,
following Simmons' arrest for a shooting rampage in Russellville
that left two people dead. Simmons was sentenced to death for the
two Russellville killings last year and has tried to waive appeals
of his death sentence, saying he wants to die.
   Patterson said he was disappointed at the disclosure of the
statement, which appears to be notes Simmons made to himself,
possibly to prepare for a telephone conversation with his daughter.
   ``I think evidence ought to come out in the trial, not in the
newspapers,'' Patterson said.
</TEXT>
