<FIRST>r a AM-NeedleExchange     02-10 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Needle Exchange,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pioneering Needle Exchange Wins Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pioneering hypodermic needle exchange to
fight AIDS has won final approval from the county health board
despite last-minute opposition from some business owners.
   The program to give addicts free needles when they turn in used
ones was started on a private basis in August by former drug
counselor Dave Purchase. Final approval of a government role in the
effort came Thursday when the the Tacoma-Pierce County Health Board
approved $43,000 to provide Purchase with a van, needles and a
salary.
   It is believed to be the nation's first full-scale,
government-sponsored effort to stop the spread of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome by offering drug users clean needles. A similar
program began in New York on an experimental basis in November but
has attracted only a handful of the city's estimated 250,000 addicts.
   Tacoma, a city of 160,000, has an estimated 3,000 intravenous
drug abusers.
   ``It might be a risk. It might save a life. That's what I want to
find out,'' said Pierce County Executive Joe Stortini, one of those
who voted for the program.
   City Council member Greg Mykland, who cast the lone no vote, said
the program sent a bad message and urged that the money be spent on
drug treatment instead.
   ``I do believe we're condoning the use of drugs by giving out
needles,'' Mykland said.
   He also was joined by downtown business operators and others in
questioning the effectiveness of the program.
   ``They will feed their habit when they need to or when they can
with the nearest needle available _ clean or dirty _ as they always
have,'' said Jim McDaniel, assistant director of the Tacoma Rescue
Mission.
   Supporters like Judy Giles of the Martin Luther King Center,
however, said the issue was saving lives.
   ``If it just saves the life of one rape victim, one child, one
baby, then we need to spend this money,'' she said.
   Health officials say 63 cases of AIDS have been reported since
1983 in the county, not counting people who might have been
diagnosed before moving to the Tacoma area.
</TEXT>
