<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the name Fonda helps an acting career like the
name Kennedy helps in politics, then Bridget Fonda should have an
easy time.
   But the 25-year-old actress said in the March issue of
Mademoiselle that she's had to battle everybody's expectations for
her to ``be somebody'' in able to ``be herself.''
   Bridget, daughter of Peter, niece of Jane and granddaughter of
Henry, says the ``only thing I can get from them is inspiration.''
   ``A person can't possibly know what's right until they've tried
it themselves. It's like these are your favorite shoes, but I wear a
different size, so big deal. I can't put them on,'' she said.
   In the movie ``Shag,'' Fonda played a teen-ager enjoying a wild
weekend with high school friends. This month, she's in London
shooting ``Scandal,'' which re-creates the scandalous Profumo affair
that brought down Britain's Conservative government in 1963.
   Her role includes some nude scenes. She hopes her future roles
won't.
   ``Now a lot of scripts I get have nudity in them because they
know I can be a bad girl,'' she said. ``I don't want that to happen.
So if the part has nudity in it from now on, I'm going to turn it
down. It's not that I'm anti-nudity, I just want to stop being
associated with it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smiling Bjorn Borg kissed his fiancee,
showed off his engagement ring and scoffed at reports that he
apparently tried to commit suicide earlier this week.
   ``It's just ridiculous gossip. Speculations that are quite
incredible,'' the former tennis star told the Swedish newspaper
Aftonbladet in a story published Friday. He was interviewed with his
Italian fiancee, rock singer Loredana Berte, at his parents' house
on the French Riviera.
   Borg had his stomach pumped out Tuesday at a Rome hospital. The
five-time Wimbledon champion said he had combined sleeping pills and
whisky after eating food that was apparently spoiled, according to
Aftonbladet.
   Some Italian media reported the incident as an apparent suicide
attempt.
   In a second interview in the French daily Nice-Matin, the couple
denied another report _ that Loredana was pregnant.
   ``Do I look pregnant? I'm not,'' Berte said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Canseco, the American League's Most Valuable
Player, was given a traffic ticket Friday after police estimated his
1989 Jaguar was traveling 125 mph on a Florida highway.
   Canseco, 24, was stopped in his bright red car on Interstate 95
at about 1:25 a.m., cited for reckless driving and allowed to drive
away, police said. No court date has been set.
   ``He was very reasonable. He did not deny it or say he did it,''
Florida Highway Patrol spokesman Lt. Tim Betts said. ``He just
accepted his ticket.''
   The maximum penalty for reckless driving is imprisonment for 90
days and a $500 fine, Betts said.
   Canseco, the Oakland Athletics' rightfielder, was a unanimous
winner of the AL MVP after hitting 42 home runs and stealing 40
bases, the first 40-40 player in major league history. Last week he
received a $1.245 million raise, the largest in baseball history. He
will make $1.6 million next season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Tracy Scoggins has refused to
testify against a man accused of pulling down her dress in a hotel
elevator, and prosecutors have dropped charges, authorities said.
   Ms. Scoggins told a prosecutor she would not travel to El Paso to
testify against Pedro Concepcion Padilla because he was to be tried
only on a misdemeanor assault charge. The maximum penalty on the
charge is $200.
   ``She told me that she is unwilling to come here to prosecute him
when all he's facing is a $200 fine,'' Assistant County Attorney
Timothy Byrne said at a court hearing Thursday.
   Ms. Scoggins, who played the role of Monica Colby on ``The
Colbys'' television show, said Padilla attacked her in February 1988.
   A grand jury declined to indict Padilla, 36, of El Paso, on
felony assault charges.
   Padilla's lawyer, Jose Montes, said Ms. Scoggins' decision proves
his contention that she was only seeking publicity.
