<DOCNO> AP890210-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-10 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Foes in Talks on Political Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday began work on
political reforms with two of its longest and bitterest foes _ men
it considered too extreme to take part when the broad-ranging talks
were proposed six months ago.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, meanwhile, was on the road
promoting agreement with the government to skeptical followers in
southern Poland.
   Several small labor disputes broke out, led by members of the
government-supported trade union alliance and opposed by the
unsanctioned but increasingly tolerated Solidarity movement.
   Adam Michnik and Jacek Kuron, opposition philosophers and
essayists who have been active in anti-government organizing since
1968, were prominent among the 36 people at the Council of Ministers
Palace to discuss political reforms.
   Michnik and Kuron were founding members of the Committee for
Defense of Workers in 1976. Michnik's collected essays, ``Letters
from Prison,'' have provided much of the philosophical underpinning
for the opposition movement.
   ``I am totally surprised that the talks did occur,'' Kuron said
later. ``They open great possibilities.''
   Kuron said he spoke about the problems of minority groups in
Poland, such as Ukranians, Lithuanians and Byelorussians, while
Michnik said he concentrated on changes occurring in other communist
nations and their meaning for Poland.
   Last year, the government vehemently opposed including Kuron and
Michnik in the proposed talks, calling them too extreme. But the
objections have been dropped in the wake of a Communist Party
decision last month to seek common ground with the opposition.
   The talks, known as the ``round table,'' began with a plenary
session Monday. Working groups have been meeting all week on
specific topics. The full negotiations are expected to last up to
six weeks.
   Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said the union seeks ``a
country that belongs to the whole nation and is not dominated by one
party.''
   At the meeting, he said, Solidarity proposed the following steps:
   _ Legalizing Solidarity;
   _ Removing political controls on the courts;
   _ Adopting a law to enable various groups to form, including
independent student organizations and groups representing national
minorities; and
   _ Making municipal governments democratically elected.
   The government said the first step should be constructing a new
parliament with representatives from the opposition, said Politburo
member Janusz Reykowski.
   Authorities have insisted that in exchange for legalizing
Solidarity, the union agree to a package of political and economic
reforms, help draft a law on elections, and take part in parliament
and other aspects of official life. The opposition has been hesitant
to endorse a political system that guarantees communist domination
and is wary of being co-opted.
   Solidarity's leader at the talks, historian Bronislaw Geremek,
said the session was difficult. ``Today was a show of differences.
... There is no mutual trust. There is a lack of, or even crisis of,
trust on both sides,'' he said.
   In Krakow, Walesa addressed 2,000 people at Jagiellonian
University to sell his vision of seeking a compromise with
authorities. Walesa invoked a slogan that rhymes in Polish:
``Agreement builds, disagreement ruins.''
   ``If you take the path of peaceful evolution, it will be a
revolution,'' he said. ``Let us give the round table a chance. Let
us not provoke, because then we will all have to pay.''
   Walesa also met with Krakow Cardinal Franciszek Macharski and
went to the city of Bielsko-Biala, site of Poland's small-car
factory, and addressed about 500 workers.
   Walesa has been urging workers not to strike during the talks
with the government, but followers of the official trade unions
staged several actions around the country Friday.
   An OPZZ strike over wages crippled bus service in Piotrkow
Trybunalski, a central provincial capital of 80,000 people. OPZZ
officials in Warsaw said it was a local grievance and they had no
immediate details.
   OPZZ unionists at a steel plant in Ostrowiec Swietokrzyski near
Kielce in southern Poland also went on strike, seeking wage
increases of about $59 a month, official media reported.
   Solidarity spokesman Robert Bogdanski said Solidarity activists
``distance themselves from the strike.''
   The OPZZ, faced with the threat of legal competition from
Solidarity, has grown increasingly militant in an apparent bid to
demonstrate its independence.
   Representatives have tried to argue that the OPZZ can do a better
job than Solidarity of protecting workers' interests because it does
not have to appear moderate to authorities in order to get legalized.
</TEXT>
