<FIRST>u i AM-Mandela     02-10 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Boy's Body Found; Church Leader Denounces Mandela Youth Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Friday they were
investigating a report that someone had found the body of a boy
allegedly abducted by teen-agers who have acted as bodyguards for
Winnie Mandela.
   An anti-apartheid leader who heads South Africa's Methodist
Church joined a growing number of blacks who have denounced the
teen-agers as lawless and accused them of kidnapping and beating
other youngsters.
   The fate of the missing 14-year-old, Stompie Sepei, has been at
the center of the controversy surrounding Mrs. Mandela, wife of
jailed African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela.
   The Weekly Mail, a prominent anti-apartheid newspaper, quoted an
unidentified Soweto activist as saying the boy's body was dug up
Thursday in Soweto. No additional details were given.
   Police headquarters said Friday it had not confirmed the report.
   The youths associated with Mrs. Mandela call themselves the
Mandela United soccer team. They have served as her bodyguards and
some live at her home in Soweto, the huge black township outside
Johannesburg.
   The Rev. Stanley Mogoba, national president of the Methodist
Church, Friday said Mandela United members had abducted four youths
who were living at a local Methodist church. One of the four,
Stompie, has been missing since Jan. 1.
   The other youths, Mogoba said, ``were severely assaulted and held
... in defiance of the unanimous will of community leadership in
Soweto.''
   He said they were held from Dec. 29 to Jan. 16.
   Bishop Peter Storey, regional leader of the Methodist Church,
said if Stompie's body had been found, ``the worst fears of the
church and community have been realized.''
   Some of Mrs. Mandela's supporters have contended that the four
youths were taken from the church to the Mandela home because they
had been sexually molested by a white minister, the Rev. Paul
Verryn. Methodist officials say they investigated the claim and
found it was false.
   Mogoba, once imprisoned for his anti-apartheid activities, said
church leaders ``noted with anger and concern the vigilante
actions'' of Mandela United.
   The allegations against Verryn were a ``a transparent attempt to
divert the attention of both church and community away from the
ruthless actions of the `football team' and the disappearence and
possible death of Stompie,'' he said.
   Mogoba said the situation resulted from a ``vacuum in leadership
in the townships through the detention of authentic leaders under
the state of emergency,'' imposed in June 1986 in response to
growing unrest over apartheid, the system of racial separation that
discriminates against blacks.
   An estimated 30,000 people, including many leading activists,
have been detained without charges during the state of emergency.
   About 150 Soweto community leaders met last month to investigate
abductions allegedly carried out by the youth group and the ANC
later asked Mrs. Mandela to disband Mandela United.
   Black leaders say the group hurts the campaign to end white
minority rule in South Africa.
   Several newspapers have reported that continuing allegations that
the teen-agers engaged in unlawful behavior have become a source of
friction between Mrs. Mandela and her husband, South Africa's
best-known black leader.
   She says she has disbanded the group.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said Thursday that police
were investigating the alleged abductions, Stompie's disappearance
and the charges of sexual abuse.
   Mrs. Mandela, widely regarded abroad as an anti-apartheid
heroine, has been entangled in several controversies in recent years.
   She was criticized for authorizing construction of a palatial
Soweto home she never moved into, and for endorsing ``necklacings,''
in which burning tires were used to execute suspected collaborators.
   Last year, high school students angered by actions of Mandela
United members set her home afire.
</TEXT>
