<FIRST>r a AM-People-Hines 1stLd-Writethru a0658 02-10 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Get First Look At `Tap'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT to `Tap,' sted `Taps.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Siskel and Ebert have nothing on students at two
Queens high schools who were treated this week to an advance
screening of the movie ``Tap'' _ followed by a talk with its star,
Gregory Hines.
   Hines told 200 students on Tuesday that they can learn some
things from his ``Tap'' character, Max Washington, who must decide
between his career as a dancer or his career as a criminal.
   ``Max confronts many of these same issues'' facing the students
in the near future, said Hines, whose previous films include ``White
Knights'' with Mikhail Baryshnikov and ``Running Scared'' with Billy
Crystal.
   ``It's good to start (a career) now,'' Hines told the students.
``In 10 years, you'll have some craft behind you. If you want it,
you have to be aggressive and make it happen for yourself.''
   Hines also offered the students a warning: If you want to follow
in his footsteps as a performer, be ready to make some sacrifices
and hard choices along the way.
   ``I think it's a risk anytime someone wants to be an artist in
our culture,'' said Hines. ``To be an artist here is to be outside
the mainstream.''
