<FIRST>u i AM-Belgium-Kidnap Bjt   02-10 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Kidnap, Bjt,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Trace of Former Premier 4 Weeks after Disappearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four weeks after former Prime Minister
Paul Vanden Boeynants vanished near his home, leaving behind a shoe,
pipe and hearing aid, police still don't know whether he is dead or
being held for ransom.
   About 100 officers are working on the case, but police stopped
holding daily press briefings for lack of information. ``We are
increasingly worried as time goes by,'' deputy prosecutor Andre
Vandoren said.
   Members of the 69-year-old politician's family have made two
television appeals for his return.
   In the second, Jan. 31, his son, Christian, said tearfully he was
willing to negotiate with the kidnappers at their convenience. His
plea for a sign that his father was alive went unanswered.
   Investigators said two weeks ago they were sure Vanden Boeynants
was abducted by the Socialist Revolutionary Brigade. The previously
unknown group claimed responsibility hours after he disappeared Jan.
14 and sent his identity card and a letter in his handwriting to a
Brussels newspaper.
   The alleged kidnappers have been silent since, however, and
police now wonder whether the group is ideological or merely a front
used by ordinary kidnappers to mislead them.
   As a result, authorities don't know whether they are dealing with
Belgium's first major political kidnapping or with its first
political killing in 39 years.
   Assailants who were never caught shot a communist leader dead in
1950 after he shouted ``Long live the republic!'' during King
Baudouin's coronation.
   Vanden Boeynants, a right-wing Christian Democrat, was a major
factor in postwar Belgian politics before a conviction for business
tax fraud ended his political career in 1986.
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens said the former premier received
threats in the weeks before he disappeared, but Martens did not
reveal their nature. Vanden Boeynants also had requested a meeting
with the interior minister, presumably to discuss his personal
safety.
   After he vanished, the alleged kidnappers made conflicting
statements, first saying Vanden Boeynants would be returned ``in
little pieces,'' then claiming he would face a ``people's tribunal''
and finally saying he would ``appear free before the people'' if
ransom was paid.
   The handwritten letter about his ordeal sent to the newspaper
Jan. 24 demonstrated that Vanden Boeynants was alive after he
disappeared, but how long remains a question.
   A ransom note from the Socialist Revolutionary Brigade demanded
30 million francs (about $790,000), two-thirds to be given to the
poor through relief agencies chosen in polls of their readers by two
newspapers. It said the money must come from the victim's political
and business allies.
   Neither paper took a poll of its readers because no further word
ws received from the alleged abductors.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister from 1966 to 1968 and briefly
in 1978. He was a skilled backstage negotiator during 40 years in
politics and had a hand in most major government decisions.
   He also made a fortune in the meat-packing industry and got into
trouble over taxes. The judge who gave him a three-year suspended
sentence in 1986 called the former prime minister an ``inveterate
swindler'' for whom ``tax evasion is second nature.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-BrownProfile 1stLd-Writethru a0655 02-10 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0655,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Moves Smoothly Between Contrasting Worlds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Democrats-Brown, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of `predominantly' in 2nd graf, `Lego' in
7th graf, ``If you</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald H. Brown, the new chairman of the
Democratic Party, ``doesn't have to wear a name tag at a party
meeting or in black politics'' said a liberal activist involved in
bringing Brown into the Jesse Jackson campaign.
   The ability to move smoothly between often contrasting worlds has
characterized Brown since his childhood when he was the black
student from Harlem at predominantly white schools on Manhattan's
Upper East Side.
   It came to the fore last May, when the establishment lawyer whose
clients included the Japanese electronics industry and the
government of Haiti stepped into a key role in Jackson's
anti-establishment presidential campaign.
   Ann Lewis, who was a top Jackson adviser, recalled that Brown had
turned down Jackson's request to be his campaign manager.
   After the bitter New York presidential primary in April 1988 _ a
contest during which New York Mayor Ed Koch had said any Jew ``would
have to be crazy'' to vote for Jackson _ the former civil rights
leader sought again to bring Brown into his campaign, this time to
be his convention manager.
   Lewis said a meeting of Jackson campaign officials was held in
her Georgetown office. Brown chaired the session and everyone
accepted his leadership role.
   ``If you did it with Lego blocks, you'd come up with someone with
Ron's qualities,'' she said when asked what characteristics the
campaign was seeking. ``Ron doesn't have to wear a name tag at a
party meeting or in black politics, and it was his ability to move
credibly in both worlds that worked so well.''
   Most Democrats cheered when Brown agreed to be Jackson's man in
the negotiations leading up to the Atlanta convention that would
nominate Michael Dukakis for president.
   ``There was a rather tense atmosphere going into the
convention,'' recalled Paul Brountas, chairman of the Dukakis
campaign. ``The Reverend Jackson had started a bus caravan in
Chicago which picked up speed and people on the way to the
convention. This was after several weeks where Reverend Jackson was
hitting Dukakis pretty hard, building an expectation that Jackson
deserved more than he had received.''
   ``None of that created an environment which assured any kind of
unity,'' Brountas said.
   Brown and Brountas met privately on the Saturday before the
convention and the Jackson aide showed up with a list of his
concerns.
   By the time their meeting ended, Brountas said, ``I understood
where he was coming from and I was able to respond to most of them
and give an indication where I was coming from.''
   There would be more meetings including one that included Dukakis
and Jackson. The result was a convention that ended on a note of
harmony.
   From his childhood, Brown has bridged two very different worlds.
He grew up in Harlem, but his parents sent him to predominantly
white private schools in the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
   He attended Middlebury College in Vermont where he was one of
only a handful of black students. When he joined Sigma Phi Epsilon
fraternity, the house was stripped of its national membership for
violating the whites-only charter.
   At St. John's University Law School, one of his professors was
Mario Cuomo.
   Brown ran the Washington office of the Urban League before
joining Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and becoming a senior aide on his
presidential campaign. Later, he became general counsel of the
Senate Judiciary Committee which Kennedy chaired.
   ``He's nobody's man but his own,'' said Kennedy. ``Ron could say
no to me or to Jesse Jackson or to anyone else if he believed that
whatever was requested wasn't in the interests of the party.''
   Big time, big money law beckoned and Brown now is a partner in
one of the capital's biggest, most politically active firms.
   During that period he also served as deputy chairman of the
Democratic National Committee.
   Former party chairman John C. White recalled Brown and Paul Kirk
from earlier days at the DNC.
   ``They were around the office all the time, mostly with a press
release demanding my resignation,'' laughed White.
   A sandy-haired Texan, White was Jimmy Carter's hand-picked choice
to head the party.
   Brown and Kirk were aides to Kennedy, who was opposing the
incumbent president's bid for renomination.
   This was down-and-dirty, no-holds-barred politics. ``I'll whip
his ass,'' the president of the United States had said of the
Massachusetts senator who bore one of the most famous names in
American politics.
   But White was an old pro and Brown and Kirk were budding young
pros.
   ``Hell, they were so nice about it, I just got so I would invite
them in for a cup of coffee,'' recalled White. ``We just got to
where we liked each other. I knew what they were doing and they knew
what I was doing.''
   Six years later, Kirk became Democratic Party chairman and on
Friday, the 47-year-old Brown succeeded him in that post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
