<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-10 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For one day, Georgia Tech President John Patrick
Crecine experienced life as a student. And it wasn't all a big party.
   For one thing, he couldn't find a parking spot and was late for
his first class.
   Crecine and junior David Ritchie traded places Thursday, an idea
of Tech's Student Foundation, which raised money by raffling off the
president's job for a day.
   When the president and the student exchanged car keys _ Crecine
inherited a 1981 Cutlass Supreme, while Ritchie drove off with the
president's new Chrysler New Yorker _ Ritchie offered tips on
parking spots.
   But Crecine still had trouble, showing up 15 minutes late for his
8 a.m. calculus class.
   ``This is embarrassing,'' he said, interrupting class. ``About
the best I can hope for is that there will be no pop quizzes.''
   Ritchie abolished parking fees for the day and thought about
canceling classes, but realized it would let Crecine off the hook.
His day was full: a speech to officials of the Ford Motor Co., a
briefing on plans to restructure the school's academic departments,
and a meeting about the need for more library funding.
   Crecine did enjoy his leisure time.
   ``The notion of having some time where you get to concentrate on
something longer than five minutes is refreshing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FERRISBURG, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Or is it Ferrisburgh?
   That's the question that seems to have troubled the town since
the original charter of 1762, when both spellings, with and without
the ``h'' appeared on different parts of the now yellow document.
   The most visible sign of the debate today is that the U.S. Post
Office for Ferrisburg stands right next door to the Town Clerk's
Office for Ferrisburgh.
   Town Clerk Paul Hoffman, who favors the Ferrisburgh spelling,
says he believes initially there was an ``h'' at the end of the word
because the town originated from a land grant.
   Webster's New World Dictionary defines ``burg'' as a fortified or
walled town, ``burgh'' as a chartered town, Hoffman explained. The
town is about 20 miles south of Burlington.
   The Ferrisburgh Historical Society officially re-adopted the
``h'' more than a decade ago, but the word never reached the state
or federal governments. The Post Office still spells it Ferrisburg,
as does the 1988 Vermont Year Book, which lists the town's
population at 2,117.
   At the Little Otter Creek General Store, even families disagree.
Owner Donald Myers said he has always added the ``h.''
   His wife, Margie Myers, does not. ``To be perfectly honest, I
didn't know it was spelled with an `h,''' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it came down to a choice of Atlantic
Coast Conference basketball or President George Bush, Republican
Gov. Jim Martin decided the president could wait.
   The governor chose to attend the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill vs. North Carolina State University basketball game,
which was held at the same time as the president's address Thursday
to a joint session of Congress.
   ``I'll watch it later,'' he said, adding he would record the
speech. ``My son, Ben, wants to go (to the game), so I can
rationalize it that way.''
   The governor said he would remain neutral at the game, which was
won by N.C. State, 98-88.
   ``I'm supporting both (UNC) Coach (Dean) Smith and (N.C. State)
Coach (Jim) Valvano _ and that's in alphabetical order,'' he said.
</TEXT>
