<FIRST>r a AM-People-Kean     02-10 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Kean,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kean To Become Drew University Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Thomas H. Kean, a two-term governor and
former classroom teacher who has championed educational causes, was
named Friday as the president of Drew University.
   Kean, who is barred by state law from seeking a third consecutive
term, will assume the post when he leaves public office in January.
   ``Governor Kean's first career was in education and we're
delighted he is returning to the academic world by coming to Drew,''
said Nancy S. Schaenen, chairwoman of the 123-year-old university's
board of trustees. The board unanimously elected him.
   Kean met with the student body shortly after the announcement. He
said he hoped to raise the visibility of the school, which has 2,200
students.
   ``What I'm looking forward to now is learning from you,'' he told
the students at the school's Baldwin Gymnasium. ``To the best of my
ability, I'm going to spend time with the student body because I
want you to teach me.''
   ``With his background in politics, he's going to be able to do
some things for Drew that others can't do,'' said Tammy Ahrens, a
21-year-old junior political science major. ``His charismatic
leadership will help put us on the map.''
   Kean, 53, an Episcopalian, will become the first non-Methodist to
hold the top job at the private university, which opened in 1866 as
a Methodist seminary. He will be Drew's 10th president.
   Kean, who gave the keynote address at the Republican National
Convention last August, taught American history and English at St.
Mark's, the preparatory school he attended as a student in
Massachusetts. He also taught history and political science at
Rutgers University.
   But Kean's record on education has not been without controversy.
   The governor's aid package to school districts this year dwindled
along with tax revenues. He also recommended no overall increase in
aid for the state's colleges and universities, and cut $60,000 from
the aid package for Drew University itself. The aid to the school
last year was $985,000.
</TEXT>
