<FIRST>r i AM-Laos-US     02-10 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laos-US,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laos, U.S. Businessman to Cooperate on Tourism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Laos has signed an agreement
for a joint venture in hotels and tourism with a U.S. businessman,
according to a Laotian news agency.
   The report described the deal as the first cooperation between
the Laotian Trade Ministry and an American businessman in 10 years.
   The Laotian news agency KPL said the agreement involves
restoration of hotels and promotion of tourism in Champassak,
Savannakhet and Vientiane, the capital of Laos. Golf courses are to
be put down in some provinces, KPL said.
   Somphavan Inthavong, deputy minister of trade and foreign
economic relations, signed the agreement with Donald W. Scott of
Brunswick, Maine, and Boun-Om Lattanavong, a Laotian living in the
United States, the agency said in a report received Friday in
Bangkok.
   In the past two years, Laos has followed many communist countries
in seeking Western investment.
   Scott's wife, Marilyn, said in Maine that her husband is an
independent businessman who specializes in real estate.
   This is his first business venture in Southeast Asia, but he has
traveled there many times in the past five years as a result of his
involvement in refugee resettlement efforts, she said. Mrs. Scott
had no other details on the venture.
   She said she and Scott, 49, became involved in refugee work,
mainly in camps in Bangkok, through their work in the U.S. medical
relief program Project Concern in Vietnam in the late 1960s. Mrs.
Scott said her husband played a key role in the 1986 resettlement of
a group of more than 200 of the Montagnard people from Vietnam, most
of whom settled in Greensboro, N.C.
</TEXT>
