<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     02-10 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Emperor Addresses Japanese Parliament for First Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Akihito opened a new session of Japan's
parliament on Friday in his first appearance before the body since
ascending to the throne last month.
   The parliament, or Diet, began a new session with legislators
gearing up for stormy sessions over a widespread stock scandal.
   The 55-year-old monarch, clad in a morning suit, said Japan is
expected to promote world peace and prosperity and to act as a
nation that cherishes both culture and nature.
   ``I sincerely hope the Diet will fully perform its mission as the
highest organ of state power,'' Akihito said in his brief speech.
His father, Emperor Hirohito, died of cancer on Jan. 7.
   Later Friday, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and other top
officials of the majority Liberal Democratic Party addressed
Parliament.
   Takeshita reiterated earlier pledges for political reform to
``restore the people's trust in politics.''
   ``All of us who have positions of responsibility in politics are
being called upon to take the initiative in exercising restraint ...
and in ensuring that our positions are upright,'' Takeshita said as
members of the political opposition jeered.
   Opposition parties are widely expected to disrupt next week's
parliamentary proceedings with demands that Takeshita or other top
leaders resign to take responsibility for the scandal.
   About 150 influential politicians, bureaucrats and executives
have been implicated in the scandal arising from purchase of shares
in Recruit-Cosmos Co., a real estate subsidiary of the employment
information conglomerate Recruit Co.
   The scandal has produced more than 20 resignations, including
those of three Cabinet members of the governing party and three
opposition members.
   The shares were legally purchased before public listing and then
later sold publicly at a large profit. However, critics say the
purchasers were still morally wrong and subject to influence as a
result of the transactions.
   Opposition boycotts over the scandal could delay passage of the
most important item on Parliament's agenda, a proposed national
budget of about $48 billion.
   The Parliament adjourned until Monday, and its regular session is
expected to last until May 28.
</TEXT>
