<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SecurityRisks     02-10 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Security Risks,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Blast Proposed Bush Order on Security Clearances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union officials representing federal, defense
and nuclear workers vowed Friday to try to block a proposed
presidential order that would eliminate protections accorded their
members during security investigations for the past 29 years.
   They promised to go to court or Congress if necessary to stop the
plan now under consideration by the Bush administration.
   Among other provisions in the 21-page draft order, applicants for
positions in the federal government and defense plants could be
denied a security clearance _ and even a job _ without explanation
or right of appeal.
   A copy of the draft now being circulated to 30 federal agencies
for comment was obtained by The Associated Press.
   ``I think it's really an outrageous action,'' said Bob Tobias,
president of the National Treasury Employees Union. He said his
union would ask congressional appropriations committees to bar any
spending to implement the order if it is signed by President Bush.
   John N. Sturdivant, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, which represents 700,000 federal workers,
called the proposal ``unreasonable and unfair.'' He said his union,
the largest one for federal workers, ``would be reviewing the draft
to determine whether court action to block it is possible.''
   ``This union would be appalled at such an action,'' said Pat
Ziska, spokesman for the Machinists union, which has 200,000 members
who work for military contractors, mostly aerospace companies.
``It's very frightening, a real threat and shock to us.''
   Nolan Hancock, legislative director of the Oil, Chemical and
Atomic Workers union, said, ``This is a far-reaching order and it's
not in the best interests of our workers or of national security if
somebody could arbitrarily revoke clearances.''
   The proposed order also has stirred opposition at the Senate
intelligence committee and elsewhere on Capitol Hill and among
interest groups such as the American Civil Liberties Union.
   Job applicants denied clearance and workers with low-level
clearances who are denied access to more secret information would be
stripped of their existing procedural rights to challenge damaging
information. Workers whose clearances were being revoked would see
their appeal rights curtailed under the proposed order.
   The order would establish the first governmentwide standards for
background investigations _ a goal long sought by both executive
branch and congressional study groups.
   It would require more thorough investigations than are done now
for initial clearances and would require a new investigation every
five years for those with top-secret clearance and at least every 10
years for those with secret clearance. Some recently apprehended
spies have not been reinvestigated for many years _ sometimes as a
result of lack of manpower.
   The order would authorize security officers to determine whether
a worker or applicant ``has exploitable vulnerabilities or has
engaged in any exploitable conduct or indiscreet behavior''
including ``criminal or dishonest activity, alcohol or substance
abuse, or exploitable sexual conduct.''
   Security agents also are to determine whether the individual
``has a history of mental, emotional and financial stability,'' the
order said.
   ``An employee could be denied a security clearance or an upgraded
clearance because of an administrative error or simply because of
personal dislike,'' AFGE's Sturdivant said. ``What harm would be
caused by giving these employees the reasons for a denial? It's
certainly not a question of national security.''
   Tobias, whose Treasury employees union represents 140,000 federal
workers, said, ``People will be summarily discharged if they fail to
get the security clearance. There are many jobs for which the
security clearance is required and if they lose it they'll be
fired.''
   He said his represents all the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
employees, all of whom must have security clearances, as well as
many Energy Department employees whose jobs require security
clearances.
   The same impact was predicted in the private sector.
   The Machinists' Ziska said, ``Lifting a clearance could mean a
lower paying job or firing. With vague standards, this could be used
against union shop stewards and leave a lot of room for abuse.''
   Hancock, whose Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers union represents
10,000 workers at privately owned nuclear plants, said, ``If they
don't have a security clearance in those plants, they don't work.
And they don't get paid waiting around the hearings that are
provided now, although it takes weeks and months to get through them.
   ``Under this, your clearance could be revoked for reasons that
have nothing to do with national security, but more to do with your
personal behavior.''
   Last October, the House intelligence committee said there were
2.8 million Pentagon workers and 1.1 million defense industry
employees whose jobs required security clearances. In addition, all
employees of the CIA, FBI and National Security Agency must have
clearances as must numerous Energy and Treasury Department employees.
   ``Circulation of the proposed executive order is the Bush
administration's first opportunity to review the question of access
to classified information,'' said National Security Council
spokesman Bob Hall.
</TEXT>
