<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JudgeProtest     02-10 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge Protest,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge To Slow Down Work Over Killed Pay Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief federal judge for southern Ohio says
he intends to work at a slower pace because Congress killed a 51
percent pay raise, and says other judges have called to say they
sympathize.
   ``I've had a number of them (fellow judges) call me and
congratulate me for saying it,'' U.S. District Judge Carl B. Rubin
said Friday. ``I don't ask anybody to join me. It's a matter of your
own conscience.''
   Rubin, a 17-year federal judge nominated to the bench by
President Nixon, said his slowdown would not involve criminal cases,
most of which must be heard within periods defined by the federal
speedy trial law.
   But Rubin, who prides himself on moving quickly to resolve civil
lawsuits, said he would hear those cases at a slower pace.
   ``All I'm doing is, I'm going to the level of the average federal
judge. That's all I'm doing,'' Rubin said. ``Would you rather that I
got a picket sign and walked in front of the Capitol?''
   S. Arthur Spiegel, another judge in the Cincinnati federal court,
said he sympathized with his colleague. ``I'm certainly disappointed
that we didn't get our raise,'' Spiegel said.
   The third judge in Cincinnati, Herman J. Weber, declined to
comment.
   Members of Congress and federal judges are paid $89,500 a year.
Under intense criticism from voters, Congress voted Tuesday to block
a proposal which would have automatically raised pay to $135,000
annually. President Bush signed the legislation.
   Rubin, 69, said he will limit himself to two civil trials a
month, starting with his oldest cases. Instead of a lawsuit going to
trial within a year in Rubin's court, it now will take the national
average of approximately 20 months, he said.
   ``I'm not willing to take this lying down,'' Rubin said. ``I
believe I have been dealt with unjustly.''
   He calculated he would be working at $100 an hour _ 900 hours a
year, or approximately 20 hours a week.
   Rubin said his current salary buys less than his first $40,000
salary as a federal judge 17 years ago. He said he would need at
least $120,000 a year to restore the purchasing power he had when he
was appointed.
   ``I do this with great reluctance. I just don't know any other
way. I'm not going to go on strike,'' he said.
   One effect of Rubin's decision could be to delay out-of-court
settlements, since some lawsuits are resolved just before they go to
trial, said Robert A. Pitcairn Jr., a lawyer who frequently
practices in federal court.
   ``One of the strengths of Judge Rubin was his control of his
docket and how hard he worked,'' Pitcairn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
