<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   02-10 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Relief Flight Arrives; Afghan Official Expects Soviet Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered jet brought 30 tons of
wheat and dried milk to Kabul's neediest residents Friday, beginning
a U.N. airlift after a two-day delay.
   In New Delhi, Afghan Ambassador Abdul Samad Azhar said he expects
the Soviet Union to continue arming his government after the Red
Army withdrawal is completed Wednesday.
   Azhar told a news conference: ``We will not rely only on their
material support, on their food supplies, in the future but also on
their military supplies and their moral support.''
   Soviet military transport planes have been flying food to Kabul,
which is packed with two million people and surrounded by guerrillas.
   He accused the United States and Pakistan of trying to prevent
peace by continuing to aid the Moslem guerrillas who began fighting
after a communist coup 11 years ago.
   The U.N. airlift was to have begun Wednesday, but was delayed by
a change of airlines.
   An Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 707, emblazoned with ``UN'' on one
side, arrived with 238 bags of supplies for distribution to 30,000
people considered the most vulnerable in one of Kabul's bitterest
winters of recent years.
   Guerrilla blockades and attacks on supply convoys created severe
food and fuel shortages as the Red Army packed up and left after a
nine-year campaign against the insurgents that cost 15,000 Soviet
lives.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and an
estimated 115,000 were in the country when the withdrawal began May
15 under a U.N.-mediated agreement. Feb. 15, next Wednesday, is the
deadline for all to be gone.
   Pakistan's official news agency said the U.N. relief flight took
off from Quetta, a southwestern city 65 miles from the Afghan
border, and another flight with 36 tons of dried milk would be made
Saturday.
   Thirty centers in Kabul will distribute the food beginning
Sunday, said Steffan de Mistura, a spokesman for the U.N. Office of
Economic and Humanitarian Assistance to Afghanistan.
   ``This is a small step, a small shipment which we hope will be
able to make a real difference to the lives of some of the
vulnerable groups in Kabul that have been suffering from a hard
winter and being caught in the middle of war,'' said Ross Mountain,
deputy drector for Afghanistan of the U.N. Development Program.
   An estimated 350,000 people in Kabul have been seriously affected
by food and fuel shortages. U.N. officials say those suffering the
most are children aged 1-5, pregnant women and nursing mothers.
   About 400 tons of food, medicine and blankets will be flown to
Kabul in a 10-day period, weather permitting, de Mistura said.
   Soviet military jets began bring bringing flour, canned meat and
other staples to the city last month. Dozens of Soviet transports
land in Kabul every day, but Soviet officers say the airlift will
stop when control of the airport is turned over to the Afghan army
next week.
   More than 6,000 tons of flour has been flown in so far this
month, about half the amount intended by the withdrawal deadline,
Soviet officials said.
   The Soviet supplies are distributed on a coupon-rationing system,
but only government employees and supporters of the Communist Party
have access to the coupons.
   When Friday's U.N. flight arrived, de Mistura said: ``I find it
rather beautiful that after many years when the United Nations has
been airlifting goods into Ethiopia, it is the Ethiopian airline
that helps out the U.N.''
   Michael Keating of the World Food Program said the crew had no
problems on the flight.
   In neighboring Pakistan, Afghan rebels met to choose a future
Islamic government for Afghanistan, but guerrillas based in Iran
boycotted the council because of a feud with the Pakistani-based
faction.
   A spokesman for Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, chairman of the guerrilla
alliance based in Pakistan, said the meeting would adjourn
``indefinitely'' while a compromise was arranged.
</TEXT>
