<FIRST>r w AM-DiscriminationSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0668 02-10 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Discrimination Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Charges Operator of Fitness Centers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with details of department's investigation; adds
byline. Note contents of graf 10, bgng ``The manager,'' may be offensive
to some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of Holiday Spa fitness centers in
six states was accused by the Justice Department on Friday of
discriminating against blacks who seek membership in the exercise
clubs.
   In a civil suit filed here in U.S. District Court, the department
charged that U.S. Health Inc. had instructed its employees to
discourage blacks from joining the Holiday Spas and offering less
favorable membership terms.
   The company operates spas in Maryland, Virginia, Massachusetts,
New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Georgia as well as the District of
Columbia.
   In a complaint signed by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, the
department sought a court order to enjoin further practices which it
said violated the public accommodation section of the Civil Rights
Act of 1964.
   The lawsuit, filed by the department's civil rights division,
charged that staff members were told to offer less favorable
membership and credit terms for black applicants than were offered
to whites.
   In addition, the suit charged that the Towson, Md.-based company
violated the Equal Credit Opportunity Act, by denying financing for
membership fees to blacks.
   ``Defendant has made statements, in account of race and color,
that would discourage a reasonable black person from making or
pursuing a credit application to purchase a membership and-or
entitlement to use the facilities of its health and fitness
centers,'' the complaint stated.
   A reporter's telephone call seeking comment from the company was
not immediately returned.
   The Justice Department found that a manager in Media, Pa., told
employees that white, middle-class executives were the ``favored
clientele,'' according to a report of the agency's investigation.
   The manager ``stated that the presence of blacks would interfere
with this regular business, describing a scenario of a prospective
white member seeing `niggers' in the swimming pool,'' the report
said.
   The manager told employees ``whites won't patronize a place if
there is a mix of races,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
