<FIRST>r a AM-LotteryDispute     02-10 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lottery Dispute,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winner of $1.3 Million Pennsylvania Lottery Prize Disputed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten car dealership employees who routinely pool
money to buy lottery tickets are challenging a co-worker's claim
that she and her husband alone won a $1.3 million jackpot before she
quit her job, their lawyer said Friday.
   State lottery officials said Friday they would hold up payment of
the jackpot until they determine the rightful winner of the Feb. 3
Wild Card Lotto drawing, which is worth $63,190 a year for 21 years
before taxes.
   ``They could go to court,'' said lottery spokeswoman Jane Shafer
in Harrisburg. ``They may settle out of court. We're like a stakes
holder. We're just waiting to find out who is the rightful party to
pay.''
   Officials said a woman and her husband, whom they refused to
identify, walked into the state lottery office in the northwestern
Pennsylvania town of Meadville on Monday with what was apparently
the winning ticket.
   Later that day, attorney John Petruso filed a counter-claim for
the same prize on behalf of 10 people, said Judy Terrell of the
Meadville lottery office.
   The dispute involves workers at Smith-Gray Cadillac Oldsmobile in
Meadville, 10 of whom pooled $50 to buy tickets for three lottery
drawings, one Feb. 3 and two the following week, Petruso said.
   Names of the 10 participants were written on an envelope, he
said. He declined to identify the woman who bought the tickets for
the other workers, but said she was not one of the participants in
the drawing.
   Petruso said the woman told a co-worker on Sunday that none of
the pool's tickets were winners, but that a ticket she and her
husband bought won.
   At work Monday, Petruso said, ``she was congratulated by
everybody. Then at some point, there were questions asked as to
where the ticket came from.'' He contended it came from the pool's
block of tickets.
   The woman quit her job Tuesday, he said.
   Shafer said ownership disputes have occurred ``two or three
times'' in the lottery commission's 17-year history.
   The winning ticket was one of a block of $1 tickets bought at the
same time, Shafer said. But she wouldn't disclose how many tickets
had been bought or whether the winning one was in the middle of the
block or at an end.
   Maxine Percy, who sells lottery tickets at the store where the
disputed ticket was bought, said she couldn't recall who bought the
tickets.
   ``No one can remember what she looks like,'' said Percy. ``She
came in quite a bit, but nobody paid much attention. She just bought
them for all the guys at Smith-Gray.''
   Lottery officials said the period of several weeks for processing
a lottery jackpot helps ensure that possible challenges will be
filed before money is paid.
   They said that period was lengthened in part because of a fraud
case last year. The lottery ``winner'' drew the first annual check
before it was discovered the ticket was phony.
</TEXT>
