<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Wives     02-10 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Wives,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush, Mila Mulroney Read Nursery Tale to Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kids got a real hoot Friday out of Barbara Bush
and Mila Mulroney.
   Within minutes of arriving in Ottawa with President Bush, who
left to meet with Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, Mrs. Bush and Mrs.
Mulroney spent about 30 minutes visiting more than 250 young
children at a school.
   They read from the book ``Owl Moon,'' stumbling momentarily over
who was to handle the hooting despite the handy instructions pasted
to pages by aides.
   ``It's terrible ... sorry,'' Mrs. Bush said after inadvertently
delivering a series of hoots intended for her partner.
   Later, the two fielded questions.
   Mrs. Bush, 63, was asked whether she liked being the wife of a
president.
   ``I have loved being George Bush's wife for 44 years, so yes,''
she said.
   Mrs. Mulroney, 36, assured the children there was a lot of work
but ``prime ministers' wives have a lot of fun.''
   Each listed her duties, from running households to answering mail
and working for favorite causes such as literacy and AIDS research
for Mrs. Bush and cystic fibrosis research for Mrs. Mulroney.
   ``But all of them are so much fun and so important that I don't
feel like it's work,'' said Mrs. Bush.
   The children gathered in a gymnasium in one wing of an old
convent school where they were entertained in a sing-song by a
guitar-playing duo who crooned such favorites as ``Jimmy Crack
Corn,'' ``Zippity Do Da'' and ``Skinamarinky Do.''
   Among them was 3-year-old Nicolas Mulroney, who snuggled between
the two while they read to his playmates.
   The gym walls were adorned with youthful handiwork: signs of
welcome, a banner reading ``Hands Across the Border'' and Canadian
and U.S. flags.
   The children greeted the visitors with a song written for the
occasion: ``Hello ladies. What do you say? It's going to be a happy
day.''
   Natalie Ryan, 11, said it sounded like the women had wonderful
lives because ``you always get to go everywhere and you always have
security guards and aides to look after you.''
   After the visit, the women toured the National Art Gallery,
stopping to admire works depicting the windswept shores of central
Ontario lakes.
   A reporter asked Mrs. Bush if she knew many of those same lakes
were dead or dying as a result of acid rain _ a topic atop the
agenda of her husband's meeting with the prime minister.
   ``They're beautiful,'' she said of the paintings before walking
away. ``They're beautiful.''
</TEXT>
