<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     02-10 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Raid Palestinian Homes, Boy Loses Eye</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers raided homes in six West Bank towns and
villages Friday and seven Palestinians were wounded by army gunfire
in scattered clashes, including a 15-year-old who lost his eye, army
and Arab reports said.
   In the West Bank town of Bir Zeit, activists of the Palestinian
Communist Party staged a march to mark the seventh anniversary of
the party's founding. The party is illegal in Israel.
   About 100 people took part, marching with red banners and
Palestinian flags, witnesses said. Many hid their faces behind Arab
keffiyehs, or checkered headdresses, or used black hoods with eye
slits.
   Arab hospitals reported that seven Palestinians suffered gunshot
wounds in stone-throwing clashes with Israeli soldiers, including a
12-year-old boy and an 11-year-old girl.
   In the Gaza Strip town of Rafah, a 15-year-old Arab boy, Anwar
Suleiman El-Eid, was hit in the eye with a rubber bullet and lost
the eye, Arab reports said. The army command confirmed a 15-year-old
was injured in Rafah but had no other details.
   The army conducted raids in Qalqilya, Jenin, Kussera and Tulat in
the north and Hebron and the nearby village of Dahariya in the
south, detaining Palestinians suspected of firebomb attacks or
threats against fellow Arabs viewed as pro-Israeli collaborators, a
spokeswoman said.
   The spokeswoman, who cannot be identified in keeping with army
regulations, refused to say how many people were arrested.
   The raids came two days after an Israeli settler died in a car
fire near the West Bank settlement of Alfei Menashe.
   Police initially said Albert Jerassi's car was firebombed but
later said they were unable to pinpoint the cause of the blaze.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, residents began a three-day
strike to protest the death of a 17-year-old resident killed when
military guards opened fire Wednesday to quell a riot in the Megiddo
prison in northern Israel. Nidal Zuhdi Deeb was one of two prisoners
killed in the incident.
   He was the 380th Palestinian to be killed in the uprising.
Fifteen Israelis have died.
   Also Friday, the army destroyed a house in the village of Burkin
near Jenin. It was the home of a Palestinian youth ``suspected as
one of the ringleaders'' in the uprising, the army said.
   The army also informed nine families their homes would be
destroyed or sealed as punishment for anti-Israeli activities. The
notice apparently was given in advance to give the families time to
appeal, Israel radio said.
   Israeli troops have destroyed or sealed more than 190 homes in
the occupied lands since the uprising began.
</TEXT>
