<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-MissileDebate     02-10 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Debate,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Wants NATO Decision on Modernization Delayed Until 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl fears a
controversial NATO proposal to upgrade some European nuclear
missiles would spoil opportunities for arms control, and he is
expected to press NATO to delay the decision three years.
   Kohl's spokesman told reporters Friday the chancellor sees no
reason for the alliance to decide prematurely on the question of
``modernization'' of short-range missiles when no decision is
necessary before 1991 or 1992.
   A NATO decision on whether to proceed with plans to replace
U.S.-made Lance missiles with longer-range rockets had been expected
in June, when Kohl and leaders of the other 15 alliance members
gather for a summit in Brussels.
   The United States, Britain and other NATO members have made clear
they intend to reaffirm the decision taken five years ago that calls
for replacement of aging short-range missiles.
   But West Germans have been demonstrating increasing resistance to
the plan because of what they see as improved opportunity for
disarmament progress in light of troop reduction proposals by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``We want no decision during this dynamic disarmament process,''
Kohl's spokesman, Friedhelm Ost, said at a news conference.
   ``We will discuss all of the elements of our strategy'' at the
Brussels summit, Ost said, ``but we want to leave our options open.''
   Kohl said in an interview published Friday that the Lance
missiles ``remain sufficient and intact until 1995,'' and that the
alliance should put off its decision on modernization for the next
three years.
   He also rejected the view of some allies that West Germany's
position on modernization will be a test of its loyalty to the
alliance.
   ``It doesn't interest me at all if others see this as a sort of
litmus test,'' Kohl told the British daily Financial Times. ``I have
to represent German interests, and I am a reliable partner.''
   Public opinion polls show that 75 percent of West Germans favor
removal of all nuclear weapons from Europe and that an even larger
percentage see no serious security threat from the East.
   Those sentiments run counter to NATO policy, which has demanded
the Warsaw Pact's superiority in conventional weaponry be reduced
before the West trades away its nuclear options.
   At an annual NATO strategy session in January, West Germany took
a verbal beating from allied defense experts for dragging its feet
on the question.
   Ost denied that the delay in making a decision was connected to
nationwide elections scheduled for December 1990. Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union has lost ground in regional contests the past two
years.
   The modernization plan would replace all 88 Lance launchers and
the more than 700 missiles deployed with the firing units. The new
missiles would be capable of reaching targets 300 miles away,
compared with their current range of 75 miles.
   The replacement missiles would bring the NATO short-range
capability to the threshold of the medium-range class, which is
being abolished under the December 1987 U.S.-Soviet agreement.
   Soviet and East-bloc officials contend the modernization program
is intended to make up some of the ground bargained away by the
medium-range agreement and that such a move would jeopardize arms
control efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FarmLabor     02-10 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Labor,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number Of Workers Hired Declines Sharply In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of workers hired by farmers showed a
sharp decline to an estimated 701,000 in January from 976,000 last
October, partly seasonal but also because of poor weather
conditions, the Agriculure Department said Friday.
   Those did not include 152,000 ``agricultural service'' workers
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors. Last fall, those
totaled 274,000 workers.
   The report said ``substantial rains'' occurred during the Jan.
8-14 week when the labor survey was made, from eastern Texas into
the middle Atlantic states.
   The report said the national figures for hired workers had a
sampling error of 4.1 percent.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $5.51
per hour, up from $5.18 during last fall's survey week of Oct. 9-15.
   For workers hired by contractors, there was no national wage rate
available. However, workers in California were reported at $6.42 per
hour in January, up from $6.16 last fall, and Florida at $5.79 in
January and $4.98 last fall.
</TEXT>
