<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Soybeans     02-10 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Soybeans,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Allowed To Plant 80 Percent Of Acreage Requested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who signed up to produce 1989 soybeans
on land normally used to grow other crops will be allowed to plant
80 percent of the acreage they had requested, Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter announced Friday.
   Yeutter also said farmers who asked to plant sunflowers, another
oilseed crop, on 1989 land normally used for the other crops will be
allowed to plant all that they requested.
   The options were authorized by Congress in last year's Disaster
Assistance Act, which was drawn up to help farmers recover from the
devastating 1988 drought.
   Normally, farmers have to use their ``permitted acreage'' under
the government's programs for wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice in
order to protect their crop base, or history of plantings.
   But the legislation authorized the Agriculture Department to
allow soybeans and sunflowers on the acres without farmers losing
their acreage history.
   The law also directed USDA to adjust the special plantings so
that the expected additional production doesn't force the 1989
market price of soybeans below $5.49 per bushel, or 115 percent of
the 1988 price support level.
   After reviewing the acreage requested by farmers, Yeutter said it
was decided to trim the additional 1989 soybeans to 80 percent of
the 3.5 million acres they had signed up to plant.
   Sunflower producers asked to plant 353,000 acres on their other
cropland, and they will be allowed 100 percent of what they sought.
</TEXT>
