<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Superior Court jury convicted Peter T.
Trepanier Friday on 27 counts stemming from a series of sniper
attacks that terrorized northern Rhode Island two winters ago.
   The jury found Trepanier guilty of six counts each of assault
with intent to commit murder and conspiracy to commit murder,
resulting from six sniper attacks that wounded four people in
Cumberlanhfield in December 1986 and January 1987.
   Trepanier was also convicted of three counts of first-degree
arson and six countd and North Smits each of conspiracy to enter a dwelling
and
entering a dwelling with intent to commit larceny in housebreaks and
house fires in Burrillville and Glocester from April to June 1987.
The arson charges carry a maximum penalty of life in prison.
   Trepanier was acquitted on two charges, both relating to a
seventh burglary.
   Trepanier, 25, stared at the court clerk and showed no emotion as
the verdicts were read. There was no reaction from spectators in the
crowded courtroom.
   Superior Court Judge Dominic F. Cresto dismissed charges
pertaining to an eighth burglary and a seventh sniper attack before
the case went to the jury on Tuesday, saying there was not enough
evidence to support them.
   During the time of   Prosecutor Eva Marie Mancuso said before the trial
began that her
case would be based on circumstantial evidence.
   She summoned ballistics experts to link a rifle found in Stump
Pond in Smithfield to bullet fragments and casings found at the
scene of several of the shootings, although the experts were unable
to establish a definite link because they could not test the rifle
itself.
   Paula Laliberte, a friend of Trepanier's, testified that
Trepanier confessed to her about the burglaries and snipings several
hours before she persuaded him to turn himself in to police.
   John J. Hardiman, Trepanier's lawyer, portrayed Trepanier as a
jokester and attention-getter who confessed to crimes to get
publicity, and said Trepanier's knowledge of the crimes was gathered
from the media.
   Trepanier and Ducharme also face charges in two sniping attacks
in Bellingham, Mass., just north of the Rhode Island border.
Massachusetts authorities said they were waiting for the Rhode
Island cases to finish before pressing charges.
