<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Deficit     02-10 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Deficit,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Banker Says `Nyet' To Helping Trim Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Soviet banker said Friday that if government
ministers knock at his door seeking cash to eliminate the
government's budget deficit, the answer will be a firm ``nyet.''
   The statement by Vyacheslav S. Zakharov, deputy chairman of the
board of the Soviet State Bank, showed a rare rift in the government
about how to tackle the country's financial woes.
   Zakharov said the State Bank already has handed over to the
government 63.4 billion rubles _ about $102 billion at official
rates _ and is not eager to give any more.
   Some economists have projected the deficit will reach $160
billion this year, although Zakharov put the figure at $56 billion.
The total Soviet budget is $789 billion.
   Zakharov appeared to become angry when asked at a news conference
whether his bank would help erase the red ink.
   ``It is the difficulty of the Ministry of Finance. And the
Ministry of Finance must deal with its own problems on its own,''
said Zakharov.
   Later, he said the deficit is the ministry's ``responsibility,
its trouble, its misfortune.''
   Aside from the money it already contributes, he said: ``The state
bank will not give one kopeck more for the financing of budget
expenses.''
   A loan could be offered, but only if interest were charged,
Zakharov indicated.
   Economists have suggested various ways of eliminating the
deficit. Oleg T. Bogomolov, director of the Institute of Economics
of the World Socialist System, told reporters Wednesday that the
government could sell land and import video recorders and personal
computers and tax them up to 10 teims their value.
   Leonid Abalkin, director of the Economics Institute, suggested
Jan. 25 that the deficit be reduced by scrapping some production
targets and closing unprofitable businesses. In addition, he told a
news conference, expensive construction projects could be canceled.
   Also at Friday's news conference, Mikhail Y. Nakhmanovich, deputy
chairman of the Soviet Savings Bank, outlined how his institution is
trying to get customers to spend their money.
   Soviets have amassed savings of $480 billion, and the savings
bank loaned just 3 billion rubles last year, Nakhmanovich said. To
encourage clients to use the bank, he said, 77,000 branches have
been opened offering 10 kinds of accounts that pay 2 percent to 4
percent interest.
   The savings bank introduced checkbooks last year, and so far 1
million have been given out, Nakhmanovich reported.
   Authorities would also like to introduce credit cards, he said,
but there aren't enough computers to run a credit card system.
Construction of one Soviet banking computer center was started 14
years ago and is still incomplete. Zakharov blamed construction
workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
