<FIRST>r w AM-DurumWheat     02-10 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Durum Wheat,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Expected To Be World's Largest Exporter This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community this year is
expected to be the world's largest exporter of durum wheat used to
make pasta products, a trade usually dominated by the United States
and Canada, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   ``Because of this year's drought-induced short crop in North
America, the increase in (EEC) exports has been achieved somewhat
easily,'' the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said. ``But
if the U.S. and Canadian durum crops return to their normal size in
1989-90, the competition for export markets may become tighter.''
   The report said the EEC had a ``good harvest and unusually large
carry-in stocks'' of durum wheat this season.
   ``As in the past with a host of other commodities, the (EEC) has
responded by dumping its surplus on the world market through the use
of large export subsidies,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
