<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Jamaica Bjt   02-10 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamaica, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manley Seeks Good Relations with Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister-elect Michael Manley said
Friday he will visit Washington to establish the ``widest and most
constructive'' relationship possible with the Bush administration.
   He said he had met with U.S. Ambassador Michael G. Sotirhos about
the trip and wanted to make it as soon as possible. Manley, 64, led
a leftist Jamaican government in the 1970s that alarmed the United
States, but has moved toward the political center.
   Manley spoke to reporters and members of the Jamaican diplomatic
corps at a news conference the day after his general election
victory over conservative Prime Minister Edward Seaga, a staunch
U.S. ally.
   Unofficial results gave his People's National Party 44 seats in
Parliament to 16 for Seaga's Jamaica Labor Party. Manley led Seaga
in the popular vote 57 percent to 43.
   The Electoral Council was recounting some districts and stopped
releasing official tallies shortly before midnight Thursday, when
with 65 percent of the ballots counted Manley's party led Seaga's
with 429,680 votes to 324,486.
   Seaga had held all 60 parliamentary seats since 1983, when he
called an election after the U.S. invasion of Grenada and Manley
boycotted it in a dispute over voter registration.
   Thursday's results were in line with pre-election opinion polls,
despite widespread allegations of ballot-stuffing and voter
intimidation.
   In a conciliatory concession speech Thursday night, Seaga said
``The people have spoken and we abide by their decision,''
indicating he had no plan to challenge the results.
   Shootings and stabbings took 13 lives during the three-week
campaign period, including two on election day, but the scale of
violence was nothing like the mayhem of 1980. An estimated 700
people were killed in that nine-month campaign.
   ``I am very, very proud of my country to have made that much
progress,'' Manley said Friday. He noted the violence did not touch
Montego Bay and the other big tourist resorts along Jamaica's north
coast.
   Manley said his first priority at home would be to foster peace
between rival political groups and that church leaders had agreed to
hold an ecumenical ``service of national peace and unity'' Sunday,
the day before he is sworn in. Both he and Seaga are expected to
attend.
   Socialist policies Manley pursued in his first two terms as prime
minister, from 1972 to 1980, alienated foreign investors as well as
the United States. In recent years, however, he has moved from
radicalism to pro-U.S. ``social democracy.''
   Asked Friday to respond to skepticism about his more moderate
image, Manley said: ``What's my answer? What I say and what I do.''
   His previous administration taught him the damage confrontations
with the United States can cause, Manley said. ``The first thing we
learned was that getting into any kind of squabble doesn't help.''
   He repeated his pledge to restore diplomatic relations with
communist Cuba, which were broken by Seaga, but said it was ``not
top of the agenda.''
   While in Washington, Manley said, he wants to meet key figures in
the Bush administration, Congress and such major lending agencies
such as the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
   Of his ``very specific objectives'' for the visit, ``the first is
to establish on the widest and most constructive possible basis the
relationship with the new administration of President Bush,'' he
said.
   Manley said he would consult with the Drug Enforcement
Administration to improve cooperation against the transit of
narcotics through Jamaica and will seek a bipartisan campaign
against drugs and guns on the island.
   Seaga, 58, was seeking an unprecedented third consecutive term.
He broke relations with Cuba upon taking office in 1980 and was an
outspoken supporter of the 1983 U.S. invasion of Grenada.
   To restore the economy, he instituted a series of austerity
measures, including higher taxes and a devaluation of the Jamaican
dollar, that cut deeply into the buying power of workers who already
were poorly paid.
   The campaign focused more on personalities than issues, with
Manley seen as a charismatic champion of the people and Seaga as
representing the interests of big business.
   On Friday, the prime minister-elect said his government would be
``genuinely willing to listen.'' He described Seaga's as
``essentially autocratic.''
</TEXT>
