<FIRST>r i AM-Syria-Hostage     02-10 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Syria-Hostage,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Hostage's Sister Prays in Ancient Church for His Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DAM1</HEAD>
<HEAD>By NICK LUDINGTON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAALOULA, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of Terry Anderson prayed Friday
in one of the oldest churches in the world for the release of her
brother, an American hostage in Lebanon; for better U.S.-Syrian
relations and for peace in war-battered Lebanon.
   Peggy Say hung a barcelet engraved with her brother's name on a
cross on the altar of the Greek Catholic church of St. Sergius,
built about 300 years after the death of Jesus.
   With the local priest, Father Michael Zarura, Mrs. Say prayed
that her heart be healed after the captivity of her brother and the
death of her father and another brother, for ``the healing of
relationships between our countries and the hearts of the people in
Lebanon so they may live in peace.''
   Zarura prayed, ``here, in the oldest church in the world, that
your wishes come true and that Terry Anderson is in good health.''
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East Correspondent for The Associated
Press, was seized by Shiite Moslem extremists on March 16, 1985.
   A native of Lorain, Ohio, Anderson is the longest-held of 15
foreign hostages in Lebanon. They are eight other Americans, three
Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian.
   Mrs. Say is in Syria to meet Syrian officials who have been
cooperating in attempts to free the hostages.
   She came to this ancient Christian site at the suggestion of
Jodeph Atiyeh, 30, a Syrian-American of Baton Rouge, La. Atiyeh, a
1984 Olympic silver medalist in wrestling, works as an oil
consultant in Syria and the United States.
   Mrs. Say and Atiyeh met in the lobby of a Damascus Hotel.
   ``We came to pray for a miracle,'' Mrs. Say said after hearing
that Maaloula is the center of the last tiny region in the Middle
East where Aramaic, the language of Jesus, is spoken, and that it is
the site of reported miracles in the early history of the Christian
church.
   Mrs. Say and Atiyeh also prayed at the chapel marking the hiding
place of St. Takla, described as the first female Christian martyr
who was converted to Christianity by St. Paul.
   Miracles attributed to St. Takla include creation of a holy
spring near the chapel, carved out of a rock cliff.
   Sister Agatha Homsy, of the convent built around the chapel,
showed Mrs. Say and Atiyeh the spring where faithful may drink from
a metal cup.
   ``I'm a believer and I believe that water has some real bounce to
it,'' Atiyeh said after he and Mrs. Say drank.
   The Rev. Raymond Barnet, 52, a Protestant minister of Vancouver,
British Columbia, who is accompanying Mrs. Say, also prayed in the
chapel and asked for a miracle for the persecuted and for ``that
special miracle you alone can grant, freedom for Terry Anderson and
all the hostages.''
   Barnet's organization, Friends in the West, is active in seeking
the hostages' release.
   Syria is believed to have played a useful role in the release of
French and German hostages last year, acting as mediator among
countries with hostages in Lebanon, Iran, and pro-Iranian Moslem
groups holding captives.
   Syria has close relations with Iran and was its only major Arab
ally in the Iran-Iraq war. It has 40,000 peacekeeping troops in
Lebanon and is the major powerbroker there.
   Lebanon's main Shiite spiritual leader, Sheik Mohammed Mehdi
Shamseddin, was quoted in an interview published there Friday as
saying he was not hopeful for an early settlement of the hostage
issue because of ``new complications,'' which he declined to explain.
   The weekly magazine Ash-Shiraa quoted Shamseddin as calling on
``those capable of putting an end to this issue to do so because it
is a dark spot in our image.''
</TEXT>
