<FIRST>u w AM-US-Jamaica 1stLd-Writethru a0685 02-10 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Jamaica, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Hopes for Friendly Ties with Jamaica</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Jamaica, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS in last graf to hurricane, instead of earthquake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday congratulated
former Prime Minister Michael Manley on his party's victory in
Jamaica's national elections and expressed hope that his return to
power there will not mean a strain in U.S.-Jamaican relations.
   When Manley headed the government from 1972 to 1980, relations
with Washington soured partly because of Jamaica's close ties to
Cuba. But State Department spokesman Charles Redman noted that
Manley has said that in contrast to his earlier period in office, he
envisions no large Cuban presence or influence on the island.
   ``In our view, Cuba is more than ever an anachronism in a
hemisphere marked by a dramatic return to democracy in the 1980s,''
Redman said.
   ``We have talked about these things before, but Cuban repressive
practices at home and support for subversion and instability abroad
argue, in our view, against reintegration in the hemispheric
community,'' he added.
   A decade ago, the State Department was troubled by Manley's
radical rhetoric. During a 1979 visit to Cuba, he said that no
region in the world had suffered more from imperialist penetration
than the Caribbean had at the hands of the United States.
   Redman noted that Manley pledged during the election campaign to
pursue policies to promote Jamaica's continued economic development
in an atmosphere conducive to private sector activities and foreign
investment.
   ``Importantly, he has been clear and firm in stating his
determination to work vigorously to combat narcotics problems. He
has clearly stated he wants good relations with the United States
and we share that objective,'' Redman said.
   The United States was elated in 1980 when Manley was soundly
defeated by Prime Minister Edward Seaga and his Jamaica Labor Party.
   Seaga was elected just five days before Ronald Reagan won the
U.S. presidential election and close ties were forged quickly after
Reagan's inaugural. Seaga was one of Reagan's first foreign visitors
and he cooperated closely with the United States in the 1983
invasion of Grenada in which Jamaica joined the United States and
several other Caribbean countries in toppling the leftist regime
there.
   The Reagan administration embraced Seaga as an avowedly
anti-communist democrat who espoused free enterprise principles. It
hoped that Jamaica would emerge as a model of capitalist development
in the Third World.
   But officials said that Seaga's free enterprise policies did not
match his rhetoric, and there was open disappointment here over the
performance of the Jamaican economy, a situation which was greatly
aggravated by a disastrous hurricane last fall.

</TEXT>
