<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     02-10 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Factions Exchange Prisoners</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Swap Hostages, Slain Druse Buried, Clashes in East Beirut
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Rival Shiite Moslem militias on Friday
exchanged 46 hostages who were captured during factional warfare
last month.
   The trade by the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the
mainstream militia Amal, which Syria supports, was part of a peace
agreement made Jan. 29.
   Syria and Iran mediated the accord, which halted eight months of
intermittent warfare that killed 500 people and wounded 1,500
wounded in Beirut and south Lebanon. The two militias are vying for
supremacy among 1 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest sect.
   Amal freed 33 detainees in Zefta, its security headquarters eight
miles southeast of Sidon in the south. Hezbollah released 13 Amal
fighters at Ein Bouswar, a few miles south of Sidon, police said.
   Police also said Friday that eight people described as civilians
were killed by sniper fire across Beirut's sectarian dividing line
in 10 days, six in Moslem districts and two on the Christian side of
the no-man's-land that cuts the city into Christian and Moslem
sectors.
   Meanwhile, a Shiite official said the International Committee of
the Red Cross had offered to arrange a trade of Lebanese held by
Israel for an Israeli airman captured in south Lebanon more than a
year ago.
   ``The ICRC has asked us to release the Israeli airman so that all
the Lebanese held in the prisons of Israel and its allies be
released,'' said Abdul Amir Qabalan, a Shiite religious judge.
   Qabalan spoke at a rally of about 10,000 people in Deir Qanoun
village, near Tyre in south Lebanon, organized by the Amal militia
to honor members killed fighting Israel.
   Hundreds of Lebanese are believed held in Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' just inside south Lebanon, which
is patrolled by Israeli soldiers and an allied militia.
   Navigator Ron Arad's plane crashed in south Lebanon while on a
bombing mission Oct. 16, 1986, and Amal said it captured him.
   Red Cross officials could not be reached for comment on Qabalan's
remarks.
</TEXT>
