<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Terrorists     02-10 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Terrorists,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigatsing Magistrate Wounded by Terrorists Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent investigating magistrate died
Friday of gunshot wounds suffered in a terrorist attack a month ago.
   Constantine Androulidakis, 52, who had been in a coma for 24
hours, died Friday morning, Evangelismos Hospital said.
   Androulidakis was shot at least three times as he prepared to
drive to work Jan. 10, and witnesses said three men fled in a car.
November 17, the most notorious terrorist group in Greece, claimed
responsibility.
   He was one of two magistrates November 17 claimed to have shot in
an attempt to intimidate the judiciary for its alleged involvement
in the acquittal of two businessmen charged with fraud in the early
1980s.
   Pnayiotis Tarasouleas, 66, a Supreme Court prosecutor, was
wounded by a lone gunman Jan. 18 and hospitalized for several days.
   The terrorist group has claimed 12 killings since it emerged in
1975 with the assassination of Richard Welch, CIA station chief in
Greece.
   It also took responsibility for the slayings of two other senior
U.S. Embassy officials and several Greek businessmen, publishers and
police officers. None of its members has ever been arrested.
   November 17 takes its name from the date of a 1973 uprising
against the military dictatorship then in power by students at the
Athens Polytechnic Institute. The uprising was crushed by soldiers
with tanks.
   Another terrorist group, May 1, claimed responsibility for
assassinating magistrate Anastasios Bernardis on Jan. 23. Pamphlets
scattered near the scene accused him of ``covering up the crimes of
capitalists and crooked unionists.''
   The group first became known in 1987, when it claimed
responsibility for wounding labor leader Giorgos Raftopoulos.
</TEXT>
