<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-PayRaises     02-10 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Pay Raises,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Puts Raises On Back Burner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday it's too
early to recommend a new package of pay raises for Congress, judges
and federal executives, saying he wants to ``let the dust settle''
on the explosive issue.
   Answering questions from reporters aboard Air Force One en route
to his vacation retreat, Bush bemoaned the refusal of the House and
Senate this week to approve 51 percent pay raises for themselves and
for top figures in the other two branches of government.
   The president reiterated his statement of Wednesday, saying
signed legislation rejecting the pay raises because he respected the
sentiment of the members of the House and Senate. The pay raise was
overwhelmingly turned down in both chambers.
   ``All I can do is make recommendations to the Congress about the
future legislation,'' Bush said. ``Having talked to some of the
leaders up there, I'm not sure the timing is right for that.''
   He said there has been ``a lot of wounds, a lot of hemorrhaging
up there. And I don't want to do something that'll look like I am
simply trying to step into the breach and raise a problem that has
caused a great deal of divisiveness in the Capitol.''
   Bush had said all along that he supported the substantial pay
raises for members of Congress, which would have elevated their
salaries from $89,500 to $135,000 a year, and he repeated that
Friday.
   ``When I signed that bill (rejecting the raise), I made a comment
about my feeling that the judicial salaries should go up. I am on
record as favoring an increase for members of Congress and senior
executives,'' he said.
   ``We've got to do something,'' the president said, signaling out
the National Institutes of Health as an example of a federal agency
that likely would suffer a loss of talent under existing pay scales
for top federal executives.
   ``But now,'' he said, ``I've got to rely on my people here to
make a recommendation to me, when I can be effective for the changes
that I think are overdue.''
   ``But what you don't want to do is come in and, when the wounded
are still lying on the battlefield, start fighting another battle,''
Bush said.
   ``Let's take a little time,'' he added. ``If I felt that a
specific recommendation out of the president right now ... would
have the effect of achieving what I've just spelled out ... I'd do
forward right now.''
</TEXT>
