<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Iraq Bjt   02-10 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top diplomats from Iran and Iraq met
face-to-face on Friday and agreed to hold talks next month in New
York in an effort to revive their deadlocked peace negotiations.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar mediated the
meeting between Foreign Minister Tariz Aziz of Iraq and Foreign
Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and their aides in a basement conference
room at U.N. Headquarters.
   ``It was a short meeting in which I found real cooperation with
both foreign ministers,'' the U.N. chief said after the 90-minute
meeting.
   He said Aziz and Velayati agreed to hold more substantive direct
meetings in New York in late March. The talks are to be preceded by
discussions this month between U.N. officials and representatives of
both countries.
   ``The idea is to give a new impetus to the peace process,'' Perez
de Cuellar said.
   Velayati said of Friday's session: ``We have only had procedural
talks.''
   But he said Iran still maintains that the next step of the peace
process should be an immediate withdrawal of forces to the prewar
boundaries of both countries.
   Iraq still occupies 260 square miles of Iranian territory it
seized during the 8-year-old war with Iran.
   This week, Aziz released a letter to Perez de Cuellar insisting
that Iran must first relinquish its right to search ships in the
Persian Gulf for Iraq-bound war cargo.
   Aziz also said Iran should show it sincerely wants peace by
agreeing to cooperate with a U.N. plan to dredge the Shatt al-Arab
waterway that forms the southern border between their nations.
   The waterway, which is blocked by silt and sunken ships, is
Iraq's outlet to international waters.
   Aziz left without offering any substantial comments.
   Velayati and Aziz seemed more comfortable this week than they had
in previous negotiating sessions held in Geneva and New York.
   On Wednesday, the Security Council unanimously called on Iran and
Iraq to stop stalling on implementing the U.N.'s peace plan.
   The demand coincided with a remarkable series of disclosures in
the Iranian media, in which Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
said Tehran had overreached its grasp during the nearly eight-year
war.
   ``We took too big a bite,'' Rafsanjani was quoted as telling the
official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   ``Yes, we wanted something, but were not able to get it, and that
was military victory. If we had moved with a bit more planning maybe
it would not have been so far off,'' said Iran's Parliament speaker.
   Iraq had accepted a U.N. call for a cease-fire in 1987, but Iran
did not agree to the truce until July after suffering humiliating
defeats during an Iraqi advance on the battlefield.
   Since the cease-fire took effect Aug. 20, Iraq has often accused
Iran of seeking the truce only to halt its military losses.
   Peace talks that opened five days later in Geneva immediately
deadlocked.
   Iran says the cease-fire is in effect, and the rest of the U.N.
peace plan should be implemented. The peace plan calls for
withdrawing armies to the border, exchanging prisoners of war, and
negotiating a settlement to the conflict.
   Baghdad, however, says the cease-fire is not legally in place
because Iran has not relinquished its right to search ships in
international waters of the gulf for war cargo bound for Iraq.
   Both sides have shown flexibility in recent weeks over secondary
measures. Iran pledged to drain an artificial lake it built between
the opposing forces in the southern front near the Shatt.
   Iraq suspended a warning to civilian air traffic not to fly into
Iran. That ban had previously forced Iran-bound flights to detour
north through Turkey.
   Baghdad and Tehran have agreed to set up a joint commission of
military officers to discuss complaints of cease-fire violations
along their 730-mile front line.
   The joint commission will be led by officers of the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group, which monitors the truce.
   Both sides have released small groups of sick and injured
prisoners of war, which raised hopes that the International
Committee of the Red Cross might be able to register and repatriate
about 100,000 POWs held by both sides.
</TEXT>
