<FIRST>u a AM-Husband-Guardian 3rdLd-Writethru a0790 02-10 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Husband-Guardian, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0790,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede ALBANY</HEAD>
<HEAD>New York's Top Court, Supreme Court Denies Motions by Abortion Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with preparations for abortion begin, new
comment from husband, anti-abortionists, father. No pickup. CHANGES byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors prepared to perform an abortion on a
comatose woman after the U.S. Supreme Court on Friday rejected
efforts by two anti-abortion activists to stop her husband from
authorizing the procedure.
   ``Tough battle but we won it,'' said the husband, Martin Klein.
``We can now turn our attention to trying to help Nancy. Justice has
been done.''
   The abortion opponents waged a two-week legal fight to prevent
Klein from becoming his wife's guardian to authorize an abortion
that doctors said could help her recover.
   New York's highest court Friday refused to hear an appeal by the
two anti-abortion activists, and U.S. Supreme Court Justice Thurgood
Marshall, who handles New York cases, later turned down their
request for a stay.
   The Court of Appeals and Marshall rejected the motions without
comment.
   Klein said he learned of Marshall's decision while at North Shore
University Hospital on Long Island where his brain-damaged wife has
been in a coma since a Dec. 13 car accident. Mrs. Klein, 32, is 17
weeks pregnant.
   ``I told Nancy that everything was going to be fine. I gave her a
kiss and came home,'' Klein told The Associated Press from his home
in Upper Brookville.
   Klein, 34, and his wife have a 3-year-old daughter.
   Dan Rosett, a hospital spokesman, said the hospital is preparing
to perform the abortion Saturday morning. Another spokeswoman, Carol
Hauptman, said doctors Friday night gave Mrs. Klein medication that
is routinely administered about 12 hours before an abortion is
performed.
   John Short, who along with John Broderick, fought Klein for
guardianship rights, said they would ask Supreme Court Justice
Antonin Scalia to impose a stay so the case can be brought before
the full Supreme Court.
   ``They are criminally assaulting her and killing her child,'' he
said Friday night. ``It is tragic but we are pulling out every stop
we can.''
   He said they would pursue the case even if an abortion is
performed so that the questions raised by the case can be resolved.
   A Nassau County police officer was stationed in the hospital and
a police cruiser was parked out front Friday after hospital
officials were told the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue might
try to stop the abortion.
   The hospital said pro-choice activist Bill Baird had warned of
possible action by Operation Rescue.
   Thursday night, the Court of Appeals granted a temporary stay of
a lower state appeals court decision in Klein's favor. On Friday,
the judges of the top court met for more than four hours to review
the case.
   The five-member Appellate Division of the state Supreme Court in
Brooklyn, calling the abortion opponents, Short and Broderick
``absolute strangers,'' ruled Thursday that they ``have no place in
the midst of this family tragedy.''
   Short said Thursday he was concerned about about the
``psychological and emotional state'' of Nancy Klein if she wakes up.
   ``Under our plan, we say the baby's down at the neonatal clinic
getting the best care possible,'' he said. ``Under their plan,
they've got to tell her they've killed her baby. Emotionally, that
would kill her.''
   Mrs. Klein's parents, Frederick and Anne Zusselman of Delray
Beach, Fla., have been staying with their son-in-law during the
court battle and support his decision to seek an abortion.
   ``Life will never be the same. It was too terrible. And then to
have the complications come in and the publicity,'' said Zusselman
on Friday. ``This has been such a horrendous ordeal. I hope no one
will ever have to experience what we have.''
   ``We're really torn apart. We've been up and down on a roller
coaster. These people have put us through absolute hell,'' Zusselman
added.
   The Appellate Division judges said Thursday previous New York
court decisions had established that strangers will not be appointed
legal guardians unless it's impossible to find someone within the
family to serve in that role.
   Klein had first petitioned to be named his wife's guardian on
Jan. 26. One day later, the anti-abortion activists moved to block
his petition.
</TEXT>
