<FIRST>u a AM-Blodgetts-Husband 1stLd-Writethru a0733 02-10 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blodgetts-Husband, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Urges No Abortion In New York Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Husband-Guardian Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CORRECT that Blodgett's never faced abortion
choice, and UPDATE with Marshall turning down request for stay in New York
case. Picks up 6th graf, `Blodgett said...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a woman who gave birth while
in a coma urged a New York man on Friday not to have his comatose
wife's pregnancy terminated, saying medical experts can be wrong.
   ``We should take whatever God has given us and that's the way it
is,'' said David Blodgett Sr., whose daughter-in-law, Barbara
Blodgett, was three months pregnant when she suffered a brain injury
in a June 1988 auto accident.
   Mrs. Blodgett, 24, gave birth to a healthy baby boy, Simon, on
Dec. 9. Despite a gloomy prognosis, she began regaining
consciousness shortly after the birth, and can now sit up in a
wheelchair, answer questions by nodding her head or pointing to
letters on a piece of paper, and hold a bottle to Simon's lips.
   Blodgett said he spoke Friday morning with John Broderick, one of
two anti-abortion activists who are fighting Martin Klein, 34, of
Upper Brookville, N.Y., to be appointed guardians of Klein's wife
Nancy, 32, and her fetus.
   New York state's highest court on Friday refused to let Broderick
and John Short intervene in the case. The abortion opponents
immediately filed a motion for a stay with U.S. Supreme Court
Justice Thurgood Marshall, who handles New York cases, but he turned
down their request late Friday.
   A spokesman at North Shore University Hospital on Long Island
said doctors were preparing to perform the abortion Saturday morning.
   Blodgett said he called Mrs. Klein's mother Thursday morning to
offer information. ``I told her what transpired with Barbie,'' he
said. ``I don't think taking the baby is going to be any benefit to
the mother.''
   Blodgett, who opposes abortion, said he was not able to talk with
Klein.
   Members of Mrs. Blodgett's family point to her recovery as proof
that doctors can be wrong in such cases.
   ``They (doctors) were at one time telling us the same kind of
thing,'' said Greg Valenzuela, Mrs. Blodgett's father. ``All we
asked them to do is make the attempt to maintain both as best they
could. Once they decided to do it, it didn't seem like a major
problem.''
   Blodgett said his daughter-in-law's life was also threatened by
elevated body temperatures caused by the brain injury, and that the
antibiotics used to treat the fever were a threat to the fetus. But
there was never any serious consideration of trying to save one over
the other, he said.
   Mrs. Klein, who is 17 weeks pregnant, has been in a coma at a
Manhasset, N.Y., hospital since a Dec. 13 car accident. She is
severely brain-damaged and given a slight chance at recovery. Klein
said some physicians advised him that an abortion may enhance her
recovery and could save her life.
</TEXT>
