<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;LWithdrawals     02-10 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Withdrawals,1st ld-writethru, a0780,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 15th graf to CORRECT name of S&amp;L to Savers of Little Rock,
Ark.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savers withdrew a record $8.1 billion from the
nation's thrift institutions in December, but $3.4 billion of the
total was accounted for by a single, healthy institution which was
shrinking deposits as part of a deliberate strategy, the government
said Friday.
   The withdrawals topped the one-month record of $7.0 billion set
in November, bringing the net outflow for two months to $15.1
billion, said the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates
2,955 federally insured savings institutions.
   Meanwhile, in a separate development, the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. said Friday it had taken control of six more savings
institutions, bringing to 10 the number of S&amp;Ls brought under the
agency's control since President Bush on Monday gave it that
responsibility under his plan for the S&amp;L crisis.
   The December outflow, the eighth consecutive, was happening at a
time of mounting publicity about S&amp;L problems. Regulators closed or
merged 75 institutions that month.
   But, Bert Ely, a financial institutions analyst in Alexandria,
Va., said money was moving out of S&amp;Ls because their interest rates
are moving up more slowing than other investments, not because
depositors were nervous.
   ``I don't think people are losing confidence. ... What this is
signaling is we have an industry ... that is under real pressure
because of these rising rates,'' he said.
   Ely noted some accelaration in the increase of interest paid to
S&amp;L depositors and said rates would likely be forced higher as the
Federal Reserve Board tightens credit in an effort to dampen
inflation.
   ``They have to start matching the rising rates and, boy, that's
hard on the bottom line. This does not bode well for thrift
earnings,'' he said. The industry, on the way to a record year of
red ink, lost $9.4 billion in the first nine months of 1988.
   According to minutes released Friday of a Dec. 13-14 meeting of
Federal Reserve policymakers, the central bank decided to push up
interest rates. The lone dissenter was Federal Reserve Board member
Martha Seger, who ``expressed particular concern that the higher
interest rates ... would aggravate'' the troubled condition of the
S&amp;L industry, the minutes of the Federal Open Market Committee said.
   Economist Martin Regalia of the National Council of Savings
Institutions said the president's effort this week appears to have
bolstered confidence in savings institutions.
   ``If you look at the stock market, they look at this whole
process as being a net plus. Thrift stocks have risen in the last
few days because I guess they feel the problem is being addressed,''
he said.
   James Barth, chief economist of the bank board, said a single
institution shrank its deposit base by $3.4 billion, on purpose,
substituting low-cost borrowing.
   He also noted that money normally flows out of savings accounts
in December as people spend to celebrate the holidays.
   For all of 1988, $8.4 billion flowed out of S&amp;Ls, compared with
$1.8 billion in 1987. The annual record of $25.4 billion was set in
1981, when interest rates soared and money flowed into money market
mutual funds and other alternatives to savings accounts.
   The six institutions taken over by the FDIC, under a cooperation
agreement with S&amp;L regulators, are: First Federal of Arkansas,
Little Rock, Ark.; Savers Federal Savings and Loan Association,
Little Rock, Ark; Sandia Federal Savings and Loan Association,
Albuquerque, N.M.; Bright Banc, Dallas; University Savings
Association, Houston, and Deseret Federal Savings and Loan
Association, Salt Lake City.
   FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman said his agency, which insures
commercial bank deposits, will take control of more than 200
insolvent S&amp;Ls in the next four to six weeks.
   In an interview Friday, he confirmed published reports that top
administration officials were worried that a faster takeover could
trigger a depositor run. He said the Federal Reserve Board put
together a plan to pump money into the S&amp;L system in the event of a
problem.
   ``There were people inside the government who were very
concerned,'' Seidman said. `` ... I was on the other side, but I was
just as eager to have a (contingency) plan just in case.''
   He said he believed the danger to the S&amp;L system had eased now
that Bush had submitted his S&amp;L proposal to Congress.
</TEXT>
