<FIRST>r w AM-UkrainianDancers     02-10 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukrainian Dancers,2nd ld-writethru, a0785, 380</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eds: To update with Izvestia report, new graf after 8th graf previous
``Gillman said'' ^By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company of Ukrainian ballet dancers down on
their luck spent Friday as tourists in the nation's capital as
American benefactors tried to find theaters that would book them.
   The 65 dancers, members of the Donetsk State Opera and Ballet
Theater, had been left in Baltimore after promoters of their 15-city
American tour backed out, leaving them without work, costumes or
music.
   The experience has left the dancers with warm feelings about the
Americans who stepped forward to pay their hotel and meal tabs, but
it has soured them on the dog-eat-dog world of capitalist show
business.
   Vadim Pisarev, the troupe's lead dancer, said of American
businessmen, ``They're very harsh. They're very dangerous.''
   ``I will be very upset if we can't continue,'' he said through an
interpreter.
   Howard Gillman, who has paid most of the costs of housing and
feeding the dancers through a foundation that bears his name, said a
decision has to be reached in the next few days on arranging a new
tour or sending the troupe back to the Ukraine.
   ``This is something you do in a year,'' he said. ``This has to be
done in days.''
   Gillman said the troupe has landed one booking in New York city
later this month.
   In Moscow, the newspaper Izvestia reported that an affiliate of
the Soviet government arts agency has reached an agreement to keep
the tour going. A schedule is being worked out, the newspaper said.
   The collapse of the tour has led to a crossfire of accusations,
with the promoters saying the dance troupe did not show up with big
Russian stars as promised, while the other side accuses the
promoters of having cold feet and empty wallets.
   In the meantime, the dancers have been shepherded through a
series of outings, finding free entertainment in museums.
   On Friday, they toured the Capitol, the White House, the National
Gallery of Art and the Smithsonian's Air and Space Museum.
   When they're not strolling through a museum, the dancers have
done what most people with time on their hands do: They watch
television.
   Lots of it.
   ``They have so many programs and they're so interesting,'' said
Vyachaslav Bilinsky, one of the dancers. The only complaint, he
said, is that the commercials are driving them crazy.
</TEXT>
