<FIRST>r i AM-Azores-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0745 02-10 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Azores-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Leaves For Italy With 15 Bodies from Azores Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with bodies shipped to Italy; CORRECTS
name of destination to Puerto Plata, sted Puerta. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILA DO PORTO, Azores Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A silver-and-white Italian
air force C-130 transport plane left Friday night with coffins
bearing the remains of 15 victims of the jetliner disaster that
killed 144 people on Santa Maria island. Earlier Friday,
investigators located the jet's flight data recorder.
   Inside the transport, the name-tagged coffins, some decorated
with flowers, were strapped to the floor for the flight to Bergamo
in northern Italy.
   Portuguese and Italian officials attended a brief memorial
service in a makeshift morgue at Santa Maria airport to bless the
coffins.
   Authorities said they expected a second Hercules transport,
waiting on the tarmac, to leave Saturday with 64 more coffins. A
third plane was to depart Sunday.
   All but two of the 137 passengers were Italian, and the seven
crew members of the U.S. charter were Americans. All on board were
killed.
   The Boeing 707, operated by Independent Air Corp. of Smyrna,
Tenn., crashed into rugged Pico Mountain on Wednesday while
preparing to land in fog on a mid-Atlantic refueling stop en route
from Bergamo to Puerto Plata, a vacation spot in the Dominican
Republic.
   On Thursday, Portuguese civilian aviation officials found the
jet's cockpit voice recorder. The flight data recorder was found
Friday in its proper place in the cockpit, said Jose Martins
Freitas, head of the Azores rescue service.
   Investigators hope information on the voice and data recorders
will explain why the aircraft hit the 1,947-foot mountain just below
its peak.
   On Friday, Italy's transport minister, Giorgio Santuz, suspended
all of the company's flights from Italy to the Dominican Republic.
He said the suspension would remain in effect while the
investigation continued.
   The jet's captain, Leon Daugherty of Nashville, Tenn., had been
cleared for landing with a safety altitude of 3,000 feet.
   A team from the U.S. National Transportation Safety Board flew to
the island, about 750 miles west of the Portuguese mainland, to join
Portuguese officials in the investigation.
   Freitas called off the search for victims Thursday, saying the
remains of all but two were found. Airport workers, however, said
the remains in their care accounted for only 132 bodies.
   Giovanni Battistini, Italy's ambassador to Portugal, said
authorities agreed to ship to Italy ``all remains that can be put
together as corpses.''
   Italian Air Force Lt. Col. Geno Proner said the coffins
containing the American crew's remains also would be flown to Italy,
most likely Rome.
   Italian officials said earlier they would be allowed only to ship
identifiable remains to Italy. By nightfall, fewer than 30 victims
had been positively identified.
</TEXT>
