<FIRST>u a AM-Obit-Hays 4thLd-Writethru a0798 02-10 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Hays, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0798,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wayne Hays, Former Congressman, Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CO8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with two grafs with wife saying he suffered a heart attack.
Picks up 3rd graf, `Hays began...'. INSERTS one graf after 16th graf, `He
was...', with 1976 Ray quote. SUBS last graf, `Besides his...' to UPDATE
with private services on Monday and to CORRECT to one daughter survives
sted two.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. CLAIRSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne L. Hays, a 14-term congressman
whose affair with House clerk Elizabeth Ray in 1976 touched off a
payroll-sex scandal and destroyed his political career, died Friday.
He was 77.
   Hays suffered a heart attack at home Friday afternoon, said his
wife, Pat. He was taken to Wheeling Hospital in nearby Wheeling,
W.Va., where he died, said hospital spokeswoman Linda Crook.
   Hays began his political career in 1939, when he was elected
mayor of Flushing in rural eastern Ohio. He was elected to his first
term in the U.S. House in 1948, with 51.4 percent of the vote.
   He ended his national political career after nearly 28 years in
Congress when he resigned Sept. 1, 1976, to stop a House Ethics
Committee investigation into his conduct. Public hearings were to
begin 2{ weeks later.
   ``I think he did it to save his family,'' Carl Albert, then House
speaker, told reporters after receiving Hays' resignation letter.
   The Ethics Committee then voted to end its three-month
investigation of the scandal on grounds that Hays no longer was a
congressman and no longer under the panel's jurisdiction.
   The Justice Department, which also was investigating, decided not
to prosecute. Department attorneys said they lacked evidence
corroborating the account of Ms. Ray, the House clerk, and her
relationship with Hays.
   After leaving office, Hays returned to his 300-acre Red Gate Farm
in Belmont, where he bred Angus cattle and Tennessee walking horses.
   In 1978, Hays made a comeback of sorts with his election to the
Ohio House. There, he pushed bills aimed at curbing big utilities
and promoting Ohio coal, but generally kept a low profile. One
exception came during an incident in which he threatened to punch a
television cameraman during a hearing.
   He was defeated in a re-election bid in 1980.
   In 1980, Hays became chairman of the Democratic Party in Belmont
County and remained active in local party politics.
   Hays and his first wife, Martha, were divorced in 1976 after 38
years of marriage. That same year, Hays married Pat.
   The sex scandal broke during the spring of 1976. Hays first
denied, then acknowledged having an affair with Ms. Ray, then 33.
But he steadfastly denied her charges that she was kept on his
Administration Committee payroll at $14,000 a year in federal funds
only to have sex with him. Hays maintained that she did regular
committee work.
   He was among congressmen who asked for the Ethics Committee to
begin an investigation in May 1976 when Ms. Ray made the allegations
in a story in The Washington Post.
   ``I can't type, I can't file, I can't even answer the phone,''
Ms. Ray told the newspaper.
   Hays first denied the charge to the Post, saying, ``Hell's fire!
I'm a very happily married man.''
   But three days later, in an emotional speech before the full
House, Hays admitted he lied when he denied having the relationship
with Ms. Ray, who began working for his House Administration
Committee in April 1974.
   Hays later said he lied because he did not want his new wife to
find out about it.
   On June 3, 1976, five days before the Ohio primary, Hays bowed to
mounting pressure from colleagues and stepped down as chairman of
the House Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
   Despite Hays' Washington reputation as mean and abrasive and the
Capitol Hill bully, many of his heavily blue-collar constituency saw
him as a man who got things done, such as pushing through pensions
for black-lung coal disease or getting official documents such as
Army discharge papers and passports.
   He could stand at a rally and call voters by their first names.
He sent greeting cards to mark marriages, anniversaries, births and
graduations.
   In a rally in Smithfield, at the height of the scandal, Hays
said, `` ... I'm not guilty of anything except a little damn
foolishness. And if they sent everybody to jail who made a mistake _
and I made one and I apologize for it _ well, you know there
wouldn't be enough to go around ... jails, that is.''
   Although he won the 1976 primary with 62 percent of the vote, the
scandal dashed his hopes of running for governor.
   Two days after the primary, Hays was rushed to a hospital in a
coma from an overdose of Dalmane, a sleeping tablet his doctors had
prescribed for him during the scandal. He emerged from the coma in
less than 24 hours but remained hospitalized for nine days.
   Hays later said the overdose was accidental: ``If I wanted to
commit suicide, there were 30 or 40 more pills in the bottle, and I
could have taken all of them and that would have done it.''
   Besides his wife, Hays is survived by a daughter and two
grandchildren. A burial service on Monday will be private, a family
friend said.
</TEXT>
