<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Lincoln Adv12   02-10 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Lincoln, Adv 12,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Feb. 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Historians Take Another Look at Lincoln</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GETTYSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On his 180th birthday, Abraham Lincoln
still makes news, and historians continue to revise the reality and
try to deflate the myths attached to the country's 16th president.
   The latest attempt to flesh out the portrait is ``The Historian's
Lincoln: Pseudohistory, Psychohistory and History.'' According to
the work's editor, Gabor S. Boritt, the book ``takes some of the
best (Lincoln) writers in the past decade and sums up what they have
to say.''
   What they have to say, in short, is that the man who freed the
slaves, preserved the union and delivered the Gettysburg Address was
afraid to be intimate with women, had an unappreciated sense of
humor and remains a complex subject that requires further study.
   Boritt, a Gettysburg College professor and a leading Lincoln
scholar, said Lincoln continues to be a subject of fascination and
examination because he is both a central figure of American history
and mythology.
   In the introduction to the 416-page book, published to coincide
with the 180th anniversary of Lincoln's birth on Feb. 12, Boritt
wrote that since his assassination in 1865, Lincoln has been viewed
as both a man and a god, a dual role that troubles historians:
   ``Whatever the public thought, the compromise whereby the common
man captured the Illinois years and the divine one the presidency
could not be satisfactory for scholars, since it suggested an
inexplicable transfiguration. Accordingly, they have labored through
much of this century to bridge the gap.''
   In addition to bridging the gap, ``The Historian's Lincoln'' also
uses relatively new tools to examine the president.
   For instance, Charles B. Strozier, editor of Psychohistory
Review, devotes a chapter of the book to traits and experiences that
helped form Lincoln's personality.
   ``Lincoln's story fades into legend,'' Strozier wrote. ``As a
result we are probably better informed about the trivial anecdotes
and more confused about the significant events of his formative
years than about those of any figure in American history.
   ``Most of us know, or think we know, a good deal more about his
rail-splitting or his absentmindeness than we do about the shape of
his personality, especially the sources of his periodic, paralyzing
bouts of depression; what gave meaning to his relationship with his
wife and his children; and what made him a uniquely fitted leader
for a nation rent by discord.''
   One section of his essay touches on Lincoln's sex life and his
uneasy dealings with several women, including Mary Todd, who became
his wife. Lincoln broke off two engagements, including one with Mary
Todd, for no apparent reason.
   ``Lincoln, it seems, feared intimacy and had steered clear of
heterosexual union in two relationships,'' Strozier wrote.
   He suggests it took the marriage of Lincoln's best friend to get
him over his fear.
   ``When Speed (his friend) at last actually consummated his
relationship with Fanny _ and the sky did not fall in _ Lincoln was
liberated from his fear of marriage. Speed experienced what Lincoln
could only fantasize about. He served as a kind of emotional proxy
for his conflicted friend,'' Strozier wrote.
   Such details may seem tame to readers familiar with the tales of
Gary Hart and Jim Bakker, but to historians, such probing was
unheard of until recently.
   ``Not so long ago, a thing like psychohistory didn't exist. These
are ideas and concepts that wouldn't have occurred to people 75
years ago,'' Boritt said. ``It would have been bad manners, it would
have been voyeurism, it would have been unacceptable.''
   Despite the title, Boritt said he demanded that contributors and
critics, whose reactions are also published in the volume, write for
a lay audience.
   ``In the last generation or so, historians have been
inaccessible,'' Boritt said. ``They write only for themselves.''
   He added that if Lincoln scholars write for themselves, the
popular vision of Lincoln will be dictated by Gore Vidal, author of
``Lincoln: A Novel,'' and others whose writings Boritt dismisses as
simplistic and flawed.
   ``The most important thing history teaches you is to weigh the
evidence,'' Boritt said. ``You don't just hop on the bandwagon and
rush off.''
   Boritt, an intense 40ish man seems always in a hurry in person,
but labors over historical points. He spent a decade tracking down
the size of Lincoln's big toe to try to determine if the president
was a victim of Marfan's Syndrome, a rare genetic disorder. Boritt's
conclusion: He probably wasn't.
   The professor is already thinking about his fifth book, yet
another look at the Civil War and Lincoln, from the view of the
British.
   ``Things undiscovered remain yet to be discovered,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Feb. 12</NOTE>
