<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-SexSells Adv12   02-10 0915</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sex Sells, Adv 12,0942</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mixing Merchandising and Libido Makes Newstand Sales Sizzle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: In 6th graf, `sexy sell' in quote is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sports Illustrated didn't invent the concept that covergirls in
skin-tight spandex make newsstand sales sizzle. That idea dawned on
magazine editors about the time they perfected glossy pictures.
   The spectrum now ranges from Four Wheeler magazine, which once a
year compliments the bodies of its trucks with bodies of beauties,
to Cosmopolitan, the women's magazine that thrives on sensuality and
cleavage.
   ``Sex is an attractive commodity if it's packaged well,'' said
Cosmopolitan's editor Helen Gurley Brown. ``Everybody likes to look
at pretty girls in bathing suits.''
   And in Cosmo's business office, there's mock surprise. ``Sex
sells? Nooooooo. Really?'' said Debbie Berg, making the questioner
feel like the farm boy caught looking at lingerie in the Sears
catalogue.
   Fashion designers know it. Health clubs show it. Car dealers grow
on it. Makers of everything from beer, booze and ice cream rake in
dough on it.
   ``Not only does sexy sell, which has been true since God created
women and men, there's a wholesomeness possible about sexiness,''
said Christie Hefner, empress of Playboy Enterprises, which
publishes the world's largest men's magazine. ``It's an acceptable
category of media. It's bigger than it's ever been.''
   Just ask Sports Illustrated. It makes an annual marketing splash
mixing merchandising and libido by showcasing baby-oiled bodies in
see-through mesh rather than the normal fare of athletes dressed in
sweat and grass stains.
   The swimsuit issue, now marking its 25th anniversary, is devoted
entirely to swimwear for the first time.
   This edition may be the best read in the magazine's 35-year
history. An estimated 41 million people, double the average, will
read it, including 13 million women, triple the norm.
   ``The notion that sex sells has been around since the turn of the
century when magazines learned they could reproduce a nice
illustration,'' said David Stewart, a consumer psychologist and
professor of marketing at the University of Southern California.
   ``You tend to get the opposite sex paying attention to the
picture, but a person of the same sex responding to the copy,'' he
said. ``Women like to emulate what they see. They want to know what
are the beauty secrets.''
   The swimsuit issue was born during the midwinter sports doldrums
when a bikini-clad Babette March graced the Jan. 20, 1964, cover.
The idea was to help readers weather the dead time between football
and spring training _ and to help magazine sales.
   The latest one could gross $30 million in sales and spinoffs for
Time Inc.
   The 2.5 million street copies are $3.95 each. The 286-page issue
has 118 pages of ads worth over $15 million. Home Box Office, also
owned by Time Inc., has a 50-minute show on how the issue was made
and has 600,000 orders for a $19.99 videocassette. About 750,000
calendars at $10.95 each are on sale.
   The success of bigger sales with smaller suits tempted
competitors to feature voluptuous women in teensy Lycra straining
against its carnal cargo.
   Inside Sports and Sport magazine have copycat versions. Swimwear
Illustrated and American Swimwear exhibit sultry women in suggestive
apparel, supplying order blanks but not bothering with articles.
   Hot Rod magazine's swimsuit issue last April pumped circulation
28 percent to more than 1 million copies. Four Wheeler, with an
audience that is 90 percent male, sold 156,000 copies or 50 percent
more than normal with a July swimsuit issue.
   ``We got 17 letters of protest, six from women who wrote, `Send
in the hunks.' They thought it was too one-sided,'' said editor John
Stewart. ``How can sex not sell? Why shouldn't it sell?''
   Sports Illustrated's swimsuit issue gets tons of free publicity,
good and bad.
   It was recently spoofed in the Doonesbury cartoon strip. Dick
Bradley, a cartoonist for The Buffalo News, once depicted Hugh
Hefner holding the issue and saying, ``Actually, I read it because
of the interesting, ah, articles.''
   On the flip side, critics blister the jock journal for
sexploitation.
   ``It's about presenting women as bimbos. What is a sports
magazine doing publishing pornographic pictures of women?'' said
Mary Jo Kane, professor of sport management at Bowling Green State
University.
   ``I wish they'd spend half as much time presenting women as
serious athlethes instead of Playboy bunnies. They wouldn't get away
with it if they put stereotypes of racism or anti-Semitism on their
cover,'' she said.
   ``It borrows from pornography. It reduces women to a collection
of body parts. It's a damaging presentation of women,'' said Norma
Ramos, general counsel for Women Against Pornography.
   The swimsuit issue gets censored from school library shelves.
   ``Offensive, indecent and chauvinistic'' was the review from
Kenneth Roetzel, superintendent of schools in New Danube, Minn., who
removed it in 1985. In a letter to Sports Illustrated he said it
``stooped to the moral depths'' of Playboy and Penthouse.
   The debate can even place columnists from the same paper on
opposite sides.
   ``SI's swimsuit issue is little more than a euphemism for soft
porn, Playboy before the public revolution. It is the girlie
magazine men figure they can buy without offending their wives,''
wrote Kathleen Parker of The Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel.
   But the paper's sports columnist Brian Schmitz preferred models
over basketball players. He wrote: ``I'd rather look at Christie
Brinkley in her underwear than Kevin McHale in his.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Feb. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
