<DOCNO> AP890210-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoeingFine     02-10 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Fine,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Paid $125,000 FAA Fine For Failure To Inspect Plane Parts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. paid a $125,000 fine in early 1988
that was assessed by the Federal Aviation Administration for the
company's failure to properly inspect self-locking nuts used in its
airplanes, a company spokesman confirmed Thursday.
   After becoming aware of the defective parts, the company
tightened its specifications for manufacturing and testing the
particular kind of self-locking nut involved, Boeing spokesman Tom
Cole said.
   The fine was the largest ever assessed against Boeing for a
quality-control violation, he said.
   Cole said the nuts are used in various parts of the airplanes,
including flight-control systems for the rudder and wing flaps.
   He said there have been no Boeing planes involved in accidents or
incidents related to failure of the defective parts that he was
aware of. Failure of the self-locking nuts would be unlikely to
cause a serious problem because of backup systems built into the
planes, Cole said.
   Boeing learned in 1985 that some of the nuts in planes delivered
to customers did not meet specifications for torquing and locking,
Cole said. The company sent service bulletins to the customers and
the FAA issued airworthiness directives ordering airlines to check
the nuts and replace them if necessary.
   Cole said Boeing didn't blame the manufacturers who supplied the
defective parts, since it was Boeing's specifications that needed to
be revised.
   Cole said Boeing 767s were involved in the inspections, but that
the self-locking nuts are used on all types of planes the company
manufactures. He said the company paid four other fines of a few
thousand dollars each for lesser quality-control violations.
   ``When we find things wrong we report it to the FAA'' and take
steps to correct it, Cole said.
</TEXT>
