<FIRST>r f PM-RJRNabisco Bjt   02-10 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR Nabisco, Bjt,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Kravis Completes RJR Nabisco Offer As A Defeated Johnson
Departs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc. is in the final
stages of its record $24.53 billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco Inc.,
having completed an epic tender offer for the food and tobacco giant.
   Kohlberg Kravis said it was tendered more than 216.6 million
shares, or approximately 97.2 percent, of RJR Nabisco's outstanding
common stock by the time its $109-per-share offer expired Thursday.
   The investment firm is undertaking the largest U.S. corporate
acquisition ever. The next largest would be the $13.4 billion
purchase of Gulf Oil Corp. by Chevron Corp. in 1984.
   As RJR Nabisco shares changed hands Thursday, so did control of
the conglomerate, which makes such well-known products as Winston
and Camel cigarettes and Oreo cookies.
   Company president F. Ross Johnson, defeated by Kohlberg Kravis in
the takeover fight, resigned as expected and was replaced by J. Paul
Sticht, a former chairman of RJR Industries Inc. RJR Industries
merged with Nabisco Brands Inc. in 1985 to form RJR Nabisco.
   Johnson left praising the people who beat him. ``I feel the
company is in good hands,'' he said in a statement issued by
Kohlberg Kravis.
   It was Johnson who instigated the bidding war for RJR Nabisco
with the announcement Oct. 20 that a management group he led was tendered
nearly 1.2 million
shares, or approximately 95 percent, of RJR Nabisco's preferred
stock. Those shares would be paid for on Friday, the firm said.
   Ruth Pachman, a spokeswoman for Kohlberg Kravis, said it was not
immediately known when the firm would complete the acquisition
because it must obtain federal approval for the new securities
before it can close the deal.
   After the acquisition is completed, Kohlberg Kravis must begin to
divest several food lines to comply with an order from the Federal
Trade Commission.
   In clearing the RJR Nabisco purchase earlier this month, the FTC
said Kohlberg Kravis must sell competing lines of oriental foods,
packaged nuts and ketchup produced by either RJR or another Kohlberg
Kravis unit, Beatrice-Hunt-Wesson Inc.
   Kohlberg Kravis will have a year to sell the product lines. Until
the divestiture is completed, it must run RJR Nabisco as a separate
operation.
   Kravis on Thursday reiterated his company's intention to sell $6
billion in food businesses over the next 18 months to help finance
the deal, which relies heavily on the use of high-interest junk
bonds.
   The purchase of RJR Nabisco is a leveraged buyout, in which a
company is acquired mainly with borrowed funds that are repaid with
money raised by asset sales or the company's cash flow.
   The size of the RJR Nabisco deal has prompted criticism of LBOs
in general and a series of congressional hearings about whether they
should be curtailed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0247 </DOCNO>
