<FIRST>r f PM-Lexus-Lexis Bjt   02-10 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lexus-Lexis, Bjt,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lexus Name May Vanish From Toyota Lineup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lexus name for Toyota Motor Corp.'s new luxury
car division will be history if a federal appeals court rules
against it in a lawsuit, a company official says.
   ``We'll have to change our name,'' Lexus General Manager Dave
Illingworth said Thursday, in the event the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeal in New York rules against it in a lawsuit brought by Mead
Data Central Inc. of Dayton, Ohio.
   Mead Data contends the car maker is illegally diluting the name
of its Lexis legal-information retrieval service.
   Illingworth, who took control of the Lexus Division last month
after Jim Perkins returned to General Motors Corp., said he expects
a ruling from the New York court by the end of the month. But if the
automaker loses, there will be no appeal to the Supreme Court, he
added.
   He said the timing of the launch of the Lexus line, consisting
for now of two sedans, requires that a name be in place by the time
the cars are delivered to showrooms this fall.
   Also, Illingworth said, ``I think it's very doubtful that the
Supreme Court would hear this case.''
   The process for choosing another name has begun, he said, but no
alternative name has been selected. He said he was aware of no
settlement negotiations going on, but that Toyota always has wanted
to resolve the case out of court.
   If the court rules against Lexus and the name is dropped,
Illingworth said, ``Two years from now, nobody will even remember
the old name.''
   During the course of the lawsuit, possible settlements had been
drafted by Mead Data and Toyota, but those will not be resurrected,
Illingworth said.
   Company officials have declined to say how much money is tied up
in the Lexus name, but that it is the millions of dollars.
   ``We aren't that unbusinesslike that we haven't made plans in
case that something unfortunate happens,'' Illingworth said. ``We're
fully prepared to make an adjustment and continue.''
   Lexus plans to sell Japanese-made cars costing between $20,000
and $40,000 in the United States this fall. But before that happens,
Illingworth said he expected a decision on a battle with Mead Data.
   Mead Data sued Toyota last year, claiming that Lexus diluted the
name of its legal-information retrieval service, Lexis. A federal
judge in New York agreed and in December ordered Lexus to stop using
the name.
   The automaker won a stay in the appellate court, which last heard
arguments Jan. 30. It has not said when it plans a ruling.
</TEXT>
