<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McCaw     02-10 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McCaw,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Losses Grow In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the
nation's biggest operator of cellular phone systems, said its losses
more than doubled in the fourth quarter because of acquisition and
start-up costs in new markets.
   McCaw lost $92.2 million on revenue of $91.3 million in the
quarter, more than twice the $44.1 million lost in the same period
of 1987 on revenue of $61.3 million, the company said Thursday.
   Craig O. McCaw, chairman and chief operating officer, said the
losses were expected. He said costs for construction, acquisitions,
debt service and marketing were expected to be substantial.
   For all of 1988, McCaw Cellular had net losses of $297 million on
revenues of $310.8 million, compared with net income of $89.9
million on revenues of $196.4 million for 1987.
   McCaw said cellular subscribers in its markets and markets in
which it has the right to buy a controlling interest rose by 65
percent in 1988 to 250,000, from 156,000 the year before.
   McCaw offers cellular telephone service under the ``Cellular
One'' name in its markets. They include Miami, West Palm Beach,
Orlando, Tampa and Jacksonville, Fla.; Memphis, Nashville, Johnson
City, and Chattanooga, Tenn.; Louisville, Ky.; Birmingham, Ala.;
Pittsburgh; Minneapolis; Kansas City, Mo.; Tulsa and Oklahoma City,
Okla.; Wichita, Kan.; Austin and San Antonio, Texas; Denver; Salt
Lake City; Sacramento, Fresno and Oxnard, Calif.; Portland, Ore.;
and Seattle and Tacoma.
   It also offers paging services in several markets in Arkansas,
Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Missouri, Minnesota, Nevada, California,
Hawaii, Alaska, Oregon and Washington.
</TEXT>
