<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-10 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade following downward
revisions in the Agriculture Department's projections for world crop
production.
   In a report released Thursday afternoon, the USDA lowered its
estimate for 1988-89 Argentine soybean production to 9 million
metric tons from 11 million metric tons and reduced its estimate for
Argentine corn production to 6 million metric tons from 8 million.
   The government also lowered its 1988-89 Soviet grain production
forecast by 5 million metric tons to 195 million and dropped its
projection for the Oct. 1 U.S. corn stockpile to 1.66 billion
bushels from 1.74 billion bushels.
   The report was considered mildly supportive for corn and soybean
futures and neutral for the wheat market.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.25{ a bushel; corn was { cent
to 2 cents higher with March at $2.65} a bushel; oats were 2 cents
to 3} cents higher with March at $2.08{ a bushel; soybeans were 2
cents to 5 cents higher with March at $7.49{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange with some feeder cattle contracts down the
permitted daily limit of 1.50 cents a pound in a continuing reaction
to Wednesday's USDA report showing a larger-than-expected U.S.
cattle herd. Pork futures were mostly higher in early trading.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .85 cent lower with the contract for
delivery in April at 74.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.22
cents to 1.50 cents lower with March at 81.42 cents a pound; live
hogs were .05 cent lower to .20 cent higher with April at 41.90
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .28 cent to .38 cent higher
with March at 37.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
