<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     02-10 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices continued their slide in early
trading today in reaction to a government report that wholesale
prices shot up last month.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond, issued on Thursday,
yielded 9.04 percent. The previous benchmark bond fell } point, or
$7.50 per $1,000 face amount, while its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from its price, rose to 9.16 percent from 8.89
percent late Thursday.
   Bonds were hurt by inflation fears that the Labor Department
raised with its report that wholesale prices skyrocketed at an
annual rate of 12.7 percent, the most in more than three years.
   The key bond had already plunged 1| points on Thursday, the
biggest one-day drop since November, in response to a slumping
dollar and a weak reception for the government's bond auction.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell 5-32 to [ point, intermediate maturities fell 11-32
point and long-term issues were down } point, according to Telerate
Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 4.39 to 1,127.23.
   In corporate trading, industrials were down. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.41
to 298.79.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.81 percent as the
discount rose 4 basis points to 8.51 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 9.01 percent as the discount rose 10 basis points to
8.52. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.17 percent as the discount
rose 9 basis points to 8.50 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 9 3-16 percent, up from 9[ percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
