<FIRST>u f PM-Markets-Inflation 2ndLd-Writethru   02-10 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Inflation, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds Fall While Dollar Rises on Inflation Data</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECT day of week in 11h graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in inflation at the wholesale level
unleashed a storm of selling in stock and Treasury bond trading
today but gave the dollar a boost on currency markets.
   Disappointment over President Bush's budget proposals was cited
as another factor in today's losses.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average skidded 15.54 to
2,307.50 by noon EST. Declining stocks outnumbered gainers by nearly
3 to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Sellers took over after the Labor Department reported wholesale
prices skyrocketed at an annual rate of 12.7 percent in January, the
biggest monthly surge in more than three years.
   The government said the steepest increase in food prices in a
year combined with the largest rise in energy prices in two years to
push up the Producer Price Index 1.0 percent last month. It was the
biggest increase since an identical surge in October 1985.
   ``The number was much larger than anyone expected,'' said
Elizabeth G. Reiners, a vice president for money market research at
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Traders were concerned that the Federal Reserve, seeing the surge
in producer prices, would drive interest rates higher to try to
corral inflation.
   In the credit markets, today's inflation report deepened
Thursay's losses, which followed a disappointing Treasury bond
auction.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond sank nearly ~ point, or about $8.75
per each $1,000 in face value, after having fallen 1| points on
Wednesday. The bond's yield soared to 9.07 percent from 8.89 percent
late Wednesday.
   But the inflation report was bullish for the dollar, which tends
to rise on speculation that the Fed will tighten credit. Higher U.S.
interest rates make the dollar more attractive to foreign buyers.
   In New York, the dollar rose after the report was released. At
midday, the U.S. currency was trading at about 1.8605 West German
marks, up from 1.8475 late Thursday, and at 128.45 Japanese yen, up
from 127.93 late Thursday.
   On Wall Street, some investors were disappointed by Bush's budget
message Thursday night, saying it didn't live up to hopes that it
would contain forceful new ideas about how to straighten out the
government's budget.
   There also was concern about Bush's plans on foreign markets. The
dollar declined in early trading overseas and prices fell sharply on
London's stock exchange.
</TEXT>
