<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-AutoIndustry Bjt   02-10 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Auto Industry, Bjt,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Automakers Moving From Exports To Overseas Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a year of booming domestic sales and further
declines in exports, Japanese automakers are introducing a fistful
of new models and boosting overseas production to try to capture
more of the global car market.
   Toyota, Nissan, Honda, Mitsubishi and Mazda all saw increased
sales in Japan last year but reported sluggish exports, largely due
to the continued high value of the yen.
   Exports, which fell 3.2 percent in 1988, are expected to continue
dwindling this year, but not just because of the strong yen, which
makes Japanese products more expensive overseas.
   ``While shipments to Europe continue to be firm, exports to the
United States will encounter a more highly competitive environment
due to a gradual downturn in the American economy,'' Nissan
President Yutaka Kume said in January.
   Japanese companies produce about 29 percent of the world's autos,
according to statistics compiled by the Motor Vehicle Manufacturing
Association of America and Japan Automobile Manfacturing Association.
   Half of the 12.7 million cars, trucks and buses made in Japan in
1988 were exported. In 1987, the last year for which comparative
figures are available, 12.2 million motor vehicles were made in
Japan, well ahead of 10.9 million produced in the United States.
   Exchange rates and continuing restrictions on exports to the
United States have led Japanese automakers to make the 1980s the
decade of ``transplanting,'' or producing autos in the markets where
they will be sold.
   The voluntary export quotas were imposed beginning in fiscal 1981
to give U.S. automakers breathing room to recover from growing
Japanese competition. But the Japanese have responded by relocating
production overseas _ they already have established eight factories
in North America _ and have fallen short of their 2.3 million
vehicle annual quota in each of the last two years.
   Expansion planned for this year in North America would bring
transplant output to about 1 million cars annually, with expected
growth to 2 million within two years.
   ``Transplants are crucial to lessening trade friction, and they
are also an intelligent alternative to exports, which have become
increasingly problematic due to yen appreciation,'' said Koji Endo,
a Nomura Securities analyst, in a February report on the auto
industry.
   Automakers also have a strong base in the ever-hungry domestic
market, which grew a phenomenal 10 percent in 1988 and it continues
to be fueled by vigorous consumption, increasing personal income and
leisure time, more new models and high turnover of private cars.
   Toyota, which is aiming for 10 percent of the world market, this
year is opening production in the Philippines and a joint venture
with Volkswagen in West Germany. Overseas production is expected to
surge 82 percent in 1989 and Toyota's joint venture with General
Motors Corp., New United Motor Manufacturing in California, foresees
80 percent growth this year.
   This fall Toyota will market its new Lexus in an attmept to
further penetrate the U.S. market for luxury cars in the $20,000
$40,000 range.
   Nissan has the same strategy with two new cars under the Infiniti
label, which will be marketed this year to challenge Mercedes, BMW
and Jaguar.
   ``We have an image in the United States as a cheap truck maker,
so we're introducing the entirely new Infiniti sales network to shed
that image,'' Nissan's Kume said in an interview.
   Last year, Nissan saw overall exports tumble 11.2 percent,
including a 36.5 percent plunge in the U.S. export market, Japan's
biggest.
   But Nissan is banking on a slew of new models to boost exports
and increase transplant production. The four-door Maxima and
two-door Silvia sports car have debuted in recent months, and the
Infiniti models will join them in the United States.
   Nissan will expand overseas production 15.1 percent this year and
the automaker will expand its Smyrna, Tenn. plant by 1990 to build
two new models for the U.S. market.
   Honda, the top-selling Japanese car in the United States, started
Japan's luxury-car assault with its Acura Legend in 1986. Last year
it began importing to Japan cars it produced in Ohio, and plans to
increase such imports tenfold to 50,000 annually by 1991.
   Honda's production overseas this year will be little changed,
although it will inaugurate production of the five-door Concerto
developed jointly with the Austin Rover Group in Britain.
   Mazda Motor plans to keep production at 1.22 million cars,
lowering exports but raising production at its U.S. plant in
Michigan by more than 50 percent. Mazda does not reveal its global
production figures.
   President Norimasa Furuta told reporters in January that the
automaker would continue developing oversears projects and examine
new ventures with its long-time business partner, Ford Motor Co.
   Mazda produces Ford-badged cars in Japan for sale here and export
elsewhere in Asia. It also is introducing a lightweight, two-seat
sports car this year in Japan and the United States.
   Mitsubishi Motors also expects lower exports, but predicts a 47.5
jump in overseas production this year, including its joint
Diamond-Star Motors venture with Chrysler Corp.
   Fuji Heavy Industries and Isuzu Motors' joint venture,
Subaru-Isuzu Automotive, goes on-line in Indiana this September.
</TEXT>
