<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Fed-Banks     02-10 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fed-Banks,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Group Will Seek To Block Fed's Plan Broadening Bank Powers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities Industry Association said Friday
it would file suit to block the Federal Reserve Board from
broadening the power of commercial banks to deal in securities.
   The association, representing nearly 600 stock brokerages and
investment banks in the United States and Canada, intends to file
suit later this month to overturn the Fed's decision enabling bank
holding companies to underwrite corporate debt and equity on a
limited basis, according to a statement by SIA President Edward I.
O'Brien and the group's chairman, Hardwick Simons.
   The suit will be filed in the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington, D.C.
   In a ruling last month, Fed governors voted to allow banks to
underwrite corporate debt through affiliates but severely limited
the amount of underwriting the subsidiaries may handle.
   The ruling was significant because it continued the evolution in
the banking industry's financial powers.
   The distinctions between the securities business and commercial
banking spelled out in the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act have
blurred over time as each of the two industries have been granted
permission to expand their services. The Fed increasingly has taken
the lead in giving banks broader powers, as Congress generally has
not done so.
   The SIA suit will attempt to persuade the court that the Fed's
action was ``a dangerous piecemeal undermining of the safety
barriers'' of the nearly 55-year old Glass-Steagall, the statement.
   ``We believe the nation's law should be amended, if necessary, by
Congress, not by regulatory and administrative organizations, such
as the Federal Reserve,'' the statement read.
   ``Legal issues aside, it is absurd to let banks risk their
capital in the volatile securities market at the very time they are
still struggling with the developing-nations' debt problems, and the
economy-threatening problems of the thrift industry,'' they stated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0270 </DOCNO>
