<FIRST>r f AM-CableMerger     02-10 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Merger,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable TV Companies Announce Revised Merger Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cable companies United Artists Communications
Inc. and United Cable Television Corp. have agreed on new terms for
their often-delayed, billion-dollar merger, sweetening the amount of
cash available to United Cable shareholders.
   Analysts and company officials estimated the deal, which would
create the nation's third-largest cable company, would be worth $1.6
billion to $1.7 billion. United Cable also has an estimated $600
million in debt.
   The new company, to be called United Artists Entertainment Co.,
would have about 2.4 million basic subscribers, placing it behind
only Tele-Communications Inc. and American Television and
Communications Inc., a Time Inc. unit.
   The revised terms disclosed late Thursday are subject to approval
by the companies' boards and approval of the board of
Tele-Communications Inc., which owns stakes in both and would have
52 percent to 55 percent of the new company.
   The revised plan boosts by $3.50 a share to $38.50 the amount of
cash that will be available for about half of United Cable's common
stock.
   United Cable has about 44 million shares of fully-diluted common
stock, and about 41 percent is held by either United Cable or
Tele-Communications.
   The revised plan would give a combination of stock and rights to
sell the stock under certain condition conditions in exchange for
each of the remaining shares of United Cable stock, the same terms
as were proposed previously.
   United Artists Communications stock would be swapped on a
one-for-one basis for stock in the new company, the same as in the
earlier plan.
   In midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, United Cable
was up 12{ cents a share at $37. United Artists Communications was
unchanged at $30.75 a share in national over-the-counter trading.
   The companies first announced plans to merge in a stock
transaction Oct. 18, 1987, but the deal was called off two days
later in the wake of the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   A new merger agreement was announced in March 1988 and amended in
September, but the companies disclosed Jan. 31 they would be unable
to meet a Feb. 28 completion deadline because of regulatory delays.
   Analysts had speculated United Cable would seek a higher price
because prices being paid for cable systems have continued
increasing sharply.
   John Tinker, an analyst at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York, said
the extra cash should allow the deal to be completed.
   ``There has been a sweetener and that will make it a lot easier
all around,'' he said. He noted the two companies already are
sharing office space in Denver and said, ``It would be hard for the
deal not to go through.''
   In announcing the latest revision, the companies said the new
deadline for completing the merger is May 31.
   ``This agreement will benefit all parties involved and should aid
us in completing our merger in a timely fashion,'' Stewart Blair,
president and chief executive of United Artists, and Gene Schneider,
chairman and chief executive of United Cable, said in a joint
statement.
   In addition to its cable interests, United Artists operates one
of the nation's largest motion picture theater chains.
</TEXT>
