<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CanolaCrop     02-10 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canola Crop,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada's Canola Catches On In The United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designator, remove bjt designation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE ST. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A seedy member of the turnip family has caught the attention of
Midwestern farmers, who contemplate competing with Canadians in the
growing market for canola and the cooking oil squeezed from its
seeds.
   U.S. citizens already consume Canadian canola seed in such
products as Puritan cooking oil, said Jack Ferris at Michigan State
University's agriculture economics department.
   ``It's low in saturated fats. It's marketable. There seems to be
a growing interest in using canola oil not only in the food industry
but in the fast food industry,'' Ferris said Thursday.
   ``Our only problem is quality. U.S.-grown canola was not meeting
the standards established in Canada,'' he said.
   Researchers believe a cool climate is the key, and they've turned
to farmers in Michigan's chilly Upper Peninsula for the answer.
   Michigan State University Cooperative Extension agent Ralph
Duffek in Houghton said Thursday he is telling his farmers that
canola's seed production is so high _ 1,800 pounds per acre _ that
at 80 cents a pound it outperforms even soybeans. One researcher
estimates that canola can cash in at a $291-per- acre profit,
compared with $200 an acre for soybeans, he said.
   Duffek said there is a ready market for canola oil and for the
crushed seed as a feed supplement for cattle.
   What he can't guarantee, however, is how Canadians will welcome
canola competition from across the border.
   Western Canadians have been growing the mustard-like winter crop
for years, crushing its tiny round seeds into cooking oils and
protein additives for cattle feed.
   ``The only skepticism that I have heard and somewhat share is
since the bulk of the canola is grown and processed in Canada,
unless the trade agreements are worked out, the U.S. producers could
be at a disadvantage,'' Duffek said.
   Archer Daniels Midland Co. Inc. is one of Canada's largest canola
processors. Only one of the company's plants, in Ontario, actually
is crushing the grain now, said Don Wright with the company's grain
marketing department.
   Archer Daniels Midland is devoting more and more of its resources
to canola processing, at the expense of soybeans, as the low-fat
crop catches on, Wright said.
   ``We've had canola for some time. It's used in Canada for
margarines, cooking oils, salad oils and the like. But when I came
here two years ago, ADM had only six or eight suppliers of it,''
Wright said. ``Now I have a source list of 20 to 25 people. I think
it's really coming along.''
   Kentucky and Illinois are the chief producers of canola in the
United States. Kentucky growers planted about 2,000 acres of canola
in 1987, then 8,000 acres as it caught on in 1988, according to a
study by the University of Kentucky.
   Farmers in Indiana, Tennessee, Ohio and Michigan so far have only
dabbled in the crop.
   Canola growers in all of Michigan probably harvested less than
5,000 bushels of seed last year, said Herm Geers, president of the
Michigan Agriculture Commodities Inc. in Lansing.
   ``The tough thing about a new crop is what if you only get 5,000
to 8,000 bushels? Most crushers don't want to switch over from one
day to the next. Frankly, we don't have the production it takes,''
Geers said.
   Yet Geers is pushing for the crop's development in Michigan and
has pledged that his company will continue to clean, store and
broker the crop if agriculture officials will continue to promote it.
   ``The potential is there,'' he said.
   Canola, a member of the rape seed family, typically is planted in
the fall and harvested in early summer, leaving farmers enough time
to put in soybeans the rest of the growing season.
   ``We feel that winter canola offers a real potential for becoming
a crop in Michigan,'' Duffek said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0273 </DOCNO>
