<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Honeywell     02-10 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Honeywell,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Reports $483 Million Loss for Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc., the struggling automation
company, said Friday it lost $483 million in the fourth quarter,
mainly because of one-time charges, and posted a loss of $435
million for the year as a whole.
   The loss was even larger than investors had expected and the
stock was off $2.12{ a share at $64.87{ in afternoon trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Honeywell had warned in December that its net loss for the year
``could'' exceed $400 million.
   James J. Renier, the chairman and chief executive, said the
company had a difficult year and was now concentrating on businesses
where it had a large share of the market.
   ``We are looking forward to a year of significant improvement in
1989,'' he said in a statement.
   Honeywell makes thermostats, gauges and other types of controls
and guidance systems for homes, buildings, industry, aerospace and
the military. It has a minority interest in Bull HN Information
Systems Inc., the computer company.
   In the fourth quarter, Honeywell reported a net loss of $483
million, compared with net income of $86 million, or $1.99 per
share, in the fourth quarter of 1987. Sales in the fourth quarter
were $1.93 billion, down from $1.99 billion in 1987.
   For the full year the net loss of $435 million compared with net
income of $254 million in 1987. Sales were $7.15 billion, up from
$6.69 billion in 1987.
   Total fourth-quarter orders for the company increased, compared
with fourth-quarter 1987.
   In December, Honeywell announced that, after posting a $67.1
million profit for the first nine months of 1988, it could lose more
than $400 million in 1988 and would cut 1,200 of its 79,000
employees. At the same time, the company said that James J. Renier,
who was already chief executive, would take over the chairmanship
from Edson Spencer, who retired.
   The company said its fourth-quarter loss includes:
   _ An income tax provision of $158 million.
   _ A provision for discontinuance of product lines of $126 million.
   _ Other charges of approximately $115 million, including the
costs of work force reductions.
</TEXT>
