<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge As Meal Supplies Weigh on Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower Friday
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid slack demand for what one analyst
called ``fairly comfortable'' supplies of soybean meal.
   Grain futures prices closed higher following downward revisions
in the Agriculture Department's forecasts for world crop production.
   The soybean complex rallied early in the session, then turned
down at midday despite a lack of significant news in the market.
   ``The soybean meal is bringing about this weakness,'' said Mario
Balletto, soybean market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
Inc. in New York.
   ``We're looking at a fairly comfortable supply situation here in
the near term and that's really starting to pressure the market, and
the market's breaking down.''
   In a report released Thursday afternoon, the USDA lowered several
of its estimates for global grain production including downward
revisions in its projections for Argentine corn and soybean
production and Soviet grain production.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 6} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.28{ a bushel; corn was { cent
to 1{ cents higher with March at $2.66 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
2\ cents higher with March at $2.07 a bushel; soybeans were 5\ cents
to 11{ cents lower with March at $7.34{ a bushel.
