<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Machinists     02-10 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Machinists,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Believe Eastern Lining Up Strike Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Machinists union said Friday that a
tight-lipped Eastern Airlines is making arrangements through other
aviation companies to hire mechanics, baggage handlers and other
workers in case of a strike.
   An International Association of Machinists leader in Atlanta
charged Fridy that Eastern was recruiting mechanics through Butler
Aviation at an office building near Hartsfield International
Airport. Frank Ortis, vice president of local 702 in Miami, said
he's received several reports of recruiting workers, apparently for
the strike, but did not have proof. And Machinist leaders said they
suspected similar efforts in other cities.
   The Machinists had an informational picket at the site in Atlanta
and were telling people who arrived for job interviews that the jobs
would be for strikebreakers at Eastern in case the unions walk.
   A classified ad pitching the interviews in Atlanta was headlined
``Aviation Careers'' and gave directions to the job interview site,
but no phone number. It identified the employer only as a ``large
national company.''
   Michael Flynn, head of the IAM local in Atlanta, said Eastern
Airlines people were inside the building where the interviews were
taking place and armed guards were outside.
   He said he had heard of recruiting in several other cities, but
had few specifics.
   ``They won't have much luck with mechanics,'' Flynn predicted.
``All the airlines are hiring mechanics now.''
   Butler officials declined to talk about the Machinists' claims.
   ``We don't have any comment on that,'' said Bill Wynperle, vice
president of marketing for Butler International Inc., of Montvale,
N.J.
   Ortis said Machinists are looking into several newspaper
advertisements in the Miami area offering aviation-related jobs.
   ``We have reason to believe they are hiring strike-breakers,''
Ortis said. ``We expect companies to go ahead and start doing this.
But looking at the salary they advertised, I cannot believe anybody
would want to work for that. That's why we're on strike.''
   Eastern continued to decline comment on strike-related activities
or union charges.
   ``We have declined comment on any specifics of our contingency
plan,'' said Eastern spokeswoman Virginia Sanchez.
   But asked if there was a contingency plan, she replied: ``There
is.''
   ``Our goal is to operate, obviously,'' she said. ``However, our
objective in the short-term is always to reach a settlement because
we feel a strike will not benefit either party.''
   The three unions met Thursday to discuss their options if a
court-imposed March 3 deadline passes without a settlement in the
Machinists' 16-month contract dispute with the airline.
   ALPA and Machinists union members met with officials of the
Transport Workers Union, which represents Eastern's 7,000 flight
attendants. The TWU executive board met Thursday to discuss options,
but did not report on the meeting's outcome.
   Eastern's 3,400 pilots Thursday were being sent a taped message
from local union leader Capt. Jack Bavis urging them to consider
supporting the Machinists if they walk off the job.
   Eastern announced record net losses of $335.4 million for 1988,
nearly double the $181.7 million loss the year before. Revenues
dropped to $3.8 billion in 1988, compared to $4.4 billion in 1987.
   The Miami-based carrier, owned by Texas Air Corp., is seeking
$150 million in union wage concessions. It also claims to be losing
$1 million a day.
   The 8,500 Machinists comprise some 30 percent of Eastern's work
force. Mechanics make up about half of the union, which includes
baggage handlers, ramp agents and other ground-services workers.
   A National Mediation Board negotiator is continuing efforts to
gain an agreement between the two sides, although no recent progress
has been reported and both sides have shown signs of gearing up for
a strike.
   Union officials are predicted overwhelming approval of a strike
when the vote is concluded Feb. 14 by locals in Atlanta. The outcome
of that strike vote is expected late next week with a strike
deadline of March 3.
</TEXT>
