<DOCNO> AP890210-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BarnyardCommandos     02-10 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barnyard Commandos,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militant Critters Getting Attention From Hoax Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next week's demonstration by ``farmers'' against
Rebel Killer Swine won't exactly be a plea for support to stop
renegade barnyard pigs.
   It's just a staged protest to tout some new vinyl action toys and
their equally militaristic sheep foes debuting at this year's Toy
Fair.
   Bib overall-clad protesters carrying placards proclaiming ``Make
Bacon Not War!'' and ``Lamb Chops Not Karate Chops!'' will greet
visitors to the 86th annual American International Toy Fair, which
starts Monday.
   A group calling itself H.I.C.K.S. _ Horticulturists Incensed by
Commercialized Killer Swine _ issued a manifesto Friday urging the
publicto ``March shoulder-to-shoulder with pork producers and wool
farmers and demonstrate your solidarity against animal
exploitation!''
   The H.I.C.K.S. actually are actors hired to pose as Midwestern
farmers outraged by the Barnyard Commandos menagerie of action
figures being introduced at the fair.
   Playmate Toys Inc., creators of Barnyard Commandos, decided to
take this offbeat publicity approach to poke fun at itself and the
toy exhibition, which over the years has been known to cultivate a
healthy crop of advertising hyperbole.
   ``No one will mistake this for a real protest,'' said Playmates
spokesman Christopher A. Perez. ``It's so tongue-in-cheek and it's
all done in the spirit of fun.''
   Playmates, of La Mirada, Calif., claims Barnyard Commandos were
the demented result of a military experiment gone awry.
   In the company's Orwellian scenario, a Platoon of Rebel Killer
Swine are battling against a Rebel Army of Militant Sheep for
control of a farm.
   The opposing forces communicate with their comrades-in-arms using
secret languages: the P.O.R.K.S. speak Pork Latin and the R.A.M.S.
use Baa Code.
   The militant critters are a spoof of the army figures and war
toys now popular among children, said Perez.
   In recent years, some toy manufacturers have prided themselves on
presenting state-of-the art items, including gear that imitates the
latest in Pentagon weaponry and thinking.
   Perez said Playmates wants to show it doesn't take itself too
seriously and has retained a sense of humor despite its serious
success last year with Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles. These
creatures, based on a comic book, are described as the result of the
mutation of normal pet turtles that fell into a sewer. The turtles
turned out to be 1988's No.1 new toy.
   The only people that could take offense at Playmates' hoax are
real farmers. The fake ones hired by Playmates, led by Farmer
Fallow, are portrayed as rather unsophisticated yokels.
   Their dummy announcement, presented to look like it was printed
on an old-fashioned typewriter, concludes with a recommendation that
wouldn't exactly appeal to animal rights advocates.
   It says, ``Buy pork and lamb from your neighborhood butcher.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
