<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-10 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Jumps; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar jumped higher against foreign
currencies Friday after reports of a big increase in wholesale
prices rekindled speculation of that U.S. interest rates would rise.
   The steep climb came just one day after the currency tumbled,
returned the dollar to where it was at midweek.
   The Labor Department reported wholesale prices rose in January at
a 12.7 percent annual rate, the steepest increase in more than three
months.
   Currency dealers speculated the Federal Reserve would combat
inflation by pushing up short-term interest rates, which would
attract global investors to put their money in dollars.
   Gold prices fell, even though investors usually flock to gold as
a haven against inflation. Dealers said selling swept the market
after gold failed to respond favorably to the wholesale price
figures.
   The dollar might have risen more but traders were uncertain how
aggressive Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan would be in
raising interest rates to cool the economy, said Garrett Glass, a
vice president at First National Bank of Chicago.
   On Thursday, the dollar's fall was blamed largely on the market's
nervous anticipation of President Bush's evening budget message to
Congress. The message contained no unpleasant surprises, market
watchers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 127.65 yen, down from Thursday's close of
129.39 yen. Later in London, the dollar was quoted at 128.15 yen. In
New York, the dollar rose to 128.68 yen from 127.93 late Thursday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7547 from $1.7540 on
Thursday. In New York, sterling fell to $1.7467 from $1.7645.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8695 West German marks, up from
1.8475; 1.5885 Swiss francs, up from 1.5675; 1.1860 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1836; 6.3588 French francs, up from 6.2875; and
1,363.5 Italian lire, up from 1,347.5.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thurday's
rates were: 1.8595 West German marks, up from 1.8585; 1.5778 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5802; 6.3200 French francs, down from 6.3225;
2.0960 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0990; 1,353.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,355.50; and 1.1857 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1832.
   In Hong Kong, where trading endd before the U.S. inflation
figures were released, gold fell 43 cents to close at a bid of
$395.15 a troy ounce.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid of $391 a troy ounce, down
from $394.25 bid late Thursday. In Zurich, the late bid was $389.50,
down from $394.25 bid late Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $388.80 a troy ounce from Thursday's $394.40.
Republic National Bank of New York said spot gold was bid at $387 an
ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $393.25.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid of $5.85 a troy ounce, down
from Thursday's late bid of $5.90. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.812 an ounce from $5.891.
</TEXT>
