<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-10 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Slide In Wholesale Price Reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An unexpected leap in wholesale prices triggered a plunge in gold
and silver futures prices Friday as traders anticipated further
credit tightening by the Federal Reserve Board in an effort to
control inflation.
   On other markets, coffee, energy and soybean futures prices fell
sharply; grain futures were higher and livestock and meat futures
were mixed.
   Gold futures prices settled $6.10 to $6.60 lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in April at
$391.70 a troy ounce; silver was 7.7 cents to 8 cents lower with
March at $5.835 a troy ounce.
   The Labor Department's report of a 1 percent rise in the Producer
Price Index last month, the sharpest monthly increase in nearly
eight years, shocked economists and sent financial markets into
turmoil.
   Gold futures prices initially rose as startled investors bought
into a market traditionally viewed as a safe haven in times of
rising prices.
   But the gold bulls were rapidly overtaken by sellers who feared
the Federal Reserve would move quickly to drive up interest rates
and clamp down on inflation.
   ``The way the (gold) market reacted was not a good reaction,''
said Stephen Platt, a precious-metals analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``We were able to rally a buck and that
was it.''
   Earlier this week, the gold market had appeared to be struggling
back from the depressed levels it slipped into in late January. But
the market's reaction to the wholesale price report held out little
hope for recovery in the near future.
   ``I don't think the market really believes that inflation's going
to build into a new problem,'' said Craig Sloane, an analyst with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``This really struck at the heart of gold bulls,'' said Platt.
   Coffee futures prices dropped sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar
&amp; Cocoa Exchange in technically inspired trading, settling 1.10
cents to 6.94 cents lower with March at $1.33 a pound.
   Weakening chart signals helped push crude oil for March delivery
as low as $17.05 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange but a
late rally partially erased the losses.
   Crude oil settled 17 cents to 35 cents lower with March at $17.11
a barrel; heating oil was .61 cent to 1.25 cents lower with March at
47.36 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to .79 cent
lower with March at 47.57 cents a gallon.
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid slack demand for what one analyst called ``fairly comfortable''
supplies of soybean meal.
   Wheat futures gained on rumors that the Agriculture Department
was preparing to target China for sales of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 6\ cents higher with March at $4.28} a
bushel; corn was } cent to 1 cent higher with March at $2.66 a
bushel; oats were } cent to 1{ cents higher with March at $2.06} a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 11 cents lower with March at $7.35
a bushel.
   Cattle futures steadied and finished mixed after an opening
plunge linked to Wednesday's USDA report showing a
larger-than-expected U.S. cattle herd.
   Pork futures also finished mixed in a day of choppy trading.
   Live cattle were .50 cent lower to .35 cent higher with April at
75.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .75 cent to 1.15 cents lower
with March at 82.15 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to .23
cent higher with February at 41.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .45 cent lower to .45 cent higher with February at 38
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
