<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Chubb-DroughtSuit     02-10 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chubb-Drought Suit,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Payment Document Filed in Chubb Drought Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first payments are to be mailed out by
mid-March to about 7,400 farmers as the result of their settlement
with a New Jersey insurer in a lawsuit over crop insurance for the
summer drought, lawyers said Friday.
   Chubb Corp., an insurer based in Warren, N.J., agreed in November
to the $43.1 million settlement with the farmers, who sued Chubb on
grounds it had broken promises to issue crop insurance as protection
against possible drought damage. The settlement covers farmers in
Illinois, Iowa, Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, Tennessee, Minnesota,
Michigan, Missouri and Wisconsin.
   Cincinnati lawyer Lawrence Kane Jr., court-appointed
administrator for the settlement, filed a proposed payment schedule
Friday with the U.S. District Court in Cincinnati. It proposes
payments ranging from $250 to about $300,000.
   The proposed payments are subject to review by lawyers for the
farmers and Chubb, and then final approval by U.S. District Judge
Carl Rubin of Cincinnati, who is presiding over the case.
   The first checks should go out in mid-March covering half the
payments, with the balance to be mailed by late April, Kane said.
Objections can delay distribution of the payments, he said.
   ``We've resolved somewhere between 400 and 500 objections so
far,'' Kane said.
   Stanley Chesley, a Cincinnati lawyer for the farmers, said he
expects the payment schedule to receive all needed approvals.
   ``We're very satisfied. We think it'll reflect an accurate
accounting,'' Chesley said.
   Lawyers for Chubb and the farmers have united to jointly sue Good
Weather International Corp., a company which allegedly sold about
$350 million worth of Chubb drought insurance policies that Chubb
refused to honor.
   The farmers are demanding unspecified damages from Good Weather,
saying it violated its contract with Chubb. Chubb is suing Good
Weather for $68 million, saying the policies should not have been
sold.
   The case was to have gone to trial this week, but has been
postponed. Chesley said the farmers and Chubb plan to split any
settlement award. Chubb would get a third of whatever it wins from
Good Weather, and the farmers would get two-thirds, Chesley said.
Rubin is to hear the trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Coastal     02-10 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Coastal,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Company Reports Fourth-Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. said Thursday its fourth-quarter
1988 earnings rose 103 percent to $71.1 million compared with a year
earlier in part because of improvements in its refining and
marketing division.
   Coastal said profits amounted to $1.22 a share on revenue of $2.1
billion. That compares with $35 million, or 68 cents a share, on
revenue of $2 billion for the same 1987 quarter.
   Coastal, a diversified energy company, last month offered to buy
Houston-based Texas Eastern Co. for $2.6 billion. Texas Eastern's
board of directors has rejected the $42-a-share bid as inadequate.
   For all of 1988, Coastal reported earnings of $157 million, or
$2.70 a share, on revenue of $8.24 billion, a 39 percent increase
from 1987 earnings of $113 million, or $2.10 a share, on revenue of
$7.43 billion.
   Profits from the company's refining and marketing segment for the
quarter increased to $124 million from a loss of $36.3 million in
1987. For the year, the segment's earnings grew to $169 million from
$43 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
