<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 2317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoShow-GM     02-10 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Show-GM,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Contracts With Disney for Lumina Advertising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan-Auto Industry, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Mouse may be at the wheel the first time
most of America sees Chevrolet's Lumina cars for 1990.
   Chevrolet and Walt Disney World Co. have entered an advertising
pact to help launch the new General Motors Corp. car line and the
Disney-MGM Studios Theme park near Orlando, Fla., Chevrolet
officials said Friday.
   Bob Burger, general manager of GM's Chevrolet Division, said the
Lumina line's advertising will focus on portraying the cars as
family oriented.
   ``The Disney name is instantly recognized by families,'' he said.
``We believe this is a win-win partnership.'
   The four-door Lumina sedan will go on sale in March, with the new
Disney-MGM park set to open in April. A two-door coupe and minivan
will be available later in the year, said Mike Erdman, Chevrolet's
general marketing manager.
   Lumina is more than 2 inches wider than Celebrity, the midsize
Chevy it replaces. Prices won't be announced for at least 30 days,
Erdman said.
   The Disney-Chevrolet campaign will be used only on the Lumina
cars, while Chevrolet's award-winning ``Heartbeat of America''
advertising theme will continue, Erdman said. Lumina advertisements
will use Disney characters and the ``Heartbeat'' theme.
   Erdman declined to say how much money was involved in the
Disney-Chevrolet collaboration. He said the agreement calls for
Chevrolet ads with Disney characters and Disney ads with Lumina
cars. The agreement lasts into the fall.
   The television ads will debut March 29 during the motion picture
Academy Awards show. The joint campaign also includes radio and
print media.
   After the deal was announced in front of the Lumina display at
the Chicago Auto Show, Burger _ looking a little embarrassed _ posed
with Mickey Mouse and Goofy.
   Also Friday, GM Chairman Roger Smith said the corporation's North
American operations earned a large profit during 1988, declining to
say how much money was involved. GM earlier this week declared its
first split of common stock since 1955 and increased dividends on
most of its stock issues. The stock market responded with a big gain
Tuesday.
   Officials said a year ago that GM earned a marginal profit in
North America.
   GM reports its year-end earnings Tuesday. Smith has said
repeatedly the earnings would be a company record. In recent years,
overseas earnings, especially in Europe, have bolstered GM's sagging
North American performance.
   Smith also said the company planned to spend about $1 billion on
tools, machinery and equipment for its Saturn Corp. plant in Spring
Hill, Tenn. He said the Saturn project remained on schedule and
under budget for a launch in mid-1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
