<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell-FarleyVisit     02-10 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell-Farley Visit,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farley Visits Company He Intends To Take Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc.'s chairman visited West
Point-Pepperell Inc. Thursday to inspect two of the company's
plants, apparently among the first of several potential buyers to
tour the textile giant's facilities.
   William Farley toured three facilities in Pepperell's consumer
apparel division: the Lanier-Carter Mill and West Point Pepperell
Mill Store in Huguley, Ala., and the Fairfax Mill in Valley, Ala.
   Pepperell spokeswoman Toni Cauble said in a statement that
Farley's visit was ``intended to permit Farley to see as much of our
operations as the other bidders will be permitted to see.''
   Ms. Cauble said Farley was in town as a bidder only and did not
meet with Pepperell Chairman Joseph Lanier Jr.
   Other prospective buyers of the West Point-based textile
manufacturer were to tour the company's facilities this week.
Representatives from two textile firms _ Dominion of Montreal and
Spartanburg, S.C.-based Milliken and Co. _ were expected to visit
soon.
   The visits were arranged to accommodate a Feb. 15 deadline to
receive bids for the textile giant. Pepperell set the deadline
Wednesday after its directors announced last week that the company
was for sale.
   Chicago-based Farley had already offered to buy Pepperell for
$1.54 billion, or $52 a share.
   Before Farley's visit, a West Point store owner had displayed a
sign suggesting that residents burn their underwear. Farley owns
Fruit of the Loom underwear, among other products.
   Workers in various Pepperell plants were busy preparing for
Farley's visit Wednesday. Some worked overtime Wednesday night
scraping ``Stop Farley'' stickers off the machinery in the plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890210-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-89 0948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Wine-Swap     02-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wine-Swap,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous French, American Wine Companies Form Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another major European investment in
California wine, the interests of the fabled Chateau
Lafite-Rothschild of Bordeaux, France, have formed an alliance with
the state's superpremium Chalone Vineyard.
   Chateau Lafite's Baron Eric de Rothschild and Board Chairman Dick
Graff of Chalone made the announcement Thursday at a news
conference. Chalone, whose best wines sell for $20 a bottle and up,
is the only publicly owned operating winery in the country.
   The executives said the agreement, subject to the approval of
shareholders, calls for an approximately 6 percent ownership swap
between the companies, with a contemplated rise to 20 percent for a
$15 million investment by each party.
   Rothschild said the swap included none of the property or vines
of Chateau Lafite itself, only the 200-year-old winery's business
ownerships, specifically its domaines _ Chateau Rieussec, Chateau
Dehart-Milon, and Chateau La Cardonne _ plus the 50 percent-owned
Vina Los Vascos of Chile.
   All the French wineries are in the famous red wine district of
Medoc.
   ``Great wines are made from the proper soil, good weather and
talented people,'' said Rothschild. ``We found Chalone the only
American wine company that shares our philosophy.''
   Chalone president Philip Woodward said the companies planned
extensive exchanges of personnel, marketing talent, winemaking
information and details of grape growing. They also will make mutual
investments in the development of winery and vineyard properties.
Chalone now exports to 12 countries.
   Rothschild is the second of his family to invest in California
wine, though not in the same way. His late cousin, Baron Philippe de
Rothschild of Mouton-Rothschild, made the move after a California
wine trounced the best of French wines in a blind tasting in Paris
in 1976.
   In the late 1970s, Philippe, who died last year, entered into a
joint venture with Napa Valley winemaker Robert Mondavi to produce
Opus One, the proprietary name for a cabernet sauvignon blend whose
vintages enter the market roughly at $50 a bottle.
   ``There will not be an Opus Two,'' said Graff, emphasizing that
Chalone plans no viticultural or blending combinations with the
French.
   The Lafite domaines swap is regarded as an important boost to the
prestige of California wine. The deal also gives the French wineries
an important new opening into the booming premium American wine
market,
   Chalone, the oldest winery in Monterey County, first planted
vines in 1919 and today owns and operates Acacia Winery of Napa
Valley's prized Carneros; Carmenet Vineyard of Sonoma, and 50
percent of Edna Valley Vineyard of San Luis Obispo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
